1. d4
{ Typically, my chapter on Repertoire Clashes is lengthy and detailed, covering 10+ sources I had consulted. However, this time, things will be a bit different mostly for two reasons: the Old Benoni is not covered much by the White authors, and I wanted to keep things theoretically light! Some of the resources I  consulted include:  IM Christof Sielecki, Keep it Simple 1.d4; FM Daniel Barrisch, The Principled Queen's Gambit; GM Nikola Sedlak, Winning with the Modern London; GM Boris Avrukh, Grandmaster Repertoire, vol.1; GM Oleg Kornev, A Practical White Repertoire 1.d4.  
I have also used multiple other sources, but basically, they are not particularly useful for most students of this course. That's for one simple reason: in reality, everyone will play c2-c4 against you, while all authors, who have the time to prepare, will keep the pawn on c2 and go Bb5+!  There is a lot to discuss in those positions, and they are very idea-based. White does have a few promising lines, and I focused on them in great detail in the theoretical chapters. But I don't think most authors are looking for some great innovations in this variation, so although consulting the sources is always useful, we will just want to focus on the theoretical part and not just the book recommendations. Also, we need to pay attention to the most popular lines as well such as the rare GM-played moves. }
1... c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6
{ Here, you will realize most of your opponents go  4.c4  , but most authors would want to play  4.Nc3  . So, quite a bit of difference between practice and reality already! }
