[Result "*"]

{ Hi and welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of this course on the Old Benoni! In just about a dozen lines, we will learn some of the main ideas of the opening, and you will be on your way to beating White in a fun and unconventional way! }
1. d4 c5
{ If you want to play the Old Benoni @@StartBracket@@not the sharp theoretical Modern setups@@EndBracket@@, then the first step is remembering to make this move, pawn to c5, right now. Why is it so important to do it now instead of waiting with  1...Nf6  first? Because for our main plan to work, we need  the h4-d8 diagonal to be open as you are about to discover!    1...Nf6  is a good move, of course, but it makes our setup impossible to achieve. This is because after  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e5  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  Be7  , you can no longer trade the bishop off  with ...Bg5, as the knight is blocking it from coming there! }
2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2... e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. c4
{ This is a very common move, especially among club players. White always places the pawn on c4, so why not here? Most players nearly pre-move 2.c4 after going 1.d4! However, I believe this setup isn't the best because this move blocks the light-squared bishop and prevents White from ever giving an annoying check on b5. Also, now the c4-square is no longer available for the white knight.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. e4
{ Both parties have placed three pawns in the center, creating a very closed position with pawn chains. Now what?   White has more space. Therefore, Black should want to trade minor pieces.  Both sides have a good and a bad bishop. For Black, the f8-bishop is the bad one because it is restricted by our own pawns. For White, on the other hand, the bad bishop is on f1. Hence, Black should specifically focus on trading that bishop.  It is also possible to discuss the pawn breaks, such as ...f7-f5, ...b7-b5, or b2-b4/f2-f4 from White's perspective, but our priority will be trading that bad bishop. }
4... Be7
{ Black is looking to play ...Bg5! on the next turn and get rid of the bishop! This is exactly why we started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  and not  1...Nf6  − the goal was to keep that knight in its original position in order to keep the  maneuver ...Bf8-e7-g5 available! Now, White can either just keep developing, or try to prevent our plan. }
5. Nf3
{ By developing the knight here, White is taking the g5-square under control, making it impossible for us to trade off the bishops as we wanted to. }
5... Bg4
{ This move is very logical. What do we want? We want to exchange the white knight and then go ...Bg5, trading off the bad dark-squared bishop. }
6. Nbd2
{ With this move, White gets ready to recapture on f3 with the knight, which would keep control of the g5-square.  Unfortunately, this is one of the few cases where our plan of trading off the dark-squared bishops does not work. We have to come up with something else! }
6... Nf6
{ Now, we are going for a slow game where the main objective will be preparing for the ...f7-f5 break. Importantly, the white knight is rather misplaced on d2!   6...Bg5?  Of course, it is possible to make this move and feel good about the pinned knight  on f3. However, just because the move is possible, it doesn't mean it's good.  7.Qa4+!  This check turns out very disruptive, as White is getting ready to take  the g5-bishop.    7...Bd7  8.Qb3!  Now  both the b7-pawn and the g5-bishop are under attack.  8...Bxd2+  9.Bxd2±  and we gifted White the bishop pair for nothing. Now White has the bishop pair, more space, and pressure on the queenside. This is a position that you should avoid by all means! }
7. Bd3 Na6
{ The knight is going to c7. I wouldn't want to develop it to d7 because, after h2-h3, our bishop will no longer have that square. }
8. h3
{ Typically, White would want to break the pin. Of course, White doesn't have to play this move, but it makes sense to do so. Now, it would be a mistake to take on f3 because that would gift White the bishop pair and help our opponent unravel the queenside pieces, which are currently rather clumsy.  It would also be wrong to retreat to h5 because White can play g2-g4 and Nf1-g3, and the bishop on g6 would be dead for the rest of the game. This should be obvious to people who have experience in the 1.e4 e5 openings, as it is a very common positional trap in the Italian Game. }
8... Bd7 { We are keeping the bishop! } 9. O-O O-O
{ Now, the question is what should White do next. And what should we do?  We will play ...g7-g6, reroute the knight to g7 via e8 or h5, and play ...f7-f5-f4, starting the typical kingside attack. White, on the other hand, should try to play b2-b4 and get some counterplay going on the queenside. }
10. a3 g6 11. Rb1 b6
{ Black can make this move either in advance or as a response to b2-b4. This way, we will make sure the queenside is sturdy, and focus on our kingside play. }
12. b4 Nh5
{ There are no games in the database that got to this position, so there's little point in memorizing possible continuations. But we will take a look at some model game examples that feature both parties playing on their own flank this way!  Again, the queenside seems rather safe, and we are ready to play ...Ng7, ...f7-f5-f4, ... g6-g5, ...h7-h5, ...g5-g4, and so on. It is important that we don't play ...f7-f5 with the knight on h5, or at least do that very carefully. This is because after exf5, taking back with a piece often runs into a g2-g4 fork while taking with the g-pawn leaves the h5-knight loose and Black often runs into tactics like Nxe5! and Qxh5!, winning a pawn. }
