[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "2nd Move Sidelines − 2.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hi and welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of this course on the Old Benoni! In just about a dozen lines, we will learn some of the main ideas of the opening, and you will be on your way to beating White in a fun and unconventional way! }
1. d4 c5
{ If you want to play the Old Benoni @@StartBracket@@not the sharp theoretical Modern setups@@EndBracket@@, then the first step is remembering to make this move, pawn to c5, right now. Why is it so important to do it now instead of waiting with  1...Nf6  first? Because for our main plan to work, we need  the h4-d8 diagonal to be open as you are about to discover!    1...Nf6  is a good move, of course, but it makes our setup impossible to achieve. This is because after  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e5  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  Be7  , you can no longer trade the bishop off  with ...Bg5, as the knight is blocking it from coming there! }
2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Bf4
{ This is an attempt to get a London setup. But, fortunately, there is a reason knowledgeable people who play the London start with e2-e3, not c2-c3. }
3... Qb6 { Now, the b2-pawn is immediately in danger! } 4. Qb3 Qxb3
{ We go for the queen trade, as that will yield us a favorable structure. } 5.
axb3 cxd4
{ Taking on d4 allows us to develop with tempo on the next move and it emphasizes the weakness of the doubled pawns on the b-file. }
6. cxd4
{ White ends up with weak b-pawns, and we get an outpost on b4, which our knight will greatly enjoy. The semi-open a-file is not an issue since there is nothing White can attack on it. }
6... Nc6
{ Black is immediately getting the initiative by attacking the d4-pawn. } 7. e3
Nb4 { White has to make more clumsy moves. } 8. Kd1 d6
{ Paving the way for the c8-bishop while obstructing the opponent's bishop on f4. }
9. Nc3 Bd7
{ Next, Black will go ...a7-a6 to free up the rook on a8, then ...Rc8, ...e7-e6, and the dark-squared bishop will likely go to e7. Interestingly enough, Black might want to wait a bit with the move ...d6-d5 − there is nothing wrong with that move, but we could use the d5-square for the knights!   However, of course, keeping the pawn on e7 and playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 is perfectly reasonable as well! Or maybe even somehow ...h7-h5 and ...g7-g5, grabbing space on the kingside, if possible. With a wonderful outpost on b4 and White's king so misplaced on d1, Black is clearly better.   White can try aggressive moves like 10.Nb5, but they are easily negated in many ways. For example 10.Nb5 Nbd5! gives Black strong initiative, especially in the event of 11.Rxa7 Rxa7 12.Nxa7 Nxf4. I decided to not make this sequence trainable as it's noo unlikely to happen and very good for us. }
