[Black "2nd Move Sidelines − 2.c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hi and welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of this course on the Old Benoni! In just about a dozen lines, we will learn some of the main ideas of the opening, and you will be on your way to beating White in a fun and unconventional way! }
1. d4 c5
{ If you want to play the Old Benoni @@StartBracket@@not the sharp theoretical Modern setups@@EndBracket@@, then the first step is remembering to make this move, pawn to c5, right now. Why is it so important to do it now instead of waiting with  1...Nf6  first? Because for our main plan to work, we need  the h4-d8 diagonal to be open as you are about to discover!    1...Nf6  is a good move, of course, but it makes our setup impossible to achieve. This is because after  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e5  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  Be7  , you can no longer trade the bishop off  with ...Bg5, as the knight is blocking it from coming there! }
2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. dxc5
{ Possible, but not dangerous at the moment. } 3... e6
{ If we can just get the pawn back, then obviously the position would be very comfortable, especially because White wasted a tempo playing the passive move c2-c3. }
4. b4
{ White should try to hold on to the pawn. Or, at least, that's the principled thing to do. Fortunately, we have a standard way of dismantling that pawn chain.   4.Be3  doesn't lead anywhere due to  4...Qc7!  5.b4  a5  , with similar play as in the main line 4.b4. }
4... a5 5. Bb2 axb4 6. cxb4 b6
{ The pawn chain collapses, which gives an advantageous position since Black will be the one with an extra pawn in the center, while the opponent will have a weakness on a2. }
7. e3 bxc5 8. bxc5 Bxc5
{ Black is clearly better due to the aforementioned reasons. } *

