[Black "2nd Move Sidelines − 2.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hi and welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of this course on the Old Benoni! In just about a dozen lines, we will learn some of the main ideas of the opening, and you will be on your way to beating White in a fun and unconventional way! }
1. d4 c5
{ If you want to play the Old Benoni @@StartBracket@@not the sharp theoretical Modern setups@@EndBracket@@, then the first step is remembering to make this move, pawn to c5, right now. Why is it so important to do it now instead of waiting with  1...Nf6  first? Because for our main plan to work, we need  the h4-d8 diagonal to be open as you are about to discover!    1...Nf6  is a good move, of course, but it makes our setup impossible to achieve. This is because after  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e5  4.Nc3  d6  5.e4  Be7  , you can no longer trade the bishop off  with ...Bg5, as the knight is blocking it from coming there! }
2. dxc5
{ Sometimes, White would simply capture the pawn. It's hanging, right? So why not? This move could be especially popular with the 'conservative' 1.d4 players, who like the setups where c2-c4 is delayed or avoided altogether.   They would be afraid to play  2.d5  , which reaches a complex position, and would consider moves like  2.c3  or  2.e3  to be too modest. So, they would just take. }
2... e6
{ Luckily, winning back the c5-pawn while also getting a great position won't be difficult at all. }
3. Nf3
{ This developing move allows Black to get the pawn right away. Of course, by playing this way, White cannot fight for any advantage. }
3... Bxc5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Both parties are about to make some logical developing moves. White isn't forced to play c2-c4, but I think it makes sense to do so at some point to fight for the center. If White completely foregoes this move, then Black would go ...d7-d5 and eventually ...Nc6 and ...e6-e5. }
5. c4 O-O 6. a3
{ Since the c1-bishop is blocked by the e3-pawn, it makes sense to prepare to play b2-b4, expanding on the queenside, and looking to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. }
6... b6
{ Black could also prevent the space grab with ...a7-a5, but I see no harm in allowing White to do that.  Furthermore, I would prefer to not weaken the b5-square, because then Nc3-b5 would be rather annoying. }
7. b4 Be7 8. Bb2
{ Here, Black has two good choices: either push ...d7-d5, opening up the center, liquidating the pawns, and getting a boring equal position @@StartBracket@@which is not a bad opening outcome by any means!@@EndBracket@@, or keep the tension and delay or forego the ...d7-d5 move altogether. }
8... a5
{ If you want to play for a win, this is the way. We are making White push the b-pawn forward, which would permanently weaken the c5-square.  8...d5  would lead to simplifications and dry equality. }
9. b5 d6
{ We are happy to have a bit less space in exchange for an outpost on c5. } 10.
Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7
{ Next, Black would install the knight on c5, play ...Rc8, and so on. With an outpost on c5, a powerful light-squared bishop, and great control of the e5-square, we seem to be for choice here. Black went on to win the game in Beeke-Thesing, Vlissingen 2012. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Black should not go ...a7-a6 and ...Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this example and the few next ones, we will learn about some of the typical mistakes in the standard Benoni positions. Sure enough, you will be mostly playing the Old Benoni ones, but it seems really beneficial to know these ideas anyway.  In this structure, White has an extra e-pawn, while Black has an extra pawn on the queenside. That's why the main plans are rather intuitive.  White wants to:  play Bf4 and Nd2-c4, putting pressure on the weak d6-pawn; play f2-f4 and e4-e5, getting a pair of powerful pawns in the center; play e4-e5, forcing ...dxe5 and getting a passed d-pawn.  
Black, on the other hand, wants to:  push ... b7-b5 and expand on the queenside @@StartBracket@@that's a dream, which typically never ever comes true@@EndBracket@@; go ...Bg4 and trade off the bishop for the f3-knight; that is done for two reasons: to decrease the spatial disadvantage, and to make sure the white knight cannot come to d2 and c4; go ...Na6-c7 and prepare ...b7-b5. However, we are about to see some of the typical mistakes! }
8. Bd3
{ Let's say White just develops. Of course, it's better to develop the bishop here than to e2, as it protects the e4-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. O-O a6
{ Black wants to prepare ...b7-b5, so it's understandable to see this move on the board, right? However... it turns out to be a very bad one. Why so? Because now Black can never go ...Na6-c7! }
10. a4 Nbd7 11. h3
{ Now, all of Black's queenside pieces are blocked and stuck. Also, ...b7-b5 can no longer be prepared, the light-squared bishop did not get out, and the knight on d7 has no future.  Next, White will just go Bf4 and Nd2-c4 and crush the opponent! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "How Black should develop the queenside"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp3pbp/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this position, White has several moves. A very popular one, as we saw previously, is Bd3. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O
{ Last time we learned why it's bad to play ...a7-a6 and ...Nbd7.  However, how should Black actually arrange the pieces? }
9... Bg4
{ As I had explained last time, White's big ambition is to put pressure on the d6-pawn by playing Bf4 and Nf3-d2.  Not only does this move with the bishop help Black trade down and get rid of the spatial disadvantage, but also, Black prevents the knight maneuver! }
10. h3
{ 10.Be2  − if the bishop was not on the f1-a6 diagonal, Black would have another interesting setup as well.  10...Re8  11.h3  Bxf3  12.Bxf3  Nfd7!?  The other knight is going to a6 and c7 to help prepare ...b7-b5, while this one is going to e5! The bishop on g7, on the other hand, is now also extremely active!  13.Re1  Na6  14.Bf4  Ne5  15.Be2  Nc7  and with ...b7-b5 coming next, Black's position is very comfortable! }
10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 { Now, Black has several good ways of playing. } 11... Nbd7
{ I know I said this move wasn't good when the bishop was on c8. But now Black isn't blocking the bishop, so why not? Instead, there is nothing wrong with  11...Nfd7  and go for the plan we've seen before. However, being armed with various setups and ideas can prove useful in the long run. }
12. Bf4
{ Black can defend the pawn with  12...Qe7  and then  play ...Ne5, or even proceed with the text move. }
12... Ne5 13. Bxe5 dxe5
{ White gets a protected passed pawn, but Black obtains an outpost on d6 for the knight. We are ready to play ...Ne8-d6 and then push ...f7-f5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Getting counterplay with ...b7-b5 fast"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp3p1p/3p1np1/2pP4/4P3/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

7... Bg7
{ In the previous examples, we had seen how White tried developing fast, which allowed the opponent to go ...Bg4 and develop the queenside pieces. So what happens if White takes things slowly, looking to prevent the opponent's ideas? }
8. h3 O-O 9. Bd3
{ Now, White is just hoping to castle and slowly finish development with Bf4, Qd2, Rfe1, and so on.  What should Black do to get counterplay? }
9... b5
{ This is a very cool tactical idea, which works because White hasn't yet castled.   9...a6?  here is more proof that ...a7-a6 is often a terrible move.  10.a4  and Black can no longer use the ...b7-b5 tactic! This means we can't get counterplay on the queenside anymore, and the plan of ...Bg4 is no longer viable either. Black has no counterplay and the position is terrible! }
10. Bxb5
{ 10.Nxb5  Re8!  also allows Black to get the pawn back.  11.Nc3  Nxe4!  12.Nxe4  f5!  and Black wins the piece back, getting a terrific position. }
10... Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxb5
{ Black regains the sacrificed pawn while also preventing White from castling and obtaining a lot of initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Trading off the bad dark-squared bishop"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp3ppp/3p4/2pPp3/2P5/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

4. e4
{ Now we will review the most important and central idea of our course. I bet you guessed in a second which one if you already studied the course at all! }
4... Be7
{ The center, as we can see, is completely locked up.  This means we have a position with pawn chains. The game will be slow and hardly contain any dynamic and tactical aspects for a while. That means both parties can focus on some strategic ideas, as opposed to dynamic ones.  Because of the pawn chains, both players have a bad bishop. For White, the bad bishop is the light-squared one, while for Black it's the dark-squared one. That's because they are both limited by their own pawns!  So, what is Black doing? Black is trying to immediately trade off the bad bishop! If you had by chance seen my course on the French Defense, you would know we are using that exact same idea there, except we are trading the bad French light-squared bishop.  The goal is to play ...Bg5 and swap the bishops off. Black thinks that losing a few tempi moving the bishop twice and moving the queen around is not a problem because the position is very closed. }
5. Nf3
{ This move seems to be preventing Black's main idea. So what should we do?   5.Nc3  Bg5!  and Black is guaranteed to trade off the bad bishop! }
5... Bg4 6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Bg5
{ And the bad bishop is gone anyway! Black's strategic dream is to leave White with a bad light-squared bishop versus a black knight and eventually outplay the opponent in the endgame. That's exactly what is about to happen! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "Why White should avoid playing c2-c4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/8/2pPp3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3"]
[SetUp "1"]

3... d6
{ This is a common pawn structure that we will be seeing all the time in the Old Benoni. Here, you can expect 90-95% of club players to go c2-c4. This is because everyone knows you should place as many pawns in the center as you can, right?  Well, actually, it is much better to not play c2-c4, as it turns out! Why so? Because White wants to:  avoid blocking the light-squared bishop to keep the option of giving a check on b5 open; most importantly, the c4-square will remain available for the white knight! }
4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bb5+
{ It's really beneficial for White to make this move. Why? Remember, Black wants to trade the dark-squared bishops with ...Bg5, right?  Often White would just go Nf3 to control the g5-square, but then the annoying Black players insist on making their idea come to fruition by playing ...Bg4!, trading off the white knight, and then trading the bishops! This check makes Black go ...Bd7 or ...Nd7, which will make ...Bg4 impossible!   5.Nf3  Bg4!  allows Black to develop very comfortably.  Next, we will take on f3 and trade the bishops off with ...Bg5, and a check on b5 can be easily dealt with.  6.Bb5+  Nd7  is by no means a problem. }
5... Bd7 6. a4 { Black can no longer go ...Bg4! } 6... Bg5
{ We trade the bishops anyway. } 7. Nf3 Bxc1 8. Qxc1 Ne7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Nc4
{ The knight on c4 is clearly placed very well, which proves that delaying c2-c4 can be very beneficial! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "A typical blunder: ...Nh5??"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p2bbppp/np1p1n2/2pPp3/1PP1P3/P4N1P/2BN1PP1/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is not a real position from the course but a very similar one. I have just adjusted the placement of a few pieces. On the board, we have a type of position you would get when you choose the slow plan where Black does not trade the bishops. Here, the main plan would be pushing ...f7-f5 and trying to develop play on the kingside. A few thoughts:  If you play ...f7-f5 without ...g7-g6, White can often take and get an outpost on e4.  To prevent that, you can first go ...g7-g6 and only then ...f7-f5 in order to be able to play ...gxf5. The advantage of this plan was just described above, but the downside is that it takes a little longer. Since the position is closed, it's typically worth waiting!  Now, the tactical part. Black needs to move the knight. Should we go to e8 or h5?  Both could be fine, but make sure to not blunder. }
12... Nh5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Qxh5
{ And we lost a pawn! So when you go ...Nh5, make sure it's either protected by ...g7-g6, or White cannot make this tactic happen for some other reason. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "The ...Bxh3! sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
{ Yes, I know, this is King's Indian, not Benoni. But we will greatly benefit from seeing the following idea, which is typical of many Benoni positions too. }
5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7
{ Now, let's learn about Black's key attacking idea. Let's say White just plays some rather meaningless moves, while Black develops kingside play as we're supposed to. }
9. Ne1 Nd7 { Black prepares ...f7-f5. } 10. Nd3 f5 11. f3 f4
{ Now, c4-c5 is supposed to be played quickly. White also should have tried to get Be3-f2 in, so that c4-c5 is easier to carry out. But let's imagine White has no clue what is happening. How would Black win then? }
12. Rb1 g5 13. Ra1 Ng6 14. Rb1 g4
{ This move enables White to grab a pawn, but again, we're only looking at the key idea Black has, so let's not be cherry-picking. }
15. Ra1 Qh4 16. Rb1 Nf6 17. Ra1 g3 { Now it's over. } 18. h3
{ 18.hxg3  fxg3  results in checkmate after ...Qh2+ as well. } 18... Bxh3
{ This is the absolute key idea to remember. Black wins by force with this bishop sacrifice. But if it didn't exist, Black wouldn't have a way to break through! }
19. gxh3 Qxh3
{ Black will either checkmate White or win a lot of material after desperate moves like Rf2. It's over. Remember this idea of a sacrifice on h3! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Structures and Ideas"]
[Black "No light-squared bishop means no attack!"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/ppp3bp/3p1nn1/3Pp3/2P1Pp1q/2NN1PpP/PP4P1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We had just seen an almost identical position but with the light-squared bishops on the board. Black was able to sacrifice the bishop on h3 and easily win the game with a decisive attack.  Here, however, this idea no longer exists, so White's king is completely safe, and White can try to develop play on the queenside with c4-c5.  The only attacking idea Black has is to bring the knight to g5 and try sacrificing it on h3 instead of the queen. That should not be good enough though, as White can now also use the second rank, which is no longer blocked by the light-squared bishop, to cover up the h2-square. }
18... h6 { Black frees up the h7-square for the knight. } 19. Kh1
{ After  19.Nb5  Rf7  20.Qe2  ,  White gets some counterplay. The position still looks dodgy, but Black cannot break through, and while the sacrifices on h3 could still be annoying and need to be watched out for, it looks like White avoided an immediate loss and is relatively safe. }
19... Nh7 20. Ne2 { The knight is coming to help defend! } 20... Ng5 21. Ng1
{ The knight maneuver looks like an interesting defensive idea, as White just prevents any sacrifices forever. This position doesn't look pretty, but Black won't be able to make progress on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Main Lines with c2-c4"]
[Black "Main Line with c2-c4 − 4.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. c4
{ This is a very common move, especially among club players. White always places the pawn on c4, so why not here? Most players nearly pre-move 2.c4 after going 1.d4! However, I believe this setup isn't the best because this move blocks the light-squared bishop and prevents White from ever giving an annoying check on b5. Also, now the c4-square is no longer available for the white knight.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. Nc3
{ White can also delay advancing the e-pawn, but if our opponent plans on doing so in the future, it will just transpose. }
4... Be7 5. Nf3
{ This is also likely to transpose but potentially could have independent meaning. }
5... Bg4 6. h3
{ The only move that could have independent value, as  6.e4  Bxf3  would transpose. }
6... Bxf3 7. gxf3
{ It seems that the harm from the ruined pawn structure outweighs the fact that the bishops will stay on the board. After  7.exf3  Bg5  , we get to fulfill our plan of exchanging the dark-squared bishops.  However, in case of  7.gxf3  , Black has  7...Bg5  , which is a logical continuation of our idea. That’s not a bad move, but here it fails to achieve the trade, as White can just go  8.e3  , so we change the plan. }
7... Nf6 8. Rg1
{ White tries to get some activity on the g-file, but we can easily shut this down. }
8... Nh5 9. e3 g6
{ Next, we will play ...Nd7, ...f7-f5, and so on. It's not obvious what to do with the white king since staying in the center is silly, but castling long is scary, as that can run into ...b7-b5; the white bishops are very restricted too. }
