[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. c4
{ This is a very common move, especially among club players. White always places the pawn on c4, so why not here? Most players nearly pre-move 2.c4 after going 1.d4! However, I believe this setup isn't the best because this move blocks the light-squared bishop and prevents White from ever giving an annoying check on b5. Also, now the c4-square is no longer available for the white knight.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. e4
{ Both parties have placed three pawns in the center, creating a very closed position with pawn chains. Now what?   White has more space. Therefore, Black should want to trade minor pieces.  Both sides have a good and a bad bishop. For Black, the f8-bishop is the bad one because it is restricted by our own pawns. For White, on the other hand, the bad bishop is on f1. Hence, Black should specifically focus on trading that bishop.  It is also possible to discuss the pawn breaks, such as ...f7-f5, ...b7-b5, or b2-b4/f2-f4 from White's perspective, but our priority will be trading that bad bishop. }
4... Be7
{ Black is looking to play ...Bg5! on the next turn and get rid of the bishop! This is exactly why we started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...c5  and not  1...Nf6  − the goal was to keep that knight in its original position in order to keep the  maneuver ...Bf8-e7-g5 available! Now, White can either just keep developing, or try to prevent our plan. }
5. Nf3
{ By developing the knight here, White is taking the g5-square under control, making it impossible for us to trade off the bishops as we wanted to. }
5... Bg4
{ This move is very logical. What do we want? We want to exchange the white knight and then go ...Bg5, trading off the bad dark-squared bishop. }
6. Qa4+ { The check is recommended by Sam Shankland. } 6... Nd7
{ We are looking to take on f3 and trade the bishops with ...Bg5 as planned earlier.  6...Qd7  is not a bad move, but I’d rather not make it, as it gives  up control of the g5-square and makes the trade impossible. }
