9... Qd8
{ The queen is placed best on its home square, surprisingly. Or, at least, that's true until the move ...a7-a6 is played and the queenside is secured. }
10. g3
{ White is immediately activating the light-squared bishop by trying to place it on h3. }
10... a6
{ 10...Ne7  was played in the games that reached this position but after  11.Bh3  Na6  12.Qe3  , I do not think Black is well-equipped to meet White's positional aggression,  such as f2-f4, which is already coming; the knights are misplaced. }
11. Bh3 Nf6 12. O-O O-O
{ With ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, ...Rb8, and ...b7-b5 coming, Black is comfortable. White is risking less here, as the bishop is perfectly placed and can be traded off if White wants to, but we have nothing to worry about.  However, the key aspect is to remember to place the knight on f6, not e7, to control the kingside more. Here, ...f7-f5 might not be easy to push because of the bishop on h3, but we can easily play on the queenside instead, as the white bishop isn’t able to control it. }
