{ This move is very logical. What do we want? We want to exchange the white knight and then go ...Bg5, trading off the bad dark-squared bishop. }
6. Be2
{ The most popular move.  6.h3  is also sometimes played, but it just results in the same positions as  6.Nc3  with a tempo down for White. Black wants to take  on f3 anyway, so why rush it? }
6... Bxf3 { Of course, we eliminate the knight that was preventing ...Bg5. } 7.
Bxf3 Bg5
{ And, as usual, we trade the bishops. Now, let's talk about the difference between White taking on f3 with the bishop or the queen. It is good for us that the white queen isn't on f3 because it could go to g3 or g4 and disturb our kingside a bit.  However, when the white bishop stays on f3, the queen remains free to go to b3 or a4 and harass our queenside. Given that our queen is leaving, going all the way to g5, we need to make sure the queenside doesn't end up endangered.   Most people let the bishop trade happen by playing  8.Nc3  or taking on g5, but some try to avoid it with the cunning move  8.Nd2  . }
8. Nd2
{ White can also avoid the bishop trade. This move seems rather logical if you think of the black bishop as a bad piece. However, it is important to remember that once it gets out of the pawn chain, it is rather active! Therefore, White isn't really accomplishing much with the last move, which is why it is not particularly popular. }
8... Nd7
{ Now, White can try one of two things: either castle and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop  (avoiding the trade)  or try to exploit the position of our bishop on g5 with some aggressive moves. }
9. g3 { This move prepares h2-h4, which would chase our bishop. } 9... Ne7
{ We place the knight on e7 in order to prepare ...f7-f5 and avoid blocking the f-pawn! }
10. h4 Bxd2+
{ The position is very closed, so it makes sense to just trade off our bishop for the knight and play with the knights versus bishops, especially because retreating to h6 would waste time and potentially make the bishop a target of a future pawn storm. }
11. Bxd2 O-O { Black is ready to push ...f7-f5 at a time of our choosing. } 12.
h5
{ White wants to run the pawn all the way up to h6, creating weaknesses on the dark squares around our king. }
12... h6 13. g4
{ This move is aimed at preventing ...f7-f5, which is something we would otherwise gladly go for, as well as at preparing g4-g5 to open up files and attack our king. }
13... f6
{ At first glance, it may seem like Black is cramped on the kingside, but closer examination reveals that this is not an accurate assessment. That's because the position is very closed.  There are no pawn breaks available to either party. White cannot ever push g4-g5. The move f2-f4 will be immediately met with ... exf4, and we will get an outpost on e5 for our knight.  Next, Black can even consider bringing the knight to g5 via f8 and h7. However, since there is no play on the kingside available to either side, it makes sense to focus on the queenside by preparing the ...b7-b5 break. Realistically, the position is so closed that it would be difficult for either side to make any progress. }
