11... Qc7
{ Now, in all the games that arrived here, White offered a queen trade but could have also jumped on b6 with the knight right away. Let's explore both. }
12. Qb6
{ This move poses the highest amount of problems, or at least, so it seems. The annoying queen is occupying a great square, offering a trade that we cannot accept. }
12... Kd8
{ Like it or not, Black needs to give up castling rights to avoid losing material. However, that's okay. The position is very closed, so if needed, Black can always hide the king on e7 in the future, or just walk it to f8-g7. Remember, we are playing for a long-term advantage. We want to get an endgame with a good knight versus a bad bishop!   12...Qxb6??  loses material by force.  13.Nxb6  Ra7  14.Nc8!  Ra8  15.Nxd6++-  and White wins. }
13. Qb3
{ Having deprived Black of castling rights, the white queen is ready to retreat. Now, White is looking to invade on b6 with the knight.   13.Qxc7+  Kxc7  is Black's dream position, of course, as the endgame is safe. There are space problems and White has a bad bishop.  We can slowly start preparing the ...b7-b5 or ...f7-f5 pawn break, enjoying risk-free positional pressure. }
13... Nd7 { We have to prevent Nb6. } 14. O-O Ngf6
{ I like developing the knight here, rather than on e7. This is because we will not be pushing ...f7-f5, at least for a foreseeable amount of time. Instead, we will focus on improving our king's position, and maybe advance our h-pawn as we are about to see! }
15. Nc3 { The knight is no longer useful on a4, so White brings it back. }
15... Ke7 { The king is walking to a better place. } 16. g3
{ With this move, White could try to prepare f2-f4, looking to grab space on the kingside. Interestingly enough, not only we are not worried about that, but we are very thrilled to see this move, as it enables our creative plan that we are seeing throughout the chapter. }
16... h5 { Black can now take advantage of this hook on the kingside! } 17. h4
Rag8
{ With ...g7-g5 coming, it is obvious that Black's position is unfolding like a powerful spring, and White already needs to be careful. Reminder: the light-squared bishop on f3 is bad, while the king on e7 is perfectly safe! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Main Lines without c2-c4"]
[Black "Main Line without c2-c4 − 4.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. e4
{ In this chapter, we will be discussing the most dangerous setup available to White against our Old Benoni. Namely, our opponent will try to take advantage of the fact the move c2-c4 has not been played yet by foregoing it altogether. But wait, why is that advantageous? Doesn't almost every 1.d4 player try to place the pawn on c4 as soon as possible, to take more space? Well, the thing is that White already controls the center. By delaying the move c2-c4, White gets the following benefits:  The c4-square is available for the knight. This is valuable because it can come there to put pressure on the d6-pawn.  The f1-bishop is not nearly as restricted. For example, White can give a check on b5 in many positions, to disrupt our development a bit. We often like going ...Bg4 to eliminate the f3-knight, but blocking the check with ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 makes that impossible.  
The bad news is that objectively speaking, White is better in this line. I do believe it is very interesting to play the Old Benoni, of course − that's why I am writing the course! But, to be fair, White is better. The good news is that at the club level, you won't have problems.  For example, the setups with c2-c4 are 4 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ more popular in Lichess games of players rated 1600-2000 than the 'correct' setup without c2-c4. And then, even within the most testing line, White played the best way in just about 1% of the games, or 50 games out of 5000! Of course, I will also suggest a few ways for us to tackle this principled setup, so you can choose, depending on your opponent and your mood. Let's go!   3.Nc3  d6  4.Nf3  Be7  5.e4  transposes to the 3.e4 lines.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. f4 { Direct play like this does not threaten Black at all. } 4...
exf4 5. Bxf4
{ Now, White's pieces seem to be coming out pretty rapidly. However, the e5-square becomes a great outpost for a black knight, and the e4-pawn could become rather weak as well. }
5... Nf6 { For now, we just develop. } 6. Nc3 a6
{ I like this move because it prepares ...b7-b5. } 7. a4
{ After White's inevitable response, we no longer have to worry about Bb5+ or Nb5-related ideas! }
7... g6
{ The bishop could also go to e7, but given the freedom to deploy it more actively, we gladly will! It will look great on the long diagonal while also making our king even safer. }
8. Nf3 Bg4
{ It would be useful to eliminate this knight in order to achieve a few things: decrease the spatial disadvantage, and get better control of the e5-square. }
9. Be2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O
{ Next, we will go ...Bxf3, ...Qe7, and ...Nbd7-e5. It is important to play the weird-looking move ...Qe7 so that after ...Nbd7, the d6-pawn won't be hanging. Black is very comfortable, and in practical play, it is much easier to play with the black pieces since White doesn't seem to have a plan! }
*

