6. a5
{ This move is aimed at squeezing the queenside. Importantly, White immediately gets access to the b6-square, which is why, surprisingly, our traditional plan turns out to not work very well.  Fortunately, the move a4-a5 is rare. However, it does not spare us the need to know about this interesting positional trap and how to deal with it! }
6... Nd7
{ This time, we will play a slow positional game with the bishops on the board.   6...Bg5?  Amazingly, this logical move doesn't work well because first White gets to trade the bishop,  7.Bxg5  Qxg5  8.Nf3  , then win a tempo on the queen.  8...Qe7  9.Nd2!  And now the knight rapidly arrives  at the c4-square, which makes Black's position rather unpleasant!  For instance, after  9...Nf6  10.Nc4  ,  White is threatening Nb6, so we need to react.  10...Nbd7  11.Bd3  . Now, White  protects the e4-pawn so the knight can move from c3.  11...O-O  12.Na4  and now, let's say Black tries to prepare the standard plan on the kingside with  12...g6  . Black can pretend to be preparing  the ...f7-f5 break, but somehow it is very difficult to make it work!    13.O-O  Nh5  , everything seems okay, right?  14.Qd2  f5?  Unfortunately, this move runs into a ton of tactical problems, such as  15.exf5!  gxf5  16.Qh6!  This is a double attack on the knight and  the d6-pawn, and after  16...Nhf6  17.Bxf5+-  , Black is losing on the spot. Quite a passive position as you can see! }
7. Nf3
{ Now, we can no longer trade the bishops off with ...Bg5, so we will focus on the ...f7-f5 plan. }
7... Ngf6 8. Bd3
{ Both parties keep developing. A reminder: typically, the white bishop is better placed on d3 than on e2 because from here it is protecting the e4-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nh5
{ We are getting ready to play ...g7-g6 and ...f7-f5 at a good moment. A few nuances:  We could start with ...g7-g6. It even seems safer to do so because then after ...Nh5 the knight will never be hanging. However, there is a downside. Namely, White's bishop can sneak into h6! That is by no means a disaster, but it is rather annoying. By delaying this move, we are waiting for White to either move the bishop elsewhere or block it with a move like Nf3-d2.  The knight on h5, although it looks loose, isn't hanging for a tactical reason! }
10. g3
{ It is logical for White to restrict our knight by preventing it from coming to f4.   10.Nxe5??  is a typical tactical idea, which turns out a blunder due to another typical tactical response!  10...Nxe5  11.Qxh5??  Bg4  and the queen gets trapped! }
10... g6 { Sooner or later, we go ...g7-g6. } 11. Nd2
{ White is trying to improve the passive knight by rerouting it to c4, as usual.   11.Bh6  − White could also develop the bishop here, as I mentioned in the previous note. But I am not too worried about that since we have  11...Ng7  ,  with ...f7-f5, or maybe ...Nf6, ...Kh8 and ...Ng8 followed by ...f7-f5 coming next. }
11... b5
{ We could just allow the knight to come there, but I prefer to make this move, which either achieves a terrific structure on the queenside or allows our knight to come to b6. }
12. axb6 Nxb6 13. Nc4
{ The knight still needs to go here, or else what would it do? } 13... Nxc4 14.
Bxc4 Bg5
{ By trading off the bishops, Black achieves a perfectly acceptable position. The computer believes White is somewhat better, and it is not too difficult to justify its evaluation − it is all about the weak-ish a6-pawn.  I do agree that the pawn is pretty weak, but it seems that with ...f7-f5 coming, and maybe ...Qxg5 followed by ...Bh3, ... Nf4, and so on, Black should have a ton of activity on the kingside to compensate for that weak pawn.  In practical terms, I definitely think Black is perfectly okay; from the analytical point, I can accept that White is somewhat better, but this advantage is not critical at all. }
15. f4 { Importantly, this natural aggressive-looking move is wrong. } 15...
exf4 16. gxf4 Bf6
{ It turns out that White weakened the king and enabled tons of counterplay − both versus the king, with ideas like ...Bd4, ...Qh4, ...Bh3 arriving in no time, and against the e4-pawn! }
