6. Nf3
{ This logical move not only develops a piece, but it also prevents the bishop trade that we are hoping to accomplish. }
6... Bg4
{ Since we are very keen on trading off the bishop via g5, we make this move in order to eliminate the opponent's knight and then trade the bishop with ...Bg5 anyway.   In this position, White is facing a bit of a critical choice. The most popular move by far is  7.Be2  . However, I think the only real way to pose problems to Black is  7.h3  because White should want to capture  on f3 with the queen and then go Qg3 or Qg4 to harass our kingside.   6...f5?  A lot of people would be tempted to push the pawn because that's a common thing to do in a position with pawn chains. However, that's a really bad idea. Since this is a typical pawn push, let's learn why it is not good.  7.exf5  Bxf5  8.Bd3!  The problem is that White will take  control of the e4-square.    8...Qd7  , it makes sense to protect the bishop instead of taking  on d3 and helping White develop the queen as well. After  9.O-O  Nf6  10.Bxf5  Qxf5  , the position wouldn't be that bad if White didn't have a way to develop a strong initiative immediately.  11.Nh4!  Qd7  12.f4!+-  and the position is opening too fast. White will take  on f4, put pressure on the d6-pawn, jump into f5 with the knight, and so on. }
7. h3
{ White should immediately challenge the bishop in order to be able to take on f3 with the queen. From here, the queen would be able to come to the kingside and attack it. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bg5
{ Of course, we still pursue our plan of trading the bishops. } 9. Qg3
{ White can also let Black take on c1 and immediately make the queen move. However, I do not believe this is a challenging way of playing. }
9... Bxc1 10. Rxc1 { 10.Qxg7?  loses material after  10...Bxb2  . } 10... g6
{ The only thing we need to be careful about is not running into h3-h4-h5. So, if White ever goes h3-h4, we immediately respond with ...h7-h5. Otherwise, we play ...Nd7, ...Ngf6, ...O-O, and then likely ...Nh5 and ...f7-f5. }
11. Bd3
{ White needs to continue developing. It makes sense to place the bishop here rather than on e2 because this way the e4-pawn is protected and the white knight is free to go wherever it likes, such as b1-d2-c4. }
11... Nd7 { We just keep developing. } 12. O-O Ngf6
{ As usual, the knight goes to f6 rather than e7. This is both to prevent the annoying h4-h5 ideas, and because we don't need the knight on e7 to 'prepare' the ...f7-f5 push.  What we need is more pieces in the attack, so it would be better to deploy the knight via h5 and f4. Also, by playing ...Nh5, we will chase away the white queen and maybe get an opportunity to sneak our queen in there with ...Qg5 or ...Qh4, making the attack much more likely to succeed!  White could consider stopping the knight maneuver with Be2, but that has several disadvantages. Specifically, the e4-pawn will be a bit loose and the c3-knight will have a hard time moving away as a result. It's not easy to play this position with White, actually! }
13. Nb1
{ This natural move turns out a bit suspicious! Black could make some normal moves like  13...O-O  or  13...Nh5  and do well, but it's even better to play the text. }
13... c4 14. Bxc4 Nxe4 15. Qe3 f5
{ Black has an extra pawn in the center and a clearly better position! Learning this ...c5-c4 idea, which is aimed at distracting the bishop from protecting the e4-pawn, is very useful for you, as it is fairly common in these positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Main Lines without c2-c4"]
[Black "Main Line without c2-c4 − 4.Nc3 a6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. e4
{ In this chapter, we will be discussing the most dangerous setup available to White against our Old Benoni. Namely, our opponent will try to take advantage of the fact the move c2-c4 has not been played yet by foregoing it altogether. But wait, why is that advantageous? Doesn't almost every 1.d4 player try to place the pawn on c4 as soon as possible, to take more space? Well, the thing is that White already controls the center. By delaying the move c2-c4, White gets the following benefits:  The c4-square is available for the knight. This is valuable because it can come there to put pressure on the d6-pawn.  The f1-bishop is not nearly as restricted. For example, White can give a check on b5 in many positions, to disrupt our development a bit. We often like going ...Bg4 to eliminate the f3-knight, but blocking the check with ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 makes that impossible.  
The bad news is that objectively speaking, White is better in this line. I do believe it is very interesting to play the Old Benoni, of course − that's why I am writing the course! But, to be fair, White is better. The good news is that at the club level, you won't have problems.  For example, the setups with c2-c4 are 4 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ more popular in Lichess games of players rated 1600-2000 than the 'correct' setup without c2-c4. And then, even within the most testing line, White played the best way in just about 1% of the games, or 50 games out of 5000! Of course, I will also suggest a few ways for us to tackle this principled setup, so you can choose, depending on your opponent and your mood. Let's go!   3.Nc3  d6  4.Nf3  Be7  5.e4  transposes to the 3.e4 lines.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. Nc3 a6
{ I like this move order best since it addresses any Bb5+ issues. If we don't go ...a7-a6, then why could this check turn out to be annoying? Well, our plan is to play ...Be7-g5 and trade off the bad bishop, right? But typically, White tries to prevent that by developing the knight to f3. In those cases, we go ...Bg4 and trade off the knight to make the ...Be7-g5 idea happen anyway.  Unfortunately, when White gives a check on b5 and we block with ...Bd7 or ...Nd7, it is no longer possible to play ...Bg4 and exchange that knight, so our main plan wouldn't work. Of course, our opponent should not let us play ...b7-b5, so White's reaction is sort of forced. }
5. a4
{ Although strictly speaking ...b7-b5 is not a threat, White does not want to always be on the lookout for this logical move, which allows the opponent to expand on the queenside. As a rule of thumb, ...b7-b5 is always good, unless Black is considerably behind in development and can have the pawn chain blown up, or if it's a blunder.   For example, right here  5.Bd3  wouldn't be a mistake, as after  5...b5  6.a4  b4  7.Nce2  , White is not worse, but I think Black gets a lot of activity in that position too. As a result, in 99% of the cases in the Benoni, the right thing to do as White is automatically  meet ...a7-a6 with a2-a4. }
5... Be7
{ Now we will develop the bishop here, looking to trade it off via g5, getting rid of our worst piece and decreasing our spatial disadvantage.   I have also investigated  5...Nf6  and did not find it terrible, but was not fully satisfied. However, I would still like to show you the way the game can go from here.  Our goal will be to play ...Be7 and castle and then push ...f7-f5.  6.Be2  , White just keeps developing.  6...Be7  7.Nf3  O-O  8.O-O  b6!?  This move is aimed at preventing White from squeezing our queenside at some point with a4-a5 and then following up with Nd2-c4-b6.    9.Nd2  , the knight is headed to a great  spot on c4.  9...Nbd7  , we just keep developing.  10.Nc4  Rb8!?  Black is looking to  push ...b6-b5 and grab space on the queenside. However, it is very important to be careful about not allowing Na5-c6 because the knight on c6 would be incredibly powerful.  11.f4!  White can afford to start developing the initiative, which is best done by opening up the center.   11...exf4  12.Bxf4  and now, the d6-pawn is under pressure:  12...Ne8  13.Qe1  . I would not call this position awful, as we can  play ...f7-f6 and ...Ne5 and keep defending in a rather solid position; however, there is certainly nothing appealing about it. }
6. Nf3
{ This logical move not only develops a piece, but it also prevents the bishop trade that we are hoping to accomplish. }
6... Bg4
{ Since we are very keen on trading off the bishop via g5, we make this move in order to eliminate the opponent's knight and then trade the bishop with ...Bg5 anyway.   In this position, White is facing a bit of a critical choice. The most popular move by far is  7.Be2  . However, I think the only real way to pose problems to Black is  7.h3  because White should want to capture  on f3 with the queen and then go Qg3 or Qg4 to harass our kingside.   6...f5?  A lot of people would be tempted to push the pawn because that's a common thing to do in a position with pawn chains. However, that's a really bad idea. Since this is a typical pawn push, let's learn why it is not good.  7.exf5  Bxf5  8.Bd3!  The problem is that White will take  control of the e4-square.    8...Qd7  , it makes sense to protect the bishop instead of taking  on d3 and helping White develop the queen as well. After  9.O-O  Nf6  10.Bxf5  Qxf5  , the position wouldn't be that bad if White didn't have a way to develop a strong initiative immediately.  11.Nh4!  Qd7  12.f4!+-  and the position is opening too fast. White will take  on f4, put pressure on the d6-pawn, jump into f5 with the knight, and so on. }
7. h3
{ White should immediately challenge the bishop in order to be able to take on f3 with the queen. From here, the queen would be able to come to the kingside and attack it. }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Bg5
{ Of course, we still pursue our plan of trading the bishops. } 9. Bxg5
{ It is imperative to force our queen to g5 in order for White's next idea to work best. }
9... Qxg5 10. h4
{ White can also consider chasing the queen away, but I am not too worried about this. }
10... Qd8
{ Typically, trading queens is good for us. However, this time I am not very confident about  10...Qf6  because it looks as though we are getting a bit squeezed on both flanks. After  11.Qxf6  Nxf6  12.a5!  Nbd7  13.g3  , the white bishop is fortunate:  it could have gone to a passive position on e2 or d3, but instead, White will bring it to a great spot on h3!    13...Ke7  , of course, it does not make any sense to castle, as the king is better off in the center.  14.Bh3!  Unfortunately, since the bishop can get active this way, White seems to have an advantage. Now White can either take on d7 on the next turn or do it at any point in the future, to avoid any long-term risk or just keep improving the position.  White is better here thanks to the extra space, but the bishop is not a bad piece.  14...h5!  We are stopping the kingside expansion. I don't think Black is in a lot of trouble, but I would certainly pick White, so let's avoid this scenario. }
11. a5
{ As usual in these positions, White wants to squeeze our queenside a bit and potentially prepare the Na4-b6 idea. }
11... Nd7 { Of course, we keep developing as usual. } 12. g3 Ne7
{ As a rule of thumb, we play ...Nf6 when we are afraid of h4-h5 because our pawn is already on g6. Or, we do that when the move ...f7-f5 is either impossible to carry out or so easy to carry out that the knight doesn't need to be on e7 to support that pawn push.  Instead, we play ...Ne7 when the pawn is not on g6 so the white h-pawn push doesn't scare us, and when ...f7-f5 is achievable but needs a bit of support. }
13. Bh3
{ This is the point of White's play, to not have the bishop in a passive position like e2 or d3. Instead, it is going to the h3-square, from where it is preventing the ...f7-f5 break while also staring at our knight! }
13... O-O 14. O-O f5
{ Here is another interesting idea for us to learn! Although it doesn't seem possible to make this pawn push work, we actually can with a bit of calculation! }
15. exf5 g6
{ We are getting the pawn back by taking advantage of the pin. Of course, White would not want to play g3-g4, ruining the king's shelter, so the pawn has to be returned. There is one more nuance that, fortunately, works in our favor. }
16. Ne4 Nxf5
{ Thankfully, we are not losing a pawn to Bxf5 followed by Nxd6 because the white queen will be hanging after we take back on f5 with the rook! }
17. Qd3 Qe7
{ White can install the knight on e6 by playing Ng5-e6, but I don't think it is doing that much there, and we can always trade it off with ...Nf8 or ...Nd4. It does look like White is somewhat better here because of the Ng5-e6 idea and the outpost on e6, but with ...Nf6, ...h7-h6, and ...Raf8 coming, I think it is fairly easy to play this position with Black! }
*

