{ Of course, we still pursue our plan of trading the bishops. } 9. Bxg5
{ It is imperative to force our queen to g5 in order for White's next idea to work best. }
9... Qxg5 10. Qg4
{ This surprising move is White's best way of playing against the Old Benoni, in my opinion. White is sort of forcing the queen trade since the threat is to invade on c8 as well as to take the g7-pawn if our queen goes too far away. }
10... Qxg4
{ So, we are forced to take. There is nothing wrong with the queen trade itself, but the problem is that White gets a semi-open h-file and more space on the kingside. }
11. hxg4 Nd7 { Of course, we should keep developing. } 12. Be2
{ And so does White. } 12... h6
{ I like this move because it prevents future g4-g5 ideas. As we are about to see, they are not dangerous right now − White could grab space that way a move earlier as well. However, it would be great to not have to worry about this possibility in the future. }
13. g5
{ This move ruins White's spatial advantage on the kingside without accomplishing much since we can simply undermine this pawn. }
13... f6 14. gxh6 Nxh6
{ White still has a slight advantage because of space and potential pressure on the h-file, but it shouldn't be too hard to neutralize that. }
15. Nd1
{ I think it makes sense for White to improve the knight, which wasn't doing anything on c3, by rerouting it to e3 and c4, from where it can put pressure on the d6-pawn. Also, by moving it away, White creates an opportunity to conveniently activate the a-rook via a3! From there, it can go to h3 or g3, to put pressure on our kingside. }
15... O-O-O
{ I like the idea of connecting the rooks this way because it will be easy for our king to look after the d6 and b7-pawns from c7. }
16. Ne3 g6 { This move restricts the white knight. } 17. Nc4 Kc7
{ With ...Nf7 and the rook trade coming next, I think Black should not have any problems whatsoever. In fact, in the long run, as usual, I can easily see Black slowly but surely taking over because the white bishop is rather unimpressive! }
