{ This logical move not only develops a piece, but it also prevents the bishop trade that we are hoping to accomplish. }
6... Bg4
{ Since we are very keen on trading off the bishop via g5, we make this move in order to eliminate the opponent's knight and then trade the bishop with ...Bg5 anyway.   In this position, White is facing a bit of a critical choice. The most popular move by far is  7.Be2  . However, I think the only real way to pose problems to Black is  7.h3  because White should want to capture  on f3 with the queen and then go Qg3 or Qg4 to harass our kingside.   6...f5?  A lot of people would be tempted to push the pawn because that's a common thing to do in a position with pawn chains. However, that's a really bad idea. Since this is a typical pawn push, let's learn why it is not good.  7.exf5  Bxf5  8.Bd3!  The problem is that White will take  control of the e4-square.    8...Qd7  , it makes sense to protect the bishop instead of taking  on d3 and helping White develop the queen as well. After  9.O-O  Nf6  10.Bxf5  Qxf5  , the position wouldn't be that bad if White didn't have a way to develop a strong initiative immediately.  11.Nh4!  Qd7  12.f4!+-  and the position is opening too fast. White will take  on f4, put pressure on the d6-pawn, jump into f5 with the knight, and so on. }
7. Be2
{ The much more popular move, but it is way less dangerous than  7.h3  . This is because White has to retake  on f3 with the bishop and not the queen. As a result, the queen is not able to jump to g4 and attack our kingside. }
7... Bxf3 { Of course, we keep carrying on with our plan. } 8. Bxf3 Bg5
{ Finally, the bad bishop is coming off the board. With only two minor pieces left, Black will not experience any spatial disadvantage problems. The goal here would be to trade the bishops, and ideally the queens and a pair of knights, and then play an endgame with a great knight versus a rather useless and restricted light-squared bishop. }
9. O-O
{ Given that the bishop trade can't be avoided anyway, White might as well just continue developing. }
9... Bxc1 10. Qxc1 Ne7
{ Next, we play ...Nd7, ...O-O, ...g7-g6, and ...f7-f5. } 11. g3
{ White tries to make room on g2 for the bishop and then prepares f2-f4 to grab space on the kingside. }
11... O-O 12. Bg2 Nd7
{ Now, White has a choice whether to push f2-f4 or not. It seems ambitious to do so, but actually, it turns out a wrong idea. }
13. f4 exf4 14. gxf4 Ng6
{ White will never be able to push f4-f5 because the knight will get a gorgeous outpost on e5. And, White will never be able to play e4-e5 either because we control that square too well. Next, we play ...Re8, maybe ...Qh4 and ...Re7 followed by ...Rae8 and ...Nf6, to put pressure on the e4-pawn. The g2-bishop is not great either. }
