9. Bxg5
{ White can trade the bishops on g5, but it is okay to have a queen on g5. It won't get in danger, and White cannot attack our queenside with moves like Nb5 or Qb3. }
9... Qxg5 10. h4
{ White can also harass our queen, but that doesn't really do anything either. }
10... Qd8 11. g3
{ This move accomplishes several things: White protects the h4-pawn so that after castling, it wouldn't be hanging; also, White covers up the f4-square while making room on g2 for the bishop. }
11... Nd7 12. a5
{ In the game that reached this position @@StartBracket@@½-½ Perez Vazquez-Esquivias Gomez, Collado Villalba 2017@@EndBracket@@, White tried squeezing Black on the queenside. That's okay because we can focus on preparing for the ...f7-f5 break. }
12... Ne7 13. O-O O-O
{ With ... g7-g6 and ...f7-f5 coming, Black is very comfortable. Again, Black would like to trade the queens and the knights and get an endgame with a good knight versus a bad bishop. At some point, potentially, ...c5-c4 and ...Nc5 or ...Rc8-c5 could be an interesting idea; however, you need to be careful to not lose the c4-pawn. }
