[White "2) Main Lines without c2-c4"]
[Black "Main Line without c2-c4 − 4.Nc3 Be7 5.Nf3 | Informational 5...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. e4
{ In this chapter, we will be discussing the most dangerous setup available to White against our Old Benoni. Namely, our opponent will try to take advantage of the fact the move c2-c4 has not been played yet by foregoing it altogether. But wait, why is that advantageous? Doesn't almost every 1.d4 player try to place the pawn on c4 as soon as possible, to take more space? Well, the thing is that White already controls the center. By delaying the move c2-c4, White gets the following benefits:  The c4-square is available for the knight. This is valuable because it can come there to put pressure on the d6-pawn.  The f1-bishop is not nearly as restricted. For example, White can give a check on b5 in many positions, to disrupt our development a bit. We often like going ...Bg4 to eliminate the f3-knight, but blocking the check with ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 makes that impossible.  
The bad news is that objectively speaking, White is better in this line. I do believe it is very interesting to play the Old Benoni, of course − that's why I am writing the course! But, to be fair, White is better. The good news is that at the club level, you won't have problems.  For example, the setups with c2-c4 are 4 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ more popular in Lichess games of players rated 1600-2000 than the 'correct' setup without c2-c4. And then, even within the most testing line, White played the best way in just about 1% of the games, or 50 games out of 5000! Of course, I will also suggest a few ways for us to tackle this principled setup, so you can choose, depending on your opponent and your mood. Let's go!   3.Nc3  d6  4.Nf3  Be7  5.e4  transposes to the 3.e4 lines.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. Nc3 Be7
{ We can also try postponing or foregoing ...a7-a6 altogether in favor of a different plan. We will go ...Nf6, castle kingside, and try to slowly prepare the ...f7-f5 break. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.Bb5+  is also a very popular and good move. Since we don't intend on  playing ...a7-a6 at any moment, it doesn't matter if White gives this check now or a move later, so it's covered  via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . }
5... Bg4
{ Let me show you why this move, and the entire idea of trading on f3 and then offering a bishop trade with ...Bg5, is not a great idea without the move ...a7-a6 included beforehand. It's not a terrible idea either, so you can certainly consider using it as an alternative option, but it's important to know about its downsides. }
6. h3 { As usual, White's best bet is to capture on f3 with the queen. } 6...
Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Bg5
{ Of course, that was the point behind ...Bg4 followed by ...Bxf3 − we want to trade the bad dark-squared bishop. }
8. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ So far so good. Then what is the downside of not going ...a7-a6 early enough? }
9. Nb5
{ Here it is! Now, the d6-pawn and the c7-square require attention, so our queen has to go back. }
9... Qd8 10. Qg4
{ White is not only attacking the g7-pawn, but is creating another threat too, and that one is easy to miss! }
10... Kf8 11. Nxd6
{ We cannot take the knight, surprisingly! So, did Black just lose a pawn? Fortunately, that didn't happen. }
11... Nf6
{ The queen is attacked, and it looks like we are about to win the knight on d6 once it goes away.  11...Qxd6??  12.Qc8+  Ke7  13.Qxb7+  loses the rook. }
12. Qc8 Qxc8 13. Nxc8 Nxe4
{ Black gets the lost pawn back. So, is everything okay? Unfortunately, our problems are not over just yet. This is for a few reasons:  White's d5-pawn will likely end up a protected passed pawn. We'd love to bring our knight to d6 to block it, but it isn't currently possible since the white c8-knight is controlling that square. So, our knight on e4 might end up in a bit of a tricky spot! }
14. Bd3 { White is immediately bothering the awkwardly positioned knight. }
14... Nd7
{ It's important to remember this creative intermediate move − we want to trade a pair of knights. The one on c8 has nowhere to retreat! Since the c8-knight is lost anyway, White can try to get something for it. At least a pawn, maybe? }
15. Bxe4
{ White shouldn't focus on winning that useless pawn, as the Nxa7 variation shows. Instead, White should try to immediately activate the bishop! The key is to prevent Black's pieces, be it a knight or a king, from arriving at the d6-square. So White must be able to meet a move like ...Ke7 with d5-d6+!, which would be a very helpful move, as it would drastically improve the bishop.   15.Nxa7?!  Interestingly enough, winning this pawn isn't a good positional decision! This is because after  15...Rxa7  16.Bxe4  Ke7!  17.c4  , Black is about to establish a great blockade on the dark squares. For example, first, we can provoke another weakening move with  17...Ra4!  and after  18.b3  Ra3=  , just blockade the white pawns.  With ...Kd6, ...g7-g6, and ...f7-f5 coming, Black has absolutely nothing to worry about despite being a pawn down. However, White had a better possibility earlier on. }
15... Rxc8 16. O-O-O
{ Now Black will experience issues because  16...Ke7  runs into  17.d6+  ,  preventing the blockade and even winning the b7-pawn. Chess is truly a tragedy of one tempo, isn't it? }
16... g6
{ We prevent the potentially annoying move Bf5! while also preparing to go ...f7-f5 ourselves. }
17. d6 b6 18. Rhe1
{ White is clearly pressing. I have explored this position a bit deeper and would love to share the analysis with you, but of course, the next moves are by no means worth memorizing. }
18... f5
{ Our goal is to play ...Kf7, ...Rhd8, and ...Nf6. Then we'll have a lot of space, and the d6-pawn could even become weak! }
19. Bb7
{ White wants to eliminate our knight by kicking out the rook that is controlling the c6-square. }
19... Rd8 20. Bc6
{ The knight cannot retreat because the e5-pawn would be lost. } 20... Kf7
{ We sacrifice the e5-pawn to get the pieces out.  20...e4?  seems natural but only helps White open the position even quicker after  21.f3! }
21. Re3
{ By declining the sacrifice, White, unfortunately, keeps some pretty noticeable pressure going on.   21.Bxd7  − surprisingly, winning a pawn isn't a great idea. It allows Black to completely equalize!  21...Rxd7  22.Rxe5  Re8!  The rook will invade  on e2 if White doesn't trade.  23.Rxe8  Kxe8=  and  with ... Kf7-e6 coming, the d6-pawn will not survive, so it's an equal endgame. Or, it's more precise to say it's a drawn endgame.  As you can see, such lines are also playable, and they are by all means worth investigating to understand the position deeper. But, objectively, it seems that playing the early ...a7-a6, which is what I recommend in the main line, is the way to go. }
