5. Nf3
{ 5.Bb5+  is also a very popular and good move. Since we don't intend on  playing ...a7-a6 at any moment, it doesn't matter if White gives this check now or a move later, so it's covered  via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . }
5... Nf6
{ The goal is to just castle and prepare the ...f7-f5 break when the time is right. }
6. Be2 { White can also just peacefully develop. } 6... O-O 7. O-O Ne8
{ The plan is to play ...f7-f5, or maybe ...g7-g6, ...Ne8-g7, and ...f7-f5 sometime later. However, it is important to not take too long because White has plenty of play, such as Nd2-c4, bringing the knight to a great semi-outpost, then a2-a4 to grab space on the queenside and stabilize the knight, then maybe f2-f4 at some point to get a semi-open f-file and put pressure on the d6-pawn after ...exf4 Bxf4, and so on. }
8. Nd2
{ White immediately starts improving the knight, which was not doing much on d2, by bringing it to a phenomenal square on c4. }
8... f5 { We follow up with this pawn break, as intended. } 9. exf5
{ White wouldn't want us to start rolling the kingside pawns up the board with ...f5-f4, ...g7-g5, etc. By capturing on f5, White also gets access to the new outpost on e4! }
9... Bxf5 10. Nc4 Nd7
{ Next, we can try to trade off this powerful c4-knight with ...Nb6, or exchange the bad dark-squared bishop with ...Be7-g5. }
11. Bd3
{ On the other hand, White wants to get rid of our light-squared bishop since it is our only piece that is currently overseeing the outpost on e4. }
11... Nb6
{ We continue with one of the mentioned trade ideas. That powerful c4-knight needs to disappear! }
12. Nxb6 Qxb6
{ Taking with the queen seems a bit awkward because now the queen is pretty misplaced. But it is better than taking with the pawn and making the structure rigid. In the future, we can still hope to go ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5, and make progress on the queenside. }
13. Bxf5
{ White is happy to trade off this bishop, as now the outpost on e4 can finally be used for the knight and because our bishop on e7 is supposedly a very bad piece. }
13... Rxf5 14. Ne4
{ So what is our plan? Why do we accept a position where the white knight seems so lovely, and where our dark-squared bishop isn't the brightest of a kind? This is because we plan on trading off the knights and enjoying pressure on the semi-open f-file, which should supposedly make up for the inferior bishop! }
14... Rf7
{ The rook retreats in advance to not be vulnerable to ideas like Qg4 or Qd3. }
15. c4
{ It seems logical for White to connect the queenside pawns. White cannot develop the c1-bishop without hanging the b2-pawn, so it makes sense to play b2-b3 next too. }
15... h6
{ This is a very important idea to remember. We want to challenge the white knight with ...Nf6, but that would run into Ng5! and then the opponent's cheeky horse will invade on e6. We make sure to prevent that! }
16. b3 Nf6 17. Ng3 Raf8
{ To my mind, Black has enough activity on the f-file and on the kingside overall to compensate for the outpost on e4 and the inferior bishop. Next, we will play ...Qd8, ...Nh7, ...Bg5, and so on, activating the rest of the pieces and looking to trade the bad bishop. }
