3... d6 4. Nc3 Be7
{ We can also try postponing or foregoing ...a7-a6 altogether in favor of a different plan. We will go ...Nf6, castle kingside, and try to slowly prepare the ...f7-f5 break. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.Bb5+  is also a very popular and good move. Since we don't intend on  playing ...a7-a6 at any moment, it doesn't matter if White gives this check now or a move later, so it's covered  via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . }
5... Nf6
{ The goal is to just castle and prepare the ...f7-f5 break when the time is right. }
6. Bb5+
{ Oftentimes in the Benoni positions, this check is very annoying. This is for a few reasons:  Often, we want to go ...Na6. So if we play ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 and then ...a7-a6 to kick out the bishop, the move ...Na6 is no longer available. If we go ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7, the move ...Bg4 is no longer available. }
6... Nbd7
{ Since we didn't plan on going ...Na6 or ...Bg4, it seems more natural to block with the knight. Now, Black has a typical positional threat: we are ready to play ...a7-a6, either kicking the bishop out and getting in the desired ...b7-b5, or forcing White to trade it on d7 for our knight, which would be great news as well because we'd get the bishop pair and solve some of our space-related problems. }
7. a4
{ A typical response and fairly forced. Now, if Black goes ...a7-a6 at any moment, White can just move the bishop back without running into ...b7-b5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ We are getting ready to play ...g7-g6, ...Ng7, and ...f7-f5. Or maybe we could consider queenside play, such as ...Nc7, ...Rb8, ...a7-a6, and ...b7-b5! }
9. Bd3
{ 9.Nd2  results in similar positions, for example after  9...a6  10.Bd3  b6  . }
9... a6
{ This move is aimed at preparing the ...b7-b5 break. Black could also start with ...b7-b6, but it's more prudent to play ...a7-a6 first to cover up the b5-square. If White goes a4-a5, Black can try ideas like ...Nc7, ...Bd7, and ...Nb5, besides the regular ...b7-b5 break. }
10. Nd2
{ White is carrying out the standard idea of improving the knight by bringing it to c4. From there, it will control the b6-square, while also putting pressure on the d6-pawn. And, of course, White is also clearing up the path for the f-pawn since one of the possible plans is to push f2-f4 to open up the f-file and develop the bishop to f4, from where it can put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... b6
{ This move is played to prevent a4-a5. Next, Black wants to go ...Nc7, ...Rb8, ...Bd7, and ...b6-b5. }
11. Nc4 Rb8 12. b3
{ I would use this variation to show you one important positional trap. If White makes such a move, feel free to use one of the typical ideas, such as trading the bishop with ...Be7-g5. However, although the ...b6-b5 break is overall desirable, it can really hurt our own position if executed at the wrong time. Let's see why. }
12... Bg5
{ 12...b5?  is terrible, as after  13.axb5  axb5  14.Na5!  +-,  the white knight is landing on c6 with devastating consequences. }
13. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ Black is ready to play ...b6-b5 some time soon, or maybe ...g7-g6 and ...f7-f5. The position is perfectly fine! }
