[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Main Lines without c2-c4"]
[Black "Main Line without c2-c4 − 4.Nc3 Be7 | Alternative #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. e4
{ In this chapter, we will be discussing the most dangerous setup available to White against our Old Benoni. Namely, our opponent will try to take advantage of the fact the move c2-c4 has not been played yet by foregoing it altogether. But wait, why is that advantageous? Doesn't almost every 1.d4 player try to place the pawn on c4 as soon as possible, to take more space? Well, the thing is that White already controls the center. By delaying the move c2-c4, White gets the following benefits:  The c4-square is available for the knight. This is valuable because it can come there to put pressure on the d6-pawn.  The f1-bishop is not nearly as restricted. For example, White can give a check on b5 in many positions, to disrupt our development a bit. We often like going ...Bg4 to eliminate the f3-knight, but blocking the check with ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 makes that impossible.  
The bad news is that objectively speaking, White is better in this line. I do believe it is very interesting to play the Old Benoni, of course − that's why I am writing the course! But, to be fair, White is better. The good news is that at the club level, you won't have problems.  For example, the setups with c2-c4 are 4 times@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ more popular in Lichess games of players rated 1600-2000 than the 'correct' setup without c2-c4. And then, even within the most testing line, White played the best way in just about 1% of the games, or 50 games out of 5000! Of course, I will also suggest a few ways for us to tackle this principled setup, so you can choose, depending on your opponent and your mood. Let's go!   3.Nc3  d6  4.Nf3  Be7  5.e4  transposes to the 3.e4 lines.   Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. Nc3 Be7
{ We can also try postponing or foregoing ...a7-a6 altogether in favor of a different plan. We will go ...Nf6, castle kingside, and try to slowly prepare the ...f7-f5 break. }
5. Nf3
{ 5.Bb5+  is also a very popular and good move. Since we don't intend on  playing ...a7-a6 at any moment, it doesn't matter if White gives this check now or a move later, so it's covered  via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2pPp3/4P3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bb5+  . }
5... Nf6
{ The goal is to just castle and prepare the ...f7-f5 break when the time is right. }
6. Bb5+
{ Oftentimes in the Benoni positions, this check is very annoying. This is for a few reasons:  Often, we want to go ...Na6. So if we play ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7 and then ...a7-a6 to kick out the bishop, the move ...Na6 is no longer available. If we go ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7, the move ...Bg4 is no longer available. }
6... Nbd7
{ Since we didn't plan on going ...Na6 or ...Bg4, it seems more natural to block with the knight. Now, Black has a typical positional threat: we are ready to play ...a7-a6, either kicking the bishop out and getting in the desired ...b7-b5, or forcing White to trade it on d7 for our knight, which would be great news as well because we'd get the bishop pair and solve some of our space-related problems. }
7. a4
{ A typical response and fairly forced. Now, if Black goes ...a7-a6 at any moment, White can just move the bishop back without running into ...b7-b5. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ We are getting ready to play ...g7-g6, ...Ng7, and ...f7-f5. Or maybe we could consider queenside play, such as ...Nc7, ...Rb8, ...a7-a6, and ...b7-b5! }
9. Bd3
{ 9.Nd2  results in similar positions, for example after  9...a6  10.Bd3  b6  . }
9... a6
{ This move is aimed at preparing the ...b7-b5 break. Black could also start with ...b7-b6, but it's more prudent to play ...a7-a6 first to cover up the b5-square. If White goes a4-a5, Black can try ideas like ...Nc7, ...Bd7, and ...Nb5, besides the regular ...b7-b5 break. }
10. Nd2
{ White is carrying out the standard idea of improving the knight by bringing it to c4. From there, it will control the b6-square, while also putting pressure on the d6-pawn. And, of course, White is also clearing up the path for the f-pawn since one of the possible plans is to push f2-f4 to open up the f-file and develop the bishop to f4, from where it can put pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... b6
{ This move is played to prevent a4-a5. Next, Black wants to go ...Nc7, ...Rb8, ...Bd7, and ...b6-b5. }
11. Nc4 Rb8 12. f4
{ This is the more ambitious plan from White's perspective, accepting the fact that we can take on f4, leaving the e5-square outside White's control @@StartBracket@@which is an outpost for us@@EndBracket@@ and a potentially weak-ish pawn on e4. Our opponent also understands we wouldn't do that because it would be a bad idea from a dynamic standpoint as you are about to see. }
12... Bf6
{ 12...exf4?  13.Bxf4  doesn't work great because White can  push e4-e5 on the next move, getting a powerful passed pawn on the d-file. We cannot go ...Bf6 and ...Ne5 because that would drop the d6-pawn. }
13. f5
{ An ambitious move, aimed at grabbing space on the kingside and preparing a big pawn storm with g2-g4-g5, and so on. But, this move is just a bad move since we can go ...b5. }
13... b5
{ Overtaking the initiative. It's important to understand that this time, unlike in one of the previous clickable variations, taking on b5 followed by Na5-c6 is no longer threatening. }
14. axb5 axb5 15. Na5 c4 16. Be2 b4 17. Nb1 Ra8
{ White is in trouble. Specifically, the knight is lost since we always have ...Qb6+ if needed. }
