[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Fianchetto Setups"]
[Black "Fianchetto Setups 4.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 { White immediately locks up the center, grabbing space. } 2...
e5
{ This move allows us to also fight for the center. Next, we will go ...d7-d6, creating a sturdy pawn center.  Now, the White players reach a crossroads − they have many possible move orders as well as setups they can try.  To my mind, the most dangerous one is when they go Nc3 and e2-e4, keeping the c-pawn in its original position. However, we will investigate all the other possibilities as well, such as playing with c2-c4, fianchettoing the bishop on g2, and so on. }
3. e4
{ Some White players, especially at the club level, can also play  3.dxe6  . However, after  3...fxe6  ,  Black wants to play ...d7-d5 and occupy the entire center, and it is easy for White to be worse in no time. }
3... d6 4. g3
{ Now, it is time for us to discuss setups where White fianchettoes the bishop! But how to make sure we do not get confused with different move orders? To my mind, it makes sense to simply divide the chapter into a few logical parts:  one where White plays c2-c4 as well as e2-e4; another one where White keeps the pawn on c2 and plays e2-e4 only; and finally, we will also look at the setups where the kingside knight goes to f3, or to e2!    4.c4  Be7  5.g3  is another way to get there, of course. }
4... Be7 5. c4
{ Let's see what happens if White does play c2-c4. Here, I am sure we could try several continuations. The most natural one, of course, is to play ...Bg5 anyway! }
5... Bg5 6. Bxg5 Qxg5 7. Ne2
{ White can try to develop this way. Perhaps the only point of doing that would be to try preparing f2-f4 sometime soon. }
7... Qe7
{ We can place the knight on h6 and prepare ...f7-f5. If that's the case, it makes more sense to keep the queen on a slightly more active e7-square rather than the slightly more passive one on d8. }
8. Bg2 Nd7 9. Nbc3 h5
{ This is by no means necessary, but why not? Whenever the knight is not on f3, but the move g2-g3 has been played, advancing the h-pawn is very tempting! You would think our opponent certainly would not want to allow for the continuous assault with ...h5-h4, which would make White permanently uncomfortable on the kingside. For that reason, our pawn should be stopped. }
10. h4 Nh6
{ However, now Black is doing great. Playing f2-f4 no longer makes sense, as the g4-square would become a hole. Black, on the other hand, can go ...f7-f5, ...O-O, ...Nf6, and prepare ...f5-f4. }
11. O-O O-O
{ Of course, this is an interesting rich position, which could be explored much further, but since it has never occurred in practice, I think it's fair for us to stop! As always, Black has no problems, as we traded off the dark-squared bishop! }
*

