5... Bg5 6. Bxg5 Qxg5 7. Nf3
{ This leads to positions that we discussed in the main chapter, except the pawn is for some reason on g3. So what? No problem! }
7... Qd8
{ It is hard to give a clear preference for one move or the other, but after  7...Qe7  , the queen  looks more harmonious on this square and makes it easier to connect the rooks in the future, while on d8 the queen is not in the way of a potential ...Ng8-e7. }
8. Bg2 Ne7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O Nd7
{ Next, as usual, we play ...g7-g6, maybe ...h7-h6 to cover up the g5-square, and then ...f7-f5. A standard and good position! }
