[Black "2.e4 cxd4 3.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. e4
{ All of a sudden, we are finding ourselves in the Sicilian Defense! More specifically, in the Smith-Morra Gambit, which has been rather popular with club players as of late. I never even thought White could play  2.e4  , until reading one of Dvoretsky's books.   The greatest coach of all time shows a game that he played versus some strong GM, where 1.d4 c5 was seen, and White started thinking, clearly not expecting this opening. Dvoretsky says 'With absolute horror, I realized White can go 2.e4, getting into the Sicilian. My opponent played both 1.d4 and 1.e4, while I didn't know much about the Sicilian. Luckily, he didn't do it.'  Fortunately for us, we won't need to learn the entire Sicilian Defense − just a few short lines will be more than enough! }
2... cxd4
{ Now, White is facing a choice, to either play  3.c3  , going for the Smith-Morra Gambit, or  3.Nf3  , trying to transpose into the Open Sicilian, which, of course, isn't something we can allow. Fortunately, we have an easy solution for both. Obviously, if you already play the Sicilian with Black and have some solutions ready, feel free to skip this chapter. }
3. c3
{ White is tempting us to take the pawn, which will yield a lead in development and easy play. Although taking is very good, I prefer to decline the sacrifice, and that is for a few reasons. Why give the opponents the type of position they want? My move order also allows us to neutralize  3.Nf3  , and if we were to accept the sacrifice, we would need to memorize more. }
3... e5 4. cxd4
{ 4.Nf3  Nc6  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/8/3pP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e5  4.c3  lines. }
4... exd4 5. Qxd4
{ This move is the only independent one, unlike Nf3, which is a transposition to what we cover elsewhere in the chapter. But it doesn't make much sense − why expose the queen so early?   5.Nf3  Nc6  6.Nxd4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Bb4  again transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/8/3pP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  e5  4.c3  lines. }
5... Nc6
{ Now, White just needs to waste time moving the queen around, so it is not surprising Black is rapidly taking over. }
6. Qd1 Nf6 { The e4-pawn is under attack. } 7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black is again threatening the e4-pawn! } 8. Bd3 d5
{ Having successfully gotten rid of the isolani, Black is enjoying the superior piece activity and a better position. Moving the queen clearly didn't work out for White. }
