[Black "2.e4 cxd4 3.Qxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. e4
{ All of a sudden, we are finding ourselves in the Sicilian Defense! More specifically, in the Smith-Morra Gambit, which has been rather popular with club players as of late. I never even thought White could play  2.e4  , until reading one of Dvoretsky's books.   The greatest coach of all time shows a game that he played versus some strong GM, where 1.d4 c5 was seen, and White started thinking, clearly not expecting this opening. Dvoretsky says 'With absolute horror, I realized White can go 2.e4, getting into the Sicilian. My opponent played both 1.d4 and 1.e4, while I didn't know much about the Sicilian. Luckily, he didn't do it.'  Fortunately for us, we won't need to learn the entire Sicilian Defense − just a few short lines will be more than enough! }
2... cxd4
{ Now, White is facing a choice, to either play  3.c3  , going for the Smith-Morra Gambit, or  3.Nf3  , trying to transpose into the Open Sicilian, which, of course, isn't something we can allow. Fortunately, we have an easy solution for both. Obviously, if you already play the Sicilian with Black and have some solutions ready, feel free to skip this chapter. }
3. Qxd4 { Taking on d4 is, of course, a pointless move. } 3... Nc6
{ White will just waste time moving the queen around. } 4. Qd1 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ Black is ready to play ...Bb4, developing fast and putting pressure on the e4-pawn, or ...d7-d5, opening up the center. }
6. Nf3 Bb4 7. Bd3
{ Here, most people went  7...d5  , which is logical, but in my opinion, not that great. Instead, I'd like to recommend a better and more ambitious path. }
7... Bxc3+
{ 7...d5  is, surprisingly, not as good, as after  8.O-O!  Bxc3  , White has an intermediate move:  9.exd5!  Nxd5  10.bxc3  . The structure is ugly and White is sacrificing a pawn, but in return,  White gets the bishop pair. In particular, the unopposed dark-squared bishop will be very strong on the a3-f8 or a1-h8 diagonals.  10...Nxc3?  11.Qe1  Nd5  12.Ba3±  and White's initiative is incredibly powerful! 1-0 Stocek-Karavaeva, chess.com 2021. }
8. bxc3 e5
{ With this move, we take control of the d4 and f4-squares, while also increasing the scope of our c8-bishop. }
9. O-O d6
{ The pawn on d6 seems a bit backward, but it cannot really be attacked. Next, we will castle, go ...h7-h6, ...Be6, and start attacking the weak queenside. Specifically, it is very easy to put pressure on the c-pawns with ...Rc8 and ...Qa5, on the a2-pawn with ...Be6 and ...Qa5, and to take advantage of the c4-square with ...Na5-c4. White has the bishop pair, but the position is closed, so White has no way of using it. Black is taking over. }
