1. d4 c5 2. e4
{ All of a sudden, we are finding ourselves in the Sicilian Defense! More specifically, in the Smith-Morra Gambit, which has been rather popular with club players as of late. I never even thought White could play  2.e4  , until reading one of Dvoretsky's books.   The greatest coach of all time shows a game that he played versus some strong GM, where 1.d4 c5 was seen, and White started thinking, clearly not expecting this opening. Dvoretsky says 'With absolute horror, I realized White can go 2.e4, getting into the Sicilian. My opponent played both 1.d4 and 1.e4, while I didn't know much about the Sicilian. Luckily, he didn't do it.'  Fortunately for us, we won't need to learn the entire Sicilian Defense − just a few short lines will be more than enough! }
2... cxd4
{ Now, White is facing a choice, to either play  3.c3  , going for the Smith-Morra Gambit, or  3.Nf3  , trying to transpose into the Open Sicilian, which, of course, isn't something we can allow. Fortunately, we have an easy solution for both. Obviously, if you already play the Sicilian with Black and have some solutions ready, feel free to skip this chapter. }
3. Nf3
{ White is trying to take the d4-pawn. If that will happen, the game will transpose into the Open Sicilian, which is an unacceptable outcome to anyone who is not a Sicilian player. }
3... e5
{ Luckily, there is an easy solution. We are protecting the d4-pawn thanks to a nice tactical trick. }
4. Bc4
{ Some players also tried focusing on development. However, it doesn't look as though it is possible to keep delaying c2-c3 infinitely.   4.Nxe5??  is, of course, impossible, as after  4...Qa5+  , Black wins the knight. }
4... Nc6 5. c3
{ Again, undermining the d4-pawn seems to be White's only reasonable continuation. And, as always, we are happy to focus on development. }
5... Nf6 6. Ng5
{ Trying to attack the weak f7-square is a logical choice. Fortunately, we can easily defend it. }
6... d5 7. exd5 Na5
{ Just like in the Fried Liver Attack, it is beneficial to keep the white d5-pawn alive, as it is blocking the a2-g8 diagonal. Instead, Black is attacking the opponent's bishop.   7...Nxd5  8.Nxf7  Kxf7  9.Qf3+  leads to White getting a ton of compensation, just like in the Fried Liver Attack. }
8. Bb5+ { 8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Bb5  will transpose. } 8... Bd7
{ Black is hoping to trade the bishops, which would completely deprive White of any hopes to create some threats. In that event, the knight on g5 would look rather foolish too. Of course, taking on d7, helping Black develop the queen, doesn't seem particularly prudent. }
9. Qa4 { Therefore, White gets the queen out. } 9... Be7
{ Black just keeps developing. Keep it simple!  9...Bxb5??  is a huge blunder, as after  10.Qxb5+  Nd7  11.b4+-  , the knight  on a5 gets trapped and lost. }
10. cxd4 O-O
{ Black can easily ignore the pawns for now. Once we have castled, our pieces are all ready to fight!  10...exd4  is also possible, but focusing on development seems even better. }
11. dxe5 Bxb5 12. Qxb5 Qxd5 13. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ Black is a pawn down but clearly enjoys tremendous compensation thanks to the considerable lead in development. For example, right now, there is a threat of ...Nb4, looking to come to c2 and trap the white rook, or to d3, disrupting White's development. }
14. Nf3
{ 14.a3??  Nb3  loses on the spot, of course, while the natural @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp2bppp/8/n2nP1N1/8/8/PP3PPP/RNB1K2R w KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.O-O  can simply be met by centralizing our rooks with ...Rac8 and ...Rfd8,  or even with  14...Bxg5  15.Bxg5  Rfe8  16.f4  Ne3  17.Rc1  Nf5  ,  when the bishop on g5 has a problem due to the incoming ...h6. Black has a fine endgame. }
14... Nb4
{ It's nice to force White's queenside knight to go into a very awkward position. }
15. Na3 Rad8 16. O-O Nd3
{ Black can take on a3 next, spoiling White's structure, and then simply follow up with ...Rfe8 and ...Rd5, winning the sacrificed pawn back. It is clear that the compensation is at least more than sufficient for equality, and at most, White has to be really careful to finish development! }
