{ White can try keeping the queens on this way. However, that only causes problems. }
9... Ng4 10. O-O
{ If White tries to eliminate any kingside dangers with  10.h3  , Black has  10...Ne5  11.Be2  Qxd1+  12.Kxd1  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Be6  followed by ...O-O-O, which is just an example of how we can liquidate into an even endgame. Since Black has equally good options along the way, we can rest assured that we're doing fine in the ending. }
10... Qc7 11. g3 Ne5
{ With ...Bh3 coming, or ...Bg4 and ...Nf3+, or ...O-O and ...Rd8, or the simple ...Nxd3, getting the bishop pair, Black is already clearly taking over. }
