[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 1.d4 c5 2.e4"]
[Black "2.e4 cxd4 3.Nf3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. e4
{ All of a sudden, we are finding ourselves in the Sicilian Defense! More specifically, in the Smith-Morra Gambit, which has been rather popular with club players as of late. I never even thought White could play  2.e4  , until reading one of Dvoretsky's books.   The greatest coach of all time shows a game that he played versus some strong GM, where 1.d4 c5 was seen, and White started thinking, clearly not expecting this opening. Dvoretsky says 'With absolute horror, I realized White can go 2.e4, getting into the Sicilian. My opponent played both 1.d4 and 1.e4, while I didn't know much about the Sicilian. Luckily, he didn't do it.'  Fortunately for us, we won't need to learn the entire Sicilian Defense − just a few short lines will be more than enough! }
2... cxd4
{ Now, White is facing a choice, to either play  3.c3  , going for the Smith-Morra Gambit, or  3.Nf3  , trying to transpose into the Open Sicilian, which, of course, isn't something we can allow. Fortunately, we have an easy solution for both. Obviously, if you already play the Sicilian with Black and have some solutions ready, feel free to skip this chapter. }
3. Nf3
{ White is trying to take the d4-pawn. If that will happen, the game will transpose into the Open Sicilian, which is an unacceptable outcome to anyone who is not a Sicilian player. }
3... e5
{ Luckily, there is an easy solution. We are protecting the d4-pawn thanks to a nice tactical trick. }
4. c3
{ Undermining the pawn, hoping Black would accept the gambit, is the most logical way to play.  4.Nxe5??  is, of course, impossible, as after  4...Qa5+  , Black wins the knight. }
4... Nc6
{ However, to my tremendous delight, I have discovered that returning the pawn in this simple way leads to easy equality. }
5. cxd4 exd4
{ Black has an isolani, which might seem undesirable, but that's totally okay, as we are about to follow up with ...Nf6, putting pressure on the e4-pawn, and then ...Bb4, adding even more pressure, or ....d7-d5, opening up and liquidating the center entirely. }
6. Nxd4 Nf6
{ It is strong, but also very natural, to develop fast and immediately put pressure on the opponent's center! }
7. Nc3
{ 7.Nxc6  is a transposition to the line we will see a move later. Actually, Black has an extra option:  7...dxc6  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8=  9.Nc3  Bb4  . Instead,  9...Bc5⩱  can be played as well.  Black can also try to benefit from not having moved the bishop yet. It's no longer needed badly on b4, so developing it elsewhere, for example, to this wonderful diagonal, is even better. }
7... Bb4
{ Now, the e4-pawn is hanging, which forces White to take some action. } 8.
Nxc6
{ White has to trade a pair of knights so that after ...bxc6 Bd3, the e4-pawn can be protected without leaving the knight on d4 hanging.   8.f3?  just allows Black to destroy the center in no time.  8...d5∓  and White's center is crumbling. }
8... dxc6
{ 8...bxc6  9.Bd3  d5  is also very good, but it is more to my taste to swap the queens whenever beneficially possible. White doesn't have a reasonable alternative to the queen trade. }
9. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ In this position, Black's king is perfectly safe in the center as multiple games of strong GMs like Swiercz, Muzychuk, and many others show. It can comfortably sit on e7 or c7. Importantly, the c6-pawn is in a great spot, as it is restricting the white knight from ever coming to d5 or b5. Now, the e4-pawn is hanging, so White needs to do something about that. }
10. Bg5
{ This move develops a bishop, prepares Queenside castling, and pins our knight, preventing us from taking the e4-pawn. It also creates a threat of e4-e5, which would take advantage of the pinned knight. }
10... h6
{ We are kicking the bishop away. Of course, if White were to capture on f6, getting the bishop pair and a semi-open g-file would be a huge positional gift to us. }
11. Bxf6+ { A gross positional error. } 11... gxf6 12. O-O-O+ Ke7
{ Black can always undouble the pawns with ...f6-f5 if we want to. White has no control of the dark squares whatsoever. Next, Black can proceed with ...Rg8 and ...h6-h5-h4, developing more pressure on the kingside as in 0-1 Kokai-Markovic, Senta 2011. }
*

