11. O-O-O+ Ke7
{ The king is very comfortable here.  11...Kc7?  In some positions, having the  king on c7 would be totally okay. However, not here, because after  12.Bf4+  , it has to keep running around since  playing ...Bd6 isn't possible. Therefore, Black should avoid this. }
12. Bh4 g5
{ Grabbing space while also winning time − what could be more appealing? } 13.
Bg3 Be6
{ Black continues developing the pieces. This move also creates a threat of winning the e4-pawn, which wasn't possible a move ago due to problems on the e-file, as the clickable variation below shows.   13...Bxc3?  14.bxc3  Nxe4??  isn't possible yet, of course, as after  15.Re1  f5  16.f3+-  , White just wins a piece. }
14. f3 { White needs to defend the pawn. } 14... Bc5
{ I really like this logical novelty. Black's bishop was no longer doing anything useful on b4, so it was time for it to leave. Now, Black has numerous great positional ideas, such as:  ...Nh5-f4, activating the knight; ...b7-b5, grabbing space on the queenside and restricting White further; ...Nd7-b6, aiming to jump to c4 with the knight; ...Be3+ and ...c6-c5-c4 as a follow-up to ...b7-b5, taking more space on the queenside and restricting White's pieces even more.  
Black also has an extra queenside pawn, which is a useful thing in the endgames. So, trading rooks could be rather useful too. All in all, Black is already taking over! }
