1. d4 c5 2. Bf4
{ One huge upside of the Old Benoni, which starts exactly with 1.d4 c5, is that the London fans are deprived of their favorite opening! Of course, White can develop the bishop to this square here as well, but it's a really silly idea. }
2... cxd4
{ Black is about to play  3.--  e5  and hold on to the extra pawn due to the typical nuance  4.Bxe5?  Qa5+  , winning the bishop. }
3. Qxd4
{ Taking on d4 is better than the alternatives, as at least White is not left a pawn down for nothing, but still doesn't make sense.   3.Nf3?  d6∓  and with ...e7-e5 inevitably coming next, Black is just going to be a pawn up. What a disaster of an opening for White! }
3... Nc6 4. Qd1 e5 5. Bg3 d5
{ Black owns the entire center and is dominating the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 c5 2.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. e3
{ White can also keep the tension in a passive way. This move looks harmless, to put it nicely, but it actually creates a bit of a problem for us, the Old Benoni players. This is because our typical setup involves keeping the knight on g8 and going ...Be7-g5.   If we go  2...Nf6  now, White can play  3.d5  at some point, transposing into the typical Benoni positions a tempo down.  Their reasoning is that the Benoni is a risky opening, so playing against it could be tempting even a tempo down.  In fact, Swedish GM Axel Smith even wrote a book with a chapter on this line that he named 'The Poor Man's Benoni!'.  However, although this variation did experience a bit of popularity, I think Black is comfortable. You just need to know a few ideas from the regular Benoni positions that I am about to show. }
2... Nf6
{ This move allows us to stay as flexible as possible.  2...d5  is the most solid reply but after  3.c4  ,  the arising positions have nothing to do with the Benoni, although obviously having played e2-e3, White isn't going for some principled opening line. }
3. Nf3 g6
{ White can choose to just go c2-c3 or something like that.  Obviously, that is not dangerous, so I will focus on covering the most principled continuation − taking space in the center. }
4. Be2 { Let's see one example of White not playing principled chess. } 4...
Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4
{ Here, the easiest solution is to give White an IQP in the best possible version from our standpoint. }
6... cxd4 7. exd4 d5
{ Next we just go ...Nc6, ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Rc8, etc. The key thing about isolated pawns is that since they are statically weak, they require active dynamic play to make up for that.  Typically in such positions, White would go Bd3-c2, Qd3, and attack the black king. However, here our bishop is fianchettoed, and therefore our king is much safer, so this version of an IQP is not appealing for White at all. Obviously, things can always be discussed in more detail, but I think this would be enough! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 c5 2.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. e3
{ White can also keep the tension in a passive way. This move looks harmless, to put it nicely, but it actually creates a bit of a problem for us, the Old Benoni players. This is because our typical setup involves keeping the knight on g8 and going ...Be7-g5.   If we go  2...Nf6  now, White can play  3.d5  at some point, transposing into the typical Benoni positions a tempo down.  Their reasoning is that the Benoni is a risky opening, so playing against it could be tempting even a tempo down.  In fact, Swedish GM Axel Smith even wrote a book with a chapter on this line that he named 'The Poor Man's Benoni!'.  However, although this variation did experience a bit of popularity, I think Black is comfortable. You just need to know a few ideas from the regular Benoni positions that I am about to show. }
2... Nf6
{ This move allows us to stay as flexible as possible.  2...d5  is the most solid reply but after  3.c4  ,  the arising positions have nothing to do with the Benoni, although obviously having played e2-e3, White isn't going for some principled opening line. }
3. Nf3 g6
{ White can choose to just go c2-c3 or something like that.  Obviously, that is not dangerous, so I will focus on covering the most principled continuation − taking space in the center. }
4. d5
{ We are getting a typical Benoni position, where using our standard ...Be7-g5 plan is no longer possible. Okay, let's make a few developing moves first. }
4... Bg7 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3
{ White is taking space in the center, preparing to also go e3-e4. } 6... d6 7.
Be2
{ Here, you can choose between two plans: the more concrete one and the more positional one, which does not create an immediate conflict. }
7... e6
{ This is the more concrete way of playing. Black is looking to undermine the center by exchanging on d5.   7...Na6  is the slower plan. Black gets the knight  out to c7 to prepare the ...b7-b5 pawn break.  8.O-O  Nc7  9.e4  Bg4  and now  Black trades off the bishop. It is really important to do so for several reasons:  Black has less space overall, so trades help. This bishop won't have any future on c8 or, say, b7. Now Black can go ...Nd7, opening up the g7-bishop without blocking in the light-squared one. The white knight could help prepare the annoying e4-e5 push.    10.h3  Bxf3  11.Bxf3  a6  .  Later, Black can try to push ...b7-b5, play ...e7-e6, undermining the center, or even ...e7-e5, closing the position down. Black went on to win a really interesting game in Rosner-Fridman, Magdeburg 2022! }
8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5
{ We got a rather imbalanced pawn structure, so let's talk about the typical plans and ideas.  ♟ White has an extra pawn in the center, therefore a typical plan could be related to advancing the e-pawn. That could be done by:  e4-e5, creating a passed pawn on the d-file; e3-e4, f2-f4, and then e4-e5, hoping to take with the f-pawn and get a powerful central pair.  
♟ White can put pressure on the d6-pawn with e3-e4, Bf4, and Nd2-c4. Black, on the other hand, should:   try to push ...b7-b5 to grab space on the queenside, where there is an extra pawn; trade pieces by going ...Bg4 followed by ...Bxf3; sometimes go ...c5-c4 and ...Nc5 if possible.  
It's very important for Black to not thoughtlessly play ...a7-a6 because after White responds with a2-a4, Black will no longer have an option of going ...Na6-c7. We will talk more about the importance of this idea in the chapter on typical plans and structures.  To my mind, the ideal setup for Black in this position involves going ...Na6-c7, then ...Bg4, exchanging on f3, and ...Nf6-d7. This way Black can prepare ...b7-b5, open up the g7-bishop, and if needed, jump to e5 with the knight. That would help shield the d6-pawn from Bf4 ideas, for instance. }
9... Bg4 { Black follows the aforementioned plan. } 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3
{ Here two continuations are good. } 11... Na6
{ Black is looking to either play ...c5-c4 and ...Nc5, or ...Nc7, putting pressure on the d5-pawn and preparing ...b7-b5. }
12. e4 { White takes more space and opens up the c1-bishop. } 12... Re8 13. Bf4
c4 { With ...Nc5-d3 coming next, Black is clearly doing great. } *

