[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 c5 2.dxc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. dxc5
{ Sometimes, White would simply capture the pawn. It's hanging, right? So why not? This move could be especially popular with the 'conservative' 1.d4 players, who like the setups where c2-c4 is delayed or avoided altogether.   They would be afraid to play  2.d5  , which reaches a complex position, and would consider moves like  2.c3  or  2.e3  to be too modest. So, they would just take. }
2... e6
{ Luckily, winning back the c5-pawn while also getting a great position won't be difficult at all. }
3. Nf3
{ This developing move allows Black to get the pawn right away. Of course, by playing this way, White cannot fight for any advantage. }
3... Bxc5 4. e3 Nf6
{ Both parties are about to make some logical developing moves. White isn't forced to play c2-c4, but I think it makes sense to do so at some point to fight for the center. If White completely foregoes this move, then Black would go ...d7-d5 and eventually ...Nc6 and ...e6-e5. }
5. c4 O-O 6. a3
{ Since the c1-bishop is blocked by the e3-pawn, it makes sense to prepare to play b2-b4, expanding on the queenside, and looking to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. }
6... b6
{ Black could also prevent the space grab with ...a7-a5, but I see no harm in allowing White to do that.  Furthermore, I would prefer to not weaken the b5-square, because then Nc3-b5 would be rather annoying. }
7. b4 Be7 8. Bb2
{ Here, Black has two good choices: either push ...d7-d5, opening up the center, liquidating the pawns, and getting a boring equal position @@StartBracket@@which is not a bad opening outcome by any means!@@EndBracket@@, or keep the tension and delay or forego the ...d7-d5 move altogether. }
8... a5
{ If you want to play for a win, this is the way. We are making White push the b-pawn forward, which would permanently weaken the c5-square.  8...d5  would lead to simplifications and dry equality. }
9. b5 d6
{ We are happy to have a bit less space in exchange for an outpost on c5. } 10.
Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7
{ Next, Black would install the knight on c5, play ...Rc8, and so on. With an outpost on c5, a powerful light-squared bishop, and great control of the e5-square, we seem to be for choice here. Black went on to win the game in Beeke-Thesing, Vlissingen 2012. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 c5 2.dxc5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. dxc5
{ Sometimes, White would simply capture the pawn. It's hanging, right? So why not? This move could be especially popular with the 'conservative' 1.d4 players, who like the setups where c2-c4 is delayed or avoided altogether.   They would be afraid to play  2.d5  , which reaches a complex position, and would consider moves like  2.c3  or  2.e3  to be too modest. So, they would just take. }
2... e6
{ Luckily, winning back the c5-pawn while also getting a great position won't be difficult at all. }
3. Nc3
{ Interestingly enough, although the move 2.dxc5 seems silly, this variation actually forces us to be somewhat accurate since the d6-square is weak and White is hurrying to play Ne4-d6! }
3... Bxc5 4. e4
{ Now, the position looks like some weird Sicilian, but Black clearly got some extra tempi − typically, Black would capture ...cxd4, which activates White's kingside knight. Here, instead, Black already got the bishop out, while White's kingside pieces are still asleep! }
4... Nc6 { We are just focusing on quick development. } 5. Nf3 Nf6
{ Next, Black can consider either playing for the quick ...d7-d5, which I like a bit less, or pursuing a slightly different plan that we are about to discover. }
6. Bd3 a6
{ This move covers up the b5-square. It's important to do so for two reasons: to potentially expand with ...b7-b5, and to play ...Qc7 safely without ever getting harassed with Nb5.   6...d5  is also possible, but I like this move less as it nearly forces an IQP.  7.exd5  exd5  with a decent position, but Black doesn't need to damage the pawn structure.  7...Nxd5?  trying to avoid an isolated pawn is a bad idea, as it gives White a huge lead in development:  8.Nxd5  Qxd5  9.Qe2±  . Be sure to avoid such positions!! }
7. O-O Qc7
{ Surprisingly, White might have some problems on the kingside because of ideas like ...Ng4! And, it is not entirely obvious how White should be developing the pieces. Let's look at a sample continuation. }
8. Bg5
{ 8.Qe2?  is an example of how quickly things can go really wrong for White.  8...Ng4!  9.h3??  Nd4!  -+ and just like in the famous Siberian trap of the Smith-Morra Gambit, Black wins on the spot! }
8... b5
{ Black is expanding, getting ready to develop the bishop to the long diagonal, which would exert even more pressure on the white king. If White were to ever take on f6, that would not only concede the bishop pair but also open up the g-file for our rook. Of course, Black's king would be happy to stay in the center. }
9. a3
{ It seems logical to stop any future possibilities of ...b5-b4 since that move could endanger the e4-pawn if White was not careful. }
9... Bb7
{ Next, Black would like to go ...Ng4 to either threaten this tactical trick ...Nd4!, distracting the f3-knight from protecting the h2-pawn, which we had seen in an earlier clickable variation, or to reroute it to e5. It's not obvious to me at all how White should be developing. }
10. Qd2 Ng4
{ The threat is ...Nd4, distracting the knight and checkmating White on h2. }
11. Bf4
{ White must do something about the h2-b8 diagonal and threats to the king, so this move is sort of forced.   11.h3??  is a massive blunder due to a gorgeous tactic.  11...Nd4!!  12.hxg4  . Wait,  but there is no mating threat on h2 now? Didn't Black just blunder?  12...Nxf3+  13.gxf3  Qg3+!!  No! We will checkmate White in an amazing manner!  14.Kh1  Qh3+!  15.Kg1  h5!  It's unbelievable, but White cannot  stop ...hxg4 followed by checkmate on h2 or h1! }
11... Nce5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5
{ Black has two amazing bishops and a wonderful knight in the center. Next, we will proceed with ...O-O, ...Rac8, and ...d7-d6, finishing development and ending up with the much more active pieces. Black is already clearly taking over. }
