1. d4 c5 2. dxc5
{ Sometimes, White would simply capture the pawn. It's hanging, right? So why not? This move could be especially popular with the 'conservative' 1.d4 players, who like the setups where c2-c4 is delayed or avoided altogether.   They would be afraid to play  2.d5  , which reaches a complex position, and would consider moves like  2.c3  or  2.e3  to be too modest. So, they would just take. }
2... e6
{ Luckily, winning back the c5-pawn while also getting a great position won't be difficult at all. }
3. Nc3
{ Interestingly enough, although the move 2.dxc5 seems silly, this variation actually forces us to be somewhat accurate since the d6-square is weak and White is hurrying to play Ne4-d6! }
3... Bxc5 4. Ne4
{ To my mind, this is the only somewhat challenging move. White is attacking the bishop while also targeting the weak d6-square. }
4... Nf6
{ Black should give up the bishop pair and prioritize development − it would be more than worth it. }
5. Nxc5 Qa5+ { Of course, we did not just blunder a bishop! } 6. c3 Qxc5 7. Nf3
d5
{ After a few natural moves, White is facing a dilemma: should White develop fast by playing e2-e3 at a cost of locking up the dark-squared bishop, or first get it out? }
8. e3
{ A very passive approach. Sure enough, White has the bishops but is behind in development, and now Black will get a wonderful position by taking the center. }
8... O-O { First, we castle. } 9. Be2 Re8
{ Then, we get another piece in the game, preparing to push the other central pawn. }
10. O-O e5
{ Now, the light-squared bishop will enjoy the open diagonal, the queenside knight will come out to c6, and the other rook will join the game via d8 or c8. I think Black is already clearly taking over. }
