[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Bf4
{ This is an attempt to get a London setup. But, fortunately, there is a reason knowledgeable people who play the London start with e2-e3, not c2-c3. }
3... Qb6 { Now, the b2-pawn is immediately in danger! } 4. Qb3 Qxb3
{ We go for the queen trade, as that will yield us a favorable structure. } 5.
axb3 cxd4
{ Taking on d4 allows us to develop with tempo on the next move and it emphasizes the weakness of the doubled pawns on the b-file. }
6. cxd4
{ White ends up with weak b-pawns, and we get an outpost on b4, which our knight will greatly enjoy. The semi-open a-file is not an issue since there is nothing White can attack on it. }
6... Nc6
{ Black is immediately getting the initiative by attacking the d4-pawn. } 7. e3
Nb4 { White has to make more clumsy moves. } 8. Kd1 d6
{ Paving the way for the c8-bishop while obstructing the opponent's bishop on f4. }
9. Nc3 Bd7
{ Next, Black will go ...a7-a6 to free up the rook on a8, then ...Rc8, ...e7-e6, and the dark-squared bishop will likely go to e7. Interestingly enough, Black might want to wait a bit with the move ...d6-d5 − there is nothing wrong with that move, but we could use the d5-square for the knights!   However, of course, keeping the pawn on e7 and playing ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 is perfectly reasonable as well! Or maybe even somehow ...h7-h5 and ...g7-g5, grabbing space on the kingside, if possible. With a wonderful outpost on b4 and White's king so misplaced on d1, Black is clearly better. }
