[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 c5 2.c3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Nf3
{ White keeps the tension. In this position, Black needs to make a decision: do we want a more complicated position or simple equality? }
3... Qc7
{ I like this move a lot since it not only keeps the tension in the center but also prevents Bf4, making the London System enthusiasts rather unhappy! Importantly, this idea has been championed by Vachier-Lagrave, who used it to beat Aronian, among others. Now, White is facing a tricky choice: develop the bishop to g5, lock it up with e2-e3, or play g2-g3, looking to fianchetto the kingside bishop? }
4. d5
{ This somewhat principled-looking move has been only seen in two games! There has to be a reason why no one plays this way, right? Let's find out what it is.  From White's point of view, playing the typical Benoni structure would not seem that unreasonable. Sure enough, White wasted a tempo playing c2-c3 and then supposedly c3-c4, but Black also made a somewhat useless move ...Qc7, right?  Well, not really! }
4... a6
{ We want to expand on the queenside with ...b7-b5 and attack the d5-pawn with ...Bb7. White needs to prevent that! }
5. a4 d6 6. c4
{ White seems to be ready to build the center with Nc3 and e2-e4. } 6... e5 7.
Nc3
{ Next, White will play e2-e4, getting the center under control, right? Not exactly... }
7... e4
{ Make sure to remember this move, as it is absolutely crucial when it comes to preventing White's plan and making the pieces wander around without a goal. }
8. Nd2 e3
{ Black is very excited to sacrifice a pawn. What does this sacrifice accomplish? It blocks in White's queenside pieces and creates a gorgeous outpost on e5 for the black knight or some other pieces, as White will never be able to kick it out with f2-f4.   8...Bf5?!  seems bad, as after  9.Qc2  Qe7  10.f3  , the bishop  on f5 is rather misplaced and White wins a pawn under much better circumstances. }
9. fxe3 Qe7
{ This move helps put pressure on the e3-pawn and control the e4 and e5-squares better. }
10. e4 Nbd7
{ It's not obvious how White should be developing the pieces! The most logical thing to do seems to be fianchettoing the light-squared bishop. }
11. g3 g6 12. Bg2 Bg7
{ However, Black clearly has terrific compensation for the missing pawn. We enjoy a wonderful outpost on e5, pressure on the e4-pawn, and numerous dark-square weaknesses in the opponent's position, such as the squares e4, d4, f2, and so on.  Next, Black will just castle, play ...Ne5, and start considering ideas like ...Bd7 and ...b7-b5, or maybe ...h7-h5-h4 to weaken the white king's position even more. }
