2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Nf3
{ White keeps the tension. In this position, Black needs to make a decision: do we want a more complicated position or simple equality? }
3... Qc7
{ I like this move a lot since it not only keeps the tension in the center but also prevents Bf4, making the London System enthusiasts rather unhappy! Importantly, this idea has been championed by Vachier-Lagrave, who used it to beat Aronian, among others. Now, White is facing a tricky choice: develop the bishop to g5, lock it up with e2-e3, or play g2-g3, looking to fianchetto the kingside bishop? }
