1. d4 c5 2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Nf3
{ White keeps the tension. In this position, Black needs to make a decision: do we want a more complicated position or simple equality? }
3... Qc7
{ I like this move a lot since it not only keeps the tension in the center but also prevents Bf4, making the London System enthusiasts rather unhappy! Importantly, this idea has been championed by Vachier-Lagrave, who used it to beat Aronian, among others. Now, White is facing a tricky choice: develop the bishop to g5, lock it up with e2-e3, or play g2-g3, looking to fianchetto the kingside bishop? }
4. e3
{ This move is certainly possible, but it is very unambitious. Why would anyone want to lock up the c1-bishop? }
4... d5
{ First, we grab space in the center, preventing any possibilities of d4-d5. We aren't really afraid of White pushing that pawn, but taking the center means we are already playing for advantage! }
5. Bd3 g6
{ Since White might want to create some Stonewall-type setup with Ne5 and f2-f4, it makes sense to fianchetto our bishop. This way, the black king would feel the safest, because the g7-bishop would be a great defender, and because the d3-bishop is now blocked by our pawns. }
6. O-O Bg7
{ You don't need to know anything beyond this, but let me show you one more idea. }
7. Nbd2 O-O
{ Both parties are finishing their development. At this point, it is not obvious what to do with White, so trying to build a Stonewall setup could be an idea. }
8. Ne5 Nc6 9. f4
{ And here comes our point. White's c1-bishop is very restricted, while the one on d3 is a lot better. So... let's trade it off! }
9... Bf5 10. Bxf5 gxf5
{ Black's pawn structure is perfectly solid, and now White has very little ability to control the light squares. Next, we can go ...e7-e6 to reinforce the pawns, and start considering queenside expansion with ...Rb8, ...b7-b5-b4, etc. }
