1. d4 c5 2. c3
{ This move is rather modest, but it is actually a bit annoying since it keeps White's position flexible. White can try to:   go Bf4 and get some kind of a London System; take the c5-pawn and hold on to it; develop with e2-e3, which isn't an ambitious setup, but probably won't get White in trouble.  
So, I would like to offer two reactions: the easy and solid one, and the more ambitious and unexplored one as well. }
2... Nf6 { For now, we keep the tension in the center. } 3. Nf3
{ White keeps the tension. In this position, Black needs to make a decision: do we want a more complicated position or simple equality? }
3... cxd4
{ The way to equality. After this trade, we get to the Exchange Slav territory. Although this is a rather dangerous opening overall, it is not in this case since White already developed the knight to f3, giving up the most ambitious setups. }
4. cxd4 d5 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ I will just annotate this variation briefly, as it is an alternative. } 6.
Bf4
{ White can also try other moves like  6.e3  , but that locks up the bishop. Now, Black has to be on a bit of a lookout  for the Nb5-c7 ideas. It's easy to prevent this threat by, for example, developing the light-squared bishop and following up with ...Rc8. But, I prefer a different path. }
6... a6
{ This move achieves several highly important goals:  it covers up the b5-square so there is no Nb5-c7; it covers up the b5-square so Bb5, pinning the knight, won't ever bother us; it prepares ...b7-b5, which will allow us to grab space on the queenside. Also, if White ever goes Qb3, we meet it with ...Na5 and if White gives a check Qa4+, it's nice to be able to play ...b7-b5.  
In this position, to do really well, Black simply needs to make sure the light-squared bishop doesn't end up stuck inside the pawn chain. Developing or even trading it off, even for a knight on f3, is totally fine. }
7. e3 Bg4
{ Black is ready to play ...e7-e6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O. If needed, we can always take on f3. At no point does the move Qb3, aimed at attacking the queenside and taking advantage of the fact the b7-pawn is loose bother us since we can always go ...Na5 or ...b7-b5 − that's when the move ...a7-a6 will prove so useful. }
8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Bxf3
{ White's bishop won't be doing much on f3. This way, we prevent any Ne5 ideas and immediately trade off more pieces. }
10. Bxf3 Bd6 { More trades coming our way. } 11. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ The only part of the board which could see some action is the queenside − in particular, the c-file. If one of the players gets lazy or ignorant and allows the opponent to take control of that file, they would be in trouble. Fortunately, that's easy to avoid. }
12. Rc1 O-O 13. Na4
{ White wants to invade on c5 with the knight. That would be rather annoying, as the b7-pawn would find itself under lots of pressure. }
13... Nd7 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. Rxc5
{ Taking with the pawn wouldn't have made sense, as doing that would give Black an extra pawn in the center. }
15... b6 { Time to kick out the rook. } 16. Rc3 Rfc8
{ Next, Black can go ...Ne7 and trade off the rooks on the c-file. The game is headed towards a clear draw, even though out of 6 games that arrived at this position, Black drew 4 and won 2!  Of course, the Exchange Slav @@StartBracket@@even this harmless line with Nf3!@@EndBracket@@ has more nuances to it. However, I thought this would be a good and concise display of how to get a comfortable position here and what to be careful about. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Main Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Christoph Karner − Jan Suran, Ceske Budejovice 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. c4 d6 4. e4 Be7
{ Black is getting ready to carry out the main plan − trading the dark-squared bishops via g5 to get rid of the worst minor piece and decrease White's spatial advantage. A reminder: what is the difference between spatial advantage and having more space?  Spatial advantage is when you have more space and the opponent is restricted. More space is just more space − the opponent doesn't have a problem. Since Black has less space here, we understand that by getting rid of some minor pieces, we will create more room for the remaining pieces, so none of them feel restricted. }
5. Nf3 { With this move, White prevents the bishop trade on g5. } 5... Bg4
{ Black keeps insisting! The goal is to take the knight on f3 and go ...Bg5 anyway. }
6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Bg5 { As planned, the bad bishop is coming off! } 8. Nc3
{ White just keeps developing and realizes there is no benefit in taking the bishop on g5 since there is no way to exploit the black queen's position on g5. So, White just gets the knight out. }
8... Bxc1 9. Rxc1 Nh6
{ This is an interesting move. On f6, the knight blocks the f-pawn. That's okay since Black doesn't need to push ...f7-f5 immediately. Some players develop the knight to e7 so the f-pawn isn't blocked, and sometimes later it goes to g6. But h6 is a bit of an unusual square. The position is closed, so time isn't that important. Black can go ...f7-f5, and then ...Nf7-g5 while also controlling the g4-square. }
10. O-O O-O
{ Okay, so both parties seem to have sort of finished their development. Now what? Black will try to play ...f7-f5. A few notes on that:  ♟ Playing ...f7-f5 without ...g7-g6 gives an extra option of exf5, when White is getting an outpost on e4. This is something we need to be careful about, but only when White has a knight! If we imagine that a pair of knights disappears, then we don't need to be afraid of giving White that square.  ♟ Trading a pair of knights is just good overall because White's bishop is pretty bad, so we will leave our opponent with a bad piece.  ♟ We can also go ...g7-g6 and then ...f7-f5, depriving White of that extra possibility. The only downside is that if we go ...f5-f4, ...g6-g5, etc, then the g-pawn would have spent an extra tempo. White, on the other hand, should probably try to play a2-a3 and b2-b4 and get play on the queenside, although it is not easy to succeed since we can simply play ...Nd7 and ...b7-b6. }
11. Qc2
{ I am not sure what is the point of this move! Is White overprotecting the e4-pawn? But it's already protected. Is White connecting the rooks? And what does that achieve? }
11... Nd7 12. a3
{ White is finally preparing b2-b4. Again, it's not a particularly dangerous idea for us to worry about! }
12... g6
{ Black figures there is no hurry, so it is better to play ...f7-f5 without allowing for exf5 in a situation where White's knight will get an outpost on e4. }
13. Qd2
{ Sure enough, this move wins a tempo by attacking the knight, but why is the queen moving around? }
13... Kg7 14. b4 Qe7
{ As we can see, Black can easily afford to just ignore the opponent's queenside ambitions. At least for now! }
15. Bd1
{ This is a very logical continuation. White realizes that the bishop is useless and is trying to improve it by bringing it over to b3 to overprotect the c4-pawn, or to a4! }
15... Rac8
{ Black is threatening to capture on b4 and win the unprotected c4-pawn. } 16.
Bb3 { So, White protects the pawn. } 16... f5
{ Black is about to start some very powerful play on the kingside without any effort. We will play ...f5-f4, ...g5-g4, ...Qh4, ...g4-g3, and so on. }
17. f4
{ White decides to dramatically prevent this scenario by pushing the f-pawn two squares up too, opening up the center! A small positional exercise: what to do with the black pieces? }
17... exf4 18. Qxf4 Ne5
{ Black doesn't find it! Black gets tempted by creating a threat of a fork with ...Nd3 but misses a great opportunity. Black is still doing very well, but it could be much better.   18...g5!  19.Qd2  f4∓  would have been the way to go. Black secures an outpost on e5, while also keeping the position closed! From there, it should be pretty easy. Black just needs to play ...g5-g4 and ...f4-f3, opening up the white king and checkmating it! }
19. bxc5 Rxc5
{ The threat of a fork on d3 is renewed.   19...dxc5!?  could have been a very interesting decision too, surprisingly. You would think, why would we give White a protected passed pawn? Because now we get an outpost on d6, and the other knight will jump in there via f7 in no time. The white bishop remains very bad, of course! }
20. exf5 Rxf5
{ Black wants to trade the rooks and queens and win the endgame with a good knight versus a bad light-squared bishop. Additionally, the c4-pawn is weak, and so are the dark squares. For example, if the board was emptier, Black could go ...Kf6-e5-d4, dramatically activating the king in no time! }
21. Qe4 Rc8
{ The rook looks great on c5, but Black finds out it's not very easy to win the c4-pawn. So, Black is trying to rediscover the purpose of the rook by bringing it on f8. }
22. Nb5 Rcf8 23. Rxf5
{ 23.Nxa7??  is too greedy. After  23...Nhg4!  ,  Black is about to slide the queen on h4 and checkmate the opponent! For instance, after  24.Nb5  Qh4!  25.h3  Rxf1+  26.Rxf1  Rxf1+  27.Kxf1  Qf2  ,  the white king rapidly discovers it's not fun being this weakened! }
23... Rxf5
{ I am not sure if this is the way to go.   23...Nxf5!  seems much more natural to me. The white king is weak, so why not try attacking it by playing ...Qg5 and ...Nh4, bringing all the pieces next to it? }
24. Re1 Nhf7
{ Black plays too passively. But it's understandable that he likely just overlooked the tactical opportunity!   24...Nhg4!  was an amazing attacking opportunity. Black has a huge threat of ...Qh4+, but this move seems to be losing a knight, doesn't it?  25.Qxg4??  looks like White is winning, but there is a counter-tactic.  25...Nf3+!  26.gxf3  Qxe1+  27.Kg2  Qe2+  28.Kg3  h5!  with a decisive attack. }
25. Nd4
{ Now, the white knight finally discovers a purpose − it is about to land on e6, which is not a disaster for Black, but definitely somewhat annoying. }
25... Rf6 26. h4
{ I am not entirely sure what is the purpose of the move. Is White just making room for the king? Because if he wants to play h4-h5, that would certainly weaken his own king much more than ours! }
26... Nh6
{ Black, unfortunately, is also losing the thread.  26...b6!  ,  it was important to first stabilize the d6-pawn to prevent the center from blowing up. }
27. c5
{ All of a sudden, the e5-knight is very unstable and Black is in trouble! }
27... Nhf7
{ Fortunately, Black can still sort of hold on.  27...dxc5??  Of course, the pawn isn't free. After  28.Ne6+  ,  White wins the e5-knight and the game. }
28. Ne6+ Kh8 29. cxd6
{ And White lets go of his advantage too.  29.c6!  was a much better move because this way, White would guarantee himself the creation of a powerful passed pawn. Crucially, White isn't worried about giving up two pieces for a rook.  29...bxc6  30.dxc6  30...Rxe6  31.c7!  The queen is too overworked. It cannot stop both the pawn and keep the e6-rook protected so after  31...Qxc7  32.Bxe6+-  ,  White's position is, of course, winning. }
29... Qxd6
{ Now, Black is doing just fine again because the d-pawn is very easy to block. }
30. Kh1 h6
{ Since the g7-square is unavailable to the king, Black figures it makes sense to make room for it on h7. }
31. Bc2
{ White wants to play h4-h5 and checkmate us on h7! We definitely don't need that to happen. }
31... h5 32. Ng5
{ The position was balanced, but White forgets about the safety of his king and gets punished right away. }
32... Ng4 { All of a sudden, checkmate on h2 is unstoppable! } 33. Nxf7+ Rxf7
{ White has a couple more checks, but there is no way to stop the mate on h2. }
34. Qd4+ Rf6 35. Re8+ Kg7 { The king is easily walking away. } 36. g3 Qxg3 37.
Re2 Qxh4+ 38. Kg1 Qg3+ 39. Kh1 Qh3+ 40. Kg1 Qf1#
{ And White got mated. Although the final part of the game got very messy and both sides definitely had their chances, I think the opening of this game is something we should definitely learn from! Black traded the bad bishop and another piece of pieces, didn't get into any dynamic trouble, and once that happened, his kingside play started unfolding very effortlessly! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Main Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Guillaume Vine − Romain Edouard, Cappelle Online Blitz 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ In this game, we will learn how the quick ...f7-f5 break helped Black free up his position. Then, the structure shortly became symmetrical and White lost material because of the poor piece coordination. }
1... c5
{ This is a blitz game, but it is still very instructive to see how the strong French GM, who was the second of Veselin Topalov at some point, used our slightly offbeat opening to outplay the weaker opponent in a very simple way. }
2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6
{ As we discuss in the theoretical chapters and the other chapter on model games, it is better for White to forego the move c2-c4 altogether in order to keep that square available for the knight and to keep the option of Bb5+ open. However, doing that is unnatural since in most mainstream 1.d4 openings, the pawn wants to go to c4, so White, naturally, makes that move too. }
4. c4
{ 4.Nc3  is the most problematic setup, and we discuss several model games that featured it in another chapter. }
4... Be7
{ Black is trying to trade off the bad bishop, which is the standard idea. } 5.
Nc3
{ 5.Nf3  is another common way to play. White is not only developing a piece but is also stopping the trade. Typically, we would insist on  5...Bg4  looking to trade off the knight and go ...Bg5 next. }
5... Bg5
{ The bad bishop is coming off the board. This is very valuable for Black for several reasons. This bishop is our worst minor piece, as all the central pawns are on the dark squares. Also, Black has less space overall. The goal is to leave White with a 'bad' minor piece, the bishop on f1, which is severely limited by the central pawns. }
6. Nf3
{ White just keeps developing. He has more space and the game is just beginning, so he is choosing a lazy approach. }
6... Bxc1 7. Qxc1 Ne7
{ Black chooses to develop the knight here, rather than on f6 because he wants to prepare the pawn break ...f7-f5. Since the center is closed and we have a position with pawn chains, it makes sense to play on one of the flanks, and the kingside is the most logical choice because Black's central pawns are pointed at it. }
8. Bd3
{ White develops the bishop exactly here, rather than to e2, because on d3, it is helping address the ...f7-f5 break and protect the e4-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nd7
{ Black continues development. If he wanted to play on the queenside, which would mean preparing ...b7-b5, he could also choose to develop the knight to a6, and then bring it to c7 to support that pawn break. From d7, however, the knight will likely come to f6 after ...f7-f5 has been played. }
10. Ne1
{ I am somewhat doubtful about how good this move is! Where is the knight going? Is White freeing up the f-pawn? Well, the move f2-f4 seems positionally wrong because after ...exf4, Black would obtain an outpost on e5, which would be easily accessible to both of his knights: one could get there from d7, and the other via g6.  Therefore, f2-f4 immediately doesn't sound great. Perhaps White wants to play g2-g3 and then f2-f4, looking to recapture back with the pawn to control the e5-square and the center overall! What about his knight? It's sort of miserable on e1, isn't it? Perhaps it wants to come to g2 after g2-g3.  I think Black could continue in a slower manner, for example by going ...Nf6, ...g7-g6, ...Nh5, and so on. But, it makes perfect sense that he decided to meet a passive move with the resolute ...f7-f5! }
10... f5 11. exf5 Nxf5
{ Now, White's knight gets an outpost on e4, but the French GM is not too worried about that since he can easily trade it off with ...Nf6 or ...Bf5. Of course, the black knight also has an outpost on d4! }
12. Bxf5
{ White decides to trade off this knight, which was about to land on d4. Since his bishop was pretty bad, this decision seems rather logical. }
12... Rxf5 13. Ne4 Nf6
{ Black is immediately trading off the powerful knight. } 14. f3
{ Now, Black not only deprives the opponent of an outpost, but he also causes tremendous coordination problems.   14.Ng5?  First of all, the e6-square, which would have been a lovely outpost if White could use it, is not a problem for us: the bishop on c8 is taking care of it. Secondly, this move is a tactical error.  14...Nxd5!  15.cxd5  Qxg5  and White just lost an important pawn for no reason.   Perhaps White's best bet would have been to keep the tension with  14.Ng3  . }
14... Nxe4 15. fxe4 Rxf1+
{ White also suffers from very poor coordination! Look, all the pieces are on the first rank! }
16. Kxf1 Qh4 { And on top of that, White is losing a pawn! } 17. Qe3 Qxh2 18.
Qg5
{ Now, all that Black needs is to get the rest of the pieces in the game and not blunder anything silly. Of course, if he wanted to, he could always trade queens with ...Qf4+. }
18... Bd7 19. Ke2 Rf8
{ 19...Be8!  seems to be an even stronger and more direct move. The white king is rather unsafe, so preparing this check with ...Bh5+ would have been a great idea! }
20. Nf3 Qf4
{ Black is sort of forced to retreat to this square, and it might seem weird to award this move with an exclamation mark. However, I am very happy that Black is getting to trade the queens! Then, he will combine the advance of his kingside pawns with pressure on all the white pawns, which are placed on the light squares, to win the game easily. }
21. Qxf4 Rxf4 22. Ke3 Rg4 23. Rg1 Kf7 { Time to start using the king! } 24. g3
h5
{ The outside passed pawn starts advancing. Next, Black should prepare ...g7-g5 and ...h5-h4. However, it is important to do that carefully: for example, ...g7-g5? right now would leave the rook without moves and get it trapped after Nh2! }
25. Nd2 Be8
{ The bishop is coming over to g6 to put pressure on the e4-pawn, which should tie up White's pieces even more. }
26. Kf2 Ke7 27. Rh1 Bg6
{ Now, the white knight and king are stuck. Next, Black should just activate his king with ...Kf6-g5 and eventually prepare ...h5-h4. }
28. Rh4 Rxh4 29. gxh4
{ White tries to block the extra pawn, but, of course, Black will easily play ...g7-g5. }
29... Kf6 30. Kf3 Bh7 31. Nf1 g5
{ An extra h-pawn, as well as the weakness on e4, should easily decide the game. }
32. Ng3 gxh4 33. Nf1
{ 33.Nxh5+?  Kg5  places the white knight in a very awkward position, where it is almost trapped, and shortly loses the pawns.  34.Ng7  Bg6!  Having prevented Ne8, which would win the d6-pawn, Black is ready to queen the pawn. The knight is helpless! }
33... Kg5 34. Ne3 h3 35. Kg3 Bxe4 { All the pawns are falling. } 36. Kxh3 Kf4
37. Nd1 Bf3 38. Nf2 e4
{ And finally White resigned. As we can see, once Black managed to trade the bishops and go ...f7-f5, and then especially trade on e4, he not only did not have any problems but in fact, he went on to easily overtake the initiative! }
