[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Main Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Artem Tyurin − Radoslav Dimitrov, Primorsko 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. c4 d6 4. e4 Be7
{ As always, Black is preparing to trade the bishops. } 5. Nc3 a6
{ Instead of hurrying to trade the bishops with ...Bg5, Black first covers the b5-square, preventing the Nb5 ideas. }
6. Nge2
{ This time, the knight comes out to a slightly unusual square. The idea is to not allow the trade ...Bg4 followed by ...Bxf3. But how would White develop his kingside? The thing is that he wants to castle queenside! }
6... Bg5 7. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ However, now it's not easy to castle queenside! White chooses to trade the queens, however after the trade, Black is perfectly safe and comfortable in the arising endgame. }
8. Qd2 Qxd2+ 9. Kxd2
{ This is a perfect example of how easy it can be to solve the opening problems in this variation versus a player that makes common sense moves but doesn't create any particular threats. Black got rid of the bad bishop and is not running the risk of ending up attacked or checkmated.  Now, the plan is to get the rest of the pieces out with ...Ne7, ...Nd7, and play ...f7-f5. Here is an interesting thought: potentially, the Na4-b6 idea can be met not only with ...Nbd7, but even with ...Kd8-c7, as the king would be perfectly safe on c7. If White ever tries to play on the queenside with b2-b4, it will help defend! }
9... Ke7
{ Black chooses to place the king on e7, which is not a bad square, but I would have preferred to develop differently, by going ...Ne7 and ...O-O, or even ...Kd8-c7 to help secure the queenside! He is clearly hoping to play ...f7-f5 and ...Nf6, deploying the knight more actively. That would be a great plan if it worked, but I don't believe it does. }
10. Nc1
{ White naturally wants to open up his blocked f1-bishop, but now the knight seems rather misplaced. This is where the game really starts going sideways for him.   10.Ng3!  would have been the way to go. This way, White could discourage ...f7-f5!  10...g6  11.Bd3  ,  Black is a bit hard-pressed to find another move that supports the ...f7-f5 break! For instance, after  11...Nh6  12.f3  f5  ,  he succeeds, but now the knight is rather misplaced on h6. }
10... f5 11. f3
{ If White wanted the opponent to take on e4 and then just take back, then it would have made sense to take with the piece. So unless he wants to play fxe4, the move f2-f3 is useless. Even worse than that − it's making his light-squared bishop worse!   11.exf5  Bxf5  12.Bd3  would also be a reasonable way for White to play. The idea is, of course, to trade a few pieces and enjoy an outpost on e4 for the knight! That's why instead of taking, Black should continue with  12...g6  ,  reinforcing the bishop and hoping the pawn appears on f5 to take control of that e4-square. }
11... fxe4 12. fxe4
{ Apparently, this is exactly what White wanted. Now White's bishop is awful, though! And he failed to get an outpost on e4. Problems are about to begin!   12.Nxe4  Bf5  13.Bd3  makes more sense. But even here, Black is doing great. In particular, I like the idea of trading a pair of pieces to make the nightmare endgame, where White is stuck with his bad bishop, a bit more of a reality.  13...Bxe4!  14.Bxe4  Nf6  .  Next, Black can try to pursue the ... b7-b5 break, or maybe grab space on the kingside with ...Nbd7, ...g7-g5, ...h7-h5, ...Rag8, ...g5-g4, etc. }
12... Nf6 13. a4
{ This is another considerable positional mistake, in my opinion. What does White want? He wants to play a4-a5 and then Na4-b6, enjoying an outpost. Well, the outpost is hardly obtainable: sure enough, the b6-square is great, but Black will just go ...Nbd7 and never let the opponent's knight in.  But the pawn on a5 could, certainly, somewhat restrict Black's queenside. So what is the downside of this move? Of course! It places another pawn on the light square, making that f1-bishop cry with huge salty tears. }
13... a5
{ Now Black has an outpost on b4 and the a4-pawn is fixed on a light square! Sure enough, White also gets an outpost on b5, but that is irrelevant because we could always trade that piece off with ...Bd7 and ...Bxb5 if we want, while our outpost is on a dark square. }
14. Be2 Na6
{ Now, Black is just finishing his development. Of course, most likely, the knight will go to b4, but probably it could find another route as well, such as c7-e8-f6, if needed. }
15. h3 { What is that? Another pawn going to a light square? Oh, God. } 15...
Bd7 16. Bf3 g5
{ Black, on the other hand, is excellent at his pawn play. Next, he'd love to go ...h7-h5 and then either ...h5-h4, fixing the white pawns on the light squares and obtaining an outpost on f4, or ...g5-g4, grabbing more space and pushing White back, while also likely opening up the g- or h-file. }
17. N1e2 h5 { The same logical plan is continuing to unfold. } 18. Ng3 Rag8 19.
Be2 h4
{ Black kicks out the knight, looking to then follow up with ...g5-g4, opening up the g-file for his rook, which is much better prepared to participate in the kingside action. }
20. Nf1
{ White keeps retreating, which, of course, is very passive. For those of you who tend to get a bit impatient while trying to convert the better positions, this game is a good reminder: it doesn't matter how fast you win! Just keep improving your pieces! Now, which black piece is not contributing much? Of course, the a6-knight!   20.Nf5+!?  This move looks counterintuitive since it trades off one of the few good white pieces. Now White is closer to the dreaded endgame with a bad bishop. However, it could be quite a good choice, the point being that after  20...Bxf5  21.exf5  21...g4  22.hxg4  Nxg4  23.Raf1  ,  Black cannot block the f-pawn with the king due to Ne4+ while blocking it with the knight would prevent his knight from helping him attack on the kingside. For instance, after  23...Nf6  24.Rh2  ,  White's position doesn't look great, but it's not easy at all to break through! }
20... Nc7
{ The knight is headed to the kingside. Where is it going? The f6-knight will move elsewhere, and this one will go to f6 via e8! Ideally, Black would like to find a home for the other one on f4, but it would be best to get there via h5 without giving White a chance to trade it off for his bishop. }
21. Ne3 Nce8 22. Ng4
{ Admittedly, despite all the passive moves White had played in his game, and the fact his position already got rather unpleasant, I think he still had decent chances to hold on. But this move is just a blunder, probably caused by fatigue after the exhausting defense, or time trouble. Or a bit of both plus psychological pressure. You need to remember that a game of chess also has to do with nerves! }
22... Nxg4 23. hxg4 Nf6 { Now Black will just pick this pawn. } 24. Ra3 b6
{ White is trying to activate the rook and Black anticipates that in advance, looking to meet Rb3 with the simple ...Rb8, defusing all the opponent's activity. }
25. Rb3 Rb8 26. Ke1 Nxg4
{ Finally, after all this effort, this pawn falls, and along with it, White's entire position collapses. }
27. Bxg4
{ White, on the other hand, at last, gets rid of his bad bishop. Not that it helps him a lot, but it is at least some relief! }
27... Bxg4 28. Ne2 Bd7
{ Black takes advantage of the loose a4-pawn. The winning plan is simple: tie the white pieces up to weaknesses, get a passed pawn on the h-file with ...g5-g4, ...h4-h3, etc. }
29. Re3
{ Obviously, it's not a good move and others were better, but it's hard to recommend White something attractive. Playing Nc3 would have prevented the knight from dealing with our passed pawn on the kingside, also leaving the b3-rook out of play, while Ra3 followed by b2-b3 would have also cut off the rook. }
29... Bxa4 { With two extra pawns, the rest is even easier. } 30. g3 Bd7 31.
Rg1 h3 32. Rh1 b5
{ On top of the powerful h-pawn, Black also creates a weakness on the queenside − the b2-pawn! }
33. cxb5 Rxb5 34. b3 a4
{ A nice final touch. White cannot take, as ...Rb1+ would win a rook on h1, so he is losing another pawn, which makes resignation very reasonable.  As we can see, although the game was decided by White playing Ng4 and basically blundering a pawn, his position was very unpleasant for a very long time before that. Once Black traded the bishops and queens, he started slowly but surely overtaking the initiative! }
