[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Main Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Ilan Manor − Inon Boim, Rishon LeZion 1990"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ This time White goes for the most challenging system − the one where White foregoes the move c2-c4. As a reminder from the theoretical chapter, it is the most challenging one because as a result, White keeps the option of giving a check on b5, which often causes disruption in the coordination of Black's pieces, and also keeps the access to the square on c4 for the knight. Oftentimes, if the knight can go to c4 and stay there, the d6-pawn finds itself under some really annoying pressure. }
4... Be7
{ As always, the goal is to trade off the bad dark-squared bishop with the move ...Bg5! }
5. Nf3 { With this move, White prevents the ...Bg5 idea, at least for now. }
5... a6
{ With this move, Black is preventing the ideas of Bb5+, as well as Nb5, which could at some point prove rather annoying. Now, he is ready to play ...b7-b5, expanding on the queenside. Of course, White cannot allow that to happen, which is why the next move is forced.  But remember guys: if your opponent forgets to respond to ...a7-a6 with a2-a4! then expanding on the queenside with ...b7-b5 is a no-brainer. }
6. a4 Bg4
{ This is another standard idea that we have already seen multiple times in the previous examples. Black is looking to trade off this knight so that White no longer controls the g5-square excessively, and then exchange the bishops with ...Bg5 anyway. }
7. Be2
{ Taking on f3 with the white bishop is not the best idea, in my view, because the bishop is doing nothing there. The white queen, instead, does belong on the kingside!   7.h3  − as I explain in the theoretical chapter, I consider it more principled and dangerous to take on f3 with the queen, because then it can go to g4 or g3, and harass Black's kingside.  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  . }
7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Bg5
{ Now, the goal of trading the bad bishop is achieved. Of course, White still has some extra space, but it's not nearly as much of a problem as it used to be because two pairs of minor pieces are gone.  The only bad aspect of our position is the fact that the white knight could at some point come to c4 and put pressure on the d6-pawn. If that wasn't the case, the position would have been equal, but I would have already preferred to play with the black pieces. }
9. O-O Bxc1 10. Qxc1 Ne7 11. a5
{ With this move, White is taking the b6-square under control. Now, he can reroute the knight to c4 without ever seeing it challenged with ...Nb6. }
11... O-O 12. Qd2
{ Now, White connects the rooks. As usual, Black would typically try to play ...f7-f5 sooner or later, for example with the inclusion of ...g7-g6 or without. White, on the other hand, should reroute the knight to c4 @@StartBracket@@I know, I repeated this one too many times!@@EndBracket@@ and try to push b2-b4, for example, to get some play on the queenside. }
12... Nd7 13. Ra3 g6
{ Black prefers the safer approach from the positional standpoint: he is willing to play ...f7-f5 only when it's possible to take back with the g-pawn. This is done in order to not allow the white knight to come to the e4-square and make it a lovely home for itself. }
14. Na4 f5 15. Re1 Rc8
{ This is a pretty mysterious-looking move, isn't it? The thing is that Black no longer needs to keep the knight on d7. However, if he were to remove that knight, then the white one could jump on b6 and force the black rook to go to b8 − what would the rook do there? So, Black moves it away in advance. Once the knight leaves d7 and the white one comes to b6, the rook will go to c7 and then f7 or g7 to attack the white king! A very subtle idea, isn't it? }
16. Be2
{ White realizes the bishop on f3 is not doing anything, so he is trying to reroute it elsewhere. He is also hoping to play f2-f3 to reinforce the pawn on e4. }
16... Rc7
{ 16...fxe4  − of course, Black could have taken the seemingly free pawn. So why didn't he? What would have happened?  17.Bg4!?  Black would no longer be able to advance the kingside pawns anymore, and the bishop would get to e6. After  17...Nf5  18.Nc3  ,  the position should be roughly balanced, but it seems that White is sort of getting out of this pressure. }
17. Rh3
{ When I saw this move, it certainly surprised me quite a bit! Certainly White cannot be thinking he would be the one attacking on the kingside. If that's not the case, then why is the rook going there? Probably the answer is that he was hoping to get the rook to help defend from the kingside attack! }
17... Nf6 18. exf5
{ The pawn on e4 was under a lot of pressure, but releasing the tension seems like a fairly undesirable thing to have to do! Now, Black can choose between two desirable outcomes: either reinforce his control of the center with ...gxf5 or activate the knight and try to bring it over to d4! }
18... Nxf5 19. Bd1 c4
{ With this move, Black is isolating the d5-pawn from the rest of the team. Now White is no longer able to play c2-c4 and protect the d5-pawn, and it could potentially become a target to ideas like ...Ne7, or ...Qe8-f7, and so on. The c4-pawn, on the other hand, cannot really be attacked because White's pieces are very passive. }
20. Nb6 Rc5
{ The white knight got somewhat active, but the c5-pawn is a real problem! }
21. Qb4 Rf7 22. c3
{ With this move, White covers the d4-square, preventing the black knight from jumping there!   22.Nxc4?  White couldn't afford to take the pawn since after  22...Nxd5  23.Qb3  Nf4!  ,  Black has too many threats: not only is he attacking the rook on h3 but also the black knight is about to come to d4! }
22... Ne7 23. Nxc4 Nexd5 24. Qb3 Qc7
{ With this move, Black makes the knight leave the c4-square, likely forcing a knight trade. Importantly, White cannot afford to defend the knight! }
25. Ne3 { 25.Be2  Nf4!  wins on the spot. } 25... Nxe3 26. Rhxe3 Kg7
{ White is sort of improving the rook, as it was useless on h3, while also sort of maneuvering a bit aimlessly. Black, on the other hand, slowly improves the position: with his last move, he unpinned the rook on f7. Now, he is ready to scoop up the a5-pawn, and maybe improve the knight with ...Nd5-f4.   Black could also afford to immediately win the pawn with  26...Rxa5  ,  and I am not entirely sure why he chose to not do that. }
27. Rd3 d5
{ Now that the e5-pawn is no longer under the pressure of both rooks, Black is able to start advancing the center. As you can see, he is not concerned about the e5-pawn at all. }
28. Rde3 e4 29. Qb4 Qxa5 { Finally, he chooses to scoop up the pawn. } 30. Qd4
Rc4 31. Qe5 Qc7
{ We are a pawn up, so that's a great opportunity to insist on a queen trade and go into the nearly-winning endgame! }
32. Qg5
{ White chooses to keep the queens to hopefully create a bit of counterplay, but Black can easily resolve that hurdle. }
32... h6 33. Qh4 g5
{ The queen has to either go to g3, where it would be traded off, or to h3, where it is just very misplaced. What is it doing there? }
34. Qh3 Qf4
{ I am not sure if I approve of this move, or rather of the fact Black seems to be just shuffling the pieces around. This is because he seemed to have a clear plan of advancing the queenside pawns and making considerable progress.   34...a5!?  If I were Black, I would choose this odd-looking move. At least, this move could look odd at a first glance to many of you. So what is going on here, exactly?  White has no play whatsoever. Black is a pawn up, which is great, but the pawn doesn't 'feel' useful at the moment. If that's the case, Black needs to create new weaknesses. What will they be?  
The goal is to create one on the queenside, and this is because the white queen is so misplaced and so far away from the queenside! So, Black wants to go ...a5-a4-a3 or ...b5-b4-b3! }
35. g3 Qd6 36. f4 { Now, Black has a forced win! Can you find it? } 36... Qd7
{ Sure, now Black gets a chance to offer a queen trade one more time, and even succeed, but missing a simple fork isn't a great thing!   36...exf3!  37.Bxf3  g4!  would have just won the game on the spot! }
37. Qxd7 Rxd7 38. fxg5 hxg5
{ White is just a pawn down in a rather sad endgame. Admittedly, it's still not very easy for Black to win, but he can certainly try to make progress in many ways. I would try to either push ...d5-d4 to create some extra opportunities to invade @@StartBracket@@such as with ...Rd2 or ...Rc2 in the future@@EndBracket@@ or ...b7-b5-b4, trying to create a weakness on b2 and a pair of connected passed pawns in the center. }
39. h4 g4
{ This move isn't bad, but to me, it wouldn't seem intuitive at all. What is going on here? Black restricted the white bishop even more and created a terrific outpost on f3 for one of his pieces. He also gave White a protected passed h-pawn. Probably the h-pawn isn't going anywhere, but nevertheless, it's a potentially risky thing to do.   39...Kg6  seems like a much more natural decision to me. Now, the black king is getting into the game, and if White wants to trade a pair of pawns, he will end up with a weakness on g3 that could be attacked in the future with the rooks from the g-file, with the knight from f5 or h5, and even the king! }
40. Bb3 Rc5 41. Rd1 Rd6
{ The rooks are finding a new use case − they are moving over to the queenside to harass the bishop and the b2-pawn! Black might not have a very forced win, but it's certainly a great way to put the opponent under more pressure and provoke him to create more weaknesses. }
42. Re2 Rb6 43. Ba2 Ra5 44. Bb1 Rab5
{ Of course, playing b2-b4 isn't possible due to arising problems on the b-file @@StartBracket@@see the variation below@@EndBracket@@, so White ends up stuck protecting that b2-pawn. }
45. Rdd2
{ 45.b4  a5!  wins a pawn since  46.bxa5??  Rxb1  is, obviously, impossible. }
45... Nh5 { Black finds another target − the g3-pawn! } 46. c4
{ White is desperate @@StartBracket@@understandably so!@@EndBracket@@ to get counterplay. He tries to get it by blowing up the center.   46.Kg2  Rf6!  seems like a huge problem, as the rook is about to invade on f6! Of course,  47.Rf2?  e3!  isn't acceptable. The point is that after  48.Rxf6  ,  Black has the intermediate move  48...exd2  ,  with an easy win. }
46... Rb3 47. cxd5 Nxg3
{ 47...Rxg3+!  would have been a lot cleaner. The point is that after  48.Rg2  e3!  49.Rc2  Kf6  ,  Black's e3-pawn is just dominating the entire position! Next, he will go ...Ke5 and scoop up the d-pawn as well, and the other rook is ready to join the game via, for instance, f6 and f3. }
48. Rg2
{ 48.Re1!  would have actually given White some chances because now he is threatening to take the e4-pawn, as well as to push the d5-pawn up the board! For instance, after  48...Rxb2  49.Bc2  Rd6  50.Kg2  Nh5  51.Rxe4  ,  the position is still rather unclear. }
48... e3 { Now it's over. } 49. Rd4 e2 50. Rxg4+ Kh6
{ White resigned since there is no way to stop the e-pawn: Kf2 runs into ...Rf6+ followed by ...Rf1+.  As you can see, this is another great example of White getting outplayed simply because... he didn't come up with an active plan. He was just making rather natural, decent-looking but useless moves the entire game, and eventually ended up outplayed.  Key takeaways: Black can take the time to patiently prepare ...f7-f5, and then in the event of exf5, designed at preventing the kingside attack, try to isolate the d5-pawn and win it! }
