[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Main Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Luca Suvorov − Piotr Piesik, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Nc3
{ This time White goes for the most challenging system − the one where White foregoes the move c2-c4. As a reminder from the theoretical chapter, it is the most challenging one because as a result, White keeps the option of giving a check on b5, which often causes disruption in the coordination of Black's pieces, and also keeps the access to the square on c4 for the knight. Oftentimes, if the knight can go to c4 and stay there, the d6-pawn finds itself under some really annoying pressure. }
4... Be7
{ As always, the goal is to trade off the bad dark-squared bishop with the move ...Bg5! }
5. Nf3 { With this move, White prevents the ...Bg5 idea, at least for now. }
5... a6
{ With this move, Black is preventing the ideas of Bb5+, as well as Nb5, which could at some point prove rather annoying. Now, he is ready to play ...b7-b5, expanding on the queenside. Of course, White cannot allow that to happen, which is why the next move is forced.  But remember guys: if your opponent forgets to respond to ...a7-a6 with a2-a4! then expanding on the queenside with ...b7-b5 is a no-brainer. }
6. a4 Bg4
{ This is another standard idea that we have already seen multiple times in the previous examples. Black is looking to trade off this knight so that White no longer controls the g5-square excessively, and then exchange the bishops with ...Bg5 anyway. }
7. Rb1
{ A very odd move. When I was looking at the games to pick as model examples, at a first glance I thought it was a misclick @@StartBracket@@since it was an online game@@EndBracket@@. But then, a moment later, I realized White had a thought behind this move: he wanted to quickly push b2-b4! That's certainly a very unusual way to execute that plan.   7.h3  − as I explain in the theoretical chapter, I consider it more principled and dangerous to take on f3 with the queen, because then it can go to g4 or g3, and harass Black's kingside. }
7... Nd7 8. Be2
{ As I emphasized many times throughout the theoretical chapter and model games, taking on f3 with the bishop is not nearly as good as with the queen because the queen wants to have the ability to jump to g4 or g3 and harass the kingside. }
8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Bg5
{ As always, Black is in a hurry to get rid of his dark-squared bishop. Now, the lack of space will no longer be a problem! }
10. b4
{ This was the point behind White's mysterious rook move. He wants to immediately open up the b-file and try to put pressure on the b7-pawn!  But that doesn't seem like an easy task to accomplish. Why doesn't Black just recapture on c5 with the knight, not only protecting the pawn but also starting to enjoy a wonderful outpost? }
10... Bxc1 11. Qxc1 cxb4
{ It would have been even more beneficial for Black to wait for the opponent to capture on c5 and take back with the knight, activating it without losing a tempo. So why wouldn't he wait? Why would he capture himself? Because he really appreciates the outpost on c5, and he is afraid that if he doesn't capture, White will play b4-b5, locking the position up. }
12. Rxb4 Nc5 13. O-O Nf6
{ We are again looking at this classic familiar scenario: Black is hoping to enjoy the amazing outpost on c5 even more once the pair of knights comes off. He would be also happy to trade other pieces, getting the wonderful endgame with a great knight versus a bad bishop.  Another idea: if Black ever managed to trade his b-pawn for the white a-pawn, for example after White goes a4-a5 and Black pushes ...b7-b6, the black a-pawn would become a very dangerous passed pawn. }
14. Qa3 O-O 15. a5
{ This move has a potential upside − it has the capacity to restrict Black's queenside pawns. However, it also has a considerable downside: it could potentially create a weak pawn on a5, or allow Black to get a passed a-pawn by going ...b7-b6 at some point, as I mentioned earlier. }
15... Rc8 16. Rb6 Nfd7
{ It turns out the d6-pawn is not hanging, so Black is able to achieve his optimal setup even faster. }
17. Rb2 { 17.Rxd6??  Qc7  traps the rook. } 17... Qh4
{ Pretty interesting!  Instead of slowly progressing on the queenside, trying to push ...b7-b6, Black tries to attack on the other flank! With ...f7-f5, ...Rf6, etc coming, White certainly has to be rather careful! }
18. g3 Qh3 19. Na4
{ White voluntarily trades off the pair of knights, which, as I had mentioned, is clearly to Black's benefit.  This is because now White ends up in a classic scenario with a wonderful knight versus a bad bishop, and clearly on the wrong side of things! }
19... Nxa4 { Of course, Black immediately jumps on the opportunity! } 20. Qxa4
Nc5 { The other knight is replacing its colleague. } 21. Qa3 f5
{ Time to start the kingside play! } 22. exf5 Qxf5
{ Of course, White is not going to get checkmated, as there are not a lot of pieces left on the board, but we can certainly disturb him quite a bit. For example, Black could triple on the f-file with ...Rf6, ...Rcf8, and see whether pressure on the f2-pawn doesn't become a problem.  Black could also consider playing ...e5-e4, disconnecting the bishop from the d5-pawn, and provoking c2-c4. Once that move is played, the d3-square becomes an outpost for the black knight. By coming there, it will help put more pressure on the f2-pawn! }
23. Bg2 e4 { Exactly! Now the d5-pawn is a serious problem. } 24. c4
{ White solves it seemingly easy, but there is a price to pay − the d3-square is going to hurt. }
24... Rc7
{ 24...h5!?  is another plan I like a lot. Of course, White wouldn't want to allow the opponent's pawn to run all the way to h3, creating an unpleasant mating net. Therefore, he will need to reply  25.h4  but now we can weaken the king even more:  25...g5!  26.hxg5  Qxg5  .   Sure enough, the black king looks pretty open as well, but Black is the only one who has pieces on the kingside! With ...h5-h4, ...Rf6-g6 coming next, etc, it seems as though Black would clearly be able to create serious problems for the opponent's king, while always having the transition to a pleasant endgame as a backup plan too. }
25. Rb6 Qe5 26. Qa1
{ The reason why I am not happy about the situation with the queen trade has to do with the recent pawn moves. The problem is that having played ...e5-e4, Black not only grabbed space but also made his pawns weaker. Therefore, I am a bit concerned about White being able to create counterplay by attacking these pawns, especially the one on e4. That wasn't possible a few moves ago! For that reason, Black had to keep the queens on the board. }
26... Qxa1 27. Rxa1 Rf6 { See, now the rooks are forced to be rather passive. }
28. Re1 Re7
{ The position is still roughly equal, but White is no longer in danger. } 29.
Bh3
{ 29.f4!?  looks like an interesting decision to me. By seemingly giving the opponent a passed pawn, White prepares to go Kf2-e3 and block it, while also making sure the f2-pawn will never be under pressure. Next, he can go Bh3, Re2, Kf2-e3, and so on. }
29... Kf7 30. Bc8 Ke8
{ Neither party is able to make progress. This was a game with faster time control. At some point White was better, then blundered and Black won. With that in mind, we should cut our analysis short here and arrive at a few conclusions:  ♟ Taking on f3 with the bishop, rather than the queen, is not a good idea for White, because his queen wants to jump to g4 or g3, and now it's not possible.   ♟ Playing b2-b4 could be a rather thematic plan for White, however, he has to be careful because doing so without proper preparation allows Black to create an outpost on c5.  ♟ If you like advancing the pawns, which Black did with ...e5-e4, you need to remember not just about the upsides, but also the fact that they could get weaker. }
31. Reb1 Rff7 32. Rxd6 e3 33. fxe3 Rxe3 34. Bg4 Re4 35. Be6 Rc7 36. Rf1 Rxc4
37. Rb6 Rd4 38. d6 Rc6 39. d7+ Nxd7 40. Bxd7+ Rxd7 41. Rb4 Rc5 42. Re4+ Kd8 43.
Rf8+ Kc7 44. Ree8 Rxa5 45. Rc8+ Kb6 46. Rh8 h6 47. Kg2 Ra2+ 48. Kh3 a5 49. Rhg8
a4 50. Ra8 Kb5 51. Rge8 Rd4 52. Re5+ Kb4 53. Re7 b5 54. Rxg7 Rdd2 55. Rb7 Rxh2+
56. Kg4 Rhc2 57. Rab8 Rc4+ 58. Kh5 Rc5+ 59. Kxh6 Rg2 60. Rg7 a3 61. g4 Kb3 62.
Ra8 b4 63. g5 a2 64. Rgg8 Rg1 65. g6 a1=Q 66. Rxa1 Rxa1 67. g7 Ra6+ 68. Kh7
Rh5# *

