[Black "Christian Hauke − Mikheil Kekelidze, Böblingen 2000"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6
{ This time, Black chooses a completely different plan, which will be the focus of this chapter's discussions. He is giving up the hope of trading the bishops with ...Be7-g5 since now the knight is preventing that idea from happening.  So why would Black do that and what's his plan? He wants to castle, then slowly develop, and prepare ...f7-f5 by means of ...g7-g6, ...Ne8-g7, and so on. Then, hopefully, he will be able to slowly build up the kingside attack. }
5. Nf3 Be7 6. Bb5+
{ This time Black is not bothered about the check. Typically, it's important for Black to be able to go ...Bg4, trade off the knight, and then the bishops with ...Bg5. Hence, having to play ...Nbd7 or ...Bd7, which prevents the setup with ...Bg4, is rather awkward. However, this time Black is not looking to play ...Bg4, but instead use a different plan, so the check is not a problem. }
6... Nbd7 7. a4
{ This is an important move for White to remember to make. If he doesn't, Black wins a tempo with ...a7-a6, forcing White to take on d7. That's because retreating is even worse as it allows Black to expand with ...b7-b5.   7.O-O ?  is a positional mistake since after  7...a6  8.Bd3  b5  ,  Black is obviously doing great. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ With this move, Black is starting to prepare his kingside play. He could play ...f7-f5 right away, but typically that won't be very positionally desirable, as after exf5 and ...Rxf5, the white pieces get an outpost on e4. For that reason, it is better to be patient, wait and prepare ...f7-f5 under good circumstances, making sure you can take with the g-pawn, increasing your control over the center. So, Black wants to go ...g7-g6 first, and only then ...f7-f5. }
9. Bd3
{ Since the bishop is no longer doing anything useful on b5, White brings it back. Naturally, he wants to keep it on d3, because from here, it helps protect the e4-pawn and discourage the ...f7-f5 break. Conversely, if it went to e2, it would be useless there. }
9... g6 10. Bh6
{ This move looks tempting, but it doesn't really accomplish anything. } 10...
Ng7 11. Qd2 Nf6
{ This is another really useful part of our 'slow' plan. Black wants to kick out the bishop by playing ...Kh8 and ...Ng8, and then push ...f7-f5 under the best circumstances possible! That plan, for historic reference, was extensively popularized by Kasparov in the 80s, who used it in the King's Indian. }
12. h3
{ This move seems rather logical since White is preventing ...Ng4 as well as ...Bg4, but I think it has some subtle downsides as well. Specifically, if Black does manage to expand on the kingside with ...f7-f5-f4, ...g6-g5-g4, and so on, then the move h2-h3 will be nothing but an extra hook for Black's attack. }
12... Kh8 13. Nh2
{ It's not obvious what White's plan should be. As we can see, he is maneuvering rather aimlessly, allowing Black to smoothly execute his plan. }
13... Ng8 14. Be3 f5 { Everything is going just perfectly! } 15. f4
{ Naturally, White, being unhappy about the current flow of things, tries to change the nature of the position. However, his decision has considerable positional flaws!   15.f3  would have allowed developing the powerful standard attack with  15...Nh5  ,  then ... f5-f4, ...Bh4 to trade White's good bishop, ...g6-g5, ...Ng3, ...h7-h5, ...g5-g4, etc. Please note White has not made any progress whatsoever on his flank! }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4
{ Now, I want you to pause and find a powerful positional idea for Black. }
16... g5 17. Bg3 f4
{ That square on e5 is meant to be a gorgeous outpost! With these two last pawn moves, Black shuts down both bishops and secures the outpost on e5! Next, he'll bring the knight there with ...Nh6-f7-e5! }
18. Bf2 Nh6 19. Rae1 Nf7
{ Perfect! I find the way Black is using his advantage extremely impressive. }
20. Nb5
{ White is trying to reroute the knight to c4, perhaps. He is also preparing the move b2-b4, which wasn't possible previously, as the pawn would have been hanging. }
20... Ne5 21. b4 b6
{ The problem is that this pawn break doesn't accomplish much! } 22. a5 a6
{ 22...h5!  I think it was even easier to just ignore the opponent's timid attempts to make any progress on the queenside. What will White do? Just trade two pairs of pawns?!  23.axb6  axb6  24.bxc5  bxc5  .  Okay, so what? Meanwhile, Black is ready to go ...g5-g4, ...Rg8, and crush the opponent. }
23. Na3 b5
{ This is also an effective way of stopping the counterplay attempts, of course. }
24. Be2 c4
{ I admire the way Black handled this entire game, but don't love this move because it gifts White an outpost on d4. He could try to bring the bishop there, or even the knight by playing c2-c3 and Nc2-d4.   After  24...h5  ,  I don't think White can get any play on the queenside! Following  25.c4  g4  ,  Black is threatening numerous things, such as ...f4-f3, ...g4-g3, and so on. Why bother about the queenside? }
25. Bd4 Bf6 26. c3 Qe8
{ White is helpless anyway. Now the queen is coming over to g6, and then ...h7-h5 and ...g5-g4 will be unstoppable. }
27. Bg4 h5
{ 27...Nd3!  seems even stronger. The rook is hanging and after  28.Bxf6  Rxf6  29.Re2  Nh5!  ,  the other knight gets tremendously active too. Poor White! }
28. Bxc8 Rxc8 29. Nc2 Qg6
{ And here the notation stops. Maybe White lost on time? Maybe the players were in time trouble and the further writing was illegible? In either case, Black clearly has a very powerful initiative here, and his next moves are extremely straightforward.  Just play ...g5-g4, ...Rg8, ...f4-f3, and see White fall apart! As you can see, this slow plan, although it doesn't look impressive at first, can turn out very powerful. Especially if White is just shuffling his pieces around! }
