5... Nf6
{ This time, Black chooses a completely different plan, which will be the focus of this chapter's discussions. He is giving up the hope of trading the bishops with ...Be7-g5 since now the knight is preventing that idea from happening.   So why would Black do that and what's his plan? He wants to castle, then slowly develop, and prepare ...f7-f5 by means of ...g7-g6, ...Ne8-g7, and so on. Then, hopefully, he will be able to slowly build up the kingside attack. }
6. Nc3 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ With this move, Black is starting to prepare his kingside play. He could play ...f7-f5 right away, but typically that won't be very positionally desirable, as after exf5 and ...Rxf5, the white pieces get an outpost on e4. For that reason, it is better to be patient, wait and prepare ...f7-f5 under good circumstances, making sure you can take with the g-pawn, increasing your control over the center. So, Black wants to go ...g7-g6 first, and only then ...f7-f5. }
9. Qe2
{ In the previous game, we saw White retreat to d3 with the bishop. Now, he makes this move, which to me seems rather mysterious. What is the queen doing on e2? }
9... g6
{ Black is starting to prepare ...f7-f5, followed by taking with the g-pawn and reinforcing the center. }
10. Bh6
{ This move looks tempting, but it doesn't really accomplish anything. } 10...
Ng7 11. a5
{ Here is a rather interesting positional idea. White seems to have a bit of a positional threat − he is looking to go a5-a6, provoke ...b7-b6 since taking on a6 ruins the pawn structure.  Therefore, after Black is forced to go ...b7-b6, the c6-square becomes a hole, and the b5-square becomes an outpost. White can then install the bishop on c6 and the knight on b5, obtaining an absolutely dominant position on the queenside, and maybe even winning something right away! Of course, that absolutely needs to be prevented. }
11... a6
{ Black absolutely must ward off the aforementioned positional threat.   11...Kh8  ,  let's say Black ignores the opponent's idea.  12.a6!  b6?  13.Bc6!  Rb8  14.Nb5+-  and the queenside just collapses! }
12. Bxd7
{ This time, White chooses to trade his bishop off. As usual, many trade-related decisions have a lot of upsides and downsides. Here, on one hand, White is getting rid of the bishop that we typically call passive and useless. He also, in anticipation of the opponent's upcoming kingside attack, decreases his piece count. But, he also gives up the spatial advantage @@StartBracket@@remember, a spatial advantage is created by having a lot of pieces@@EndBracket@@, and helps Black unravel! }
12... Bxd7 13. Nd2
{ This maneuver is, as usual, a very good idea. As I keep repeating, the biggest reason why not playing c2-c4 and leaving the pawn on c2 is a good idea is because the c4-square is available for the knight. So, White is rerouting it there to put pressure on the d6-pawn and the queenside! }
13... f5
{ Black, on the other hand, predictably starts a kingside attack. Remember, in these positions, the light-squared bishop is a really important piece because it can eventually sacrifice itself on h3, helping break up White's defenses. The d7-bishop is still alive! }
14. Nc4 f4 { The d6-pawn is, of course, by no means in danger. } 15. f3
{ 15.Nb6  seems like an attractive idea because, as we had discussed earlier, it's good for White to trade off the light-squared bishop. However, this move runs into a very strong response. Can you find it?  15...f3!  Of course! Remember this idea. If White doesn't go f2-f3 himself, he is not safe!  16.gxf3  Bg5!    The dark squares are extremely weak. White should trade the bishops and play with a weak king. However, for example after  17.Nxd7  Bxh6  18.Nxf8  Bf4!  ,  he can easily get in more trouble. ...Qh4 is coming, Black will take the knight back, and of course, the compensation for the sacrificed exchange is overwhelming! }
15... Rf7
{ Black unpins the g7-knight in order to move it away to h5 and leave the white bishop on h6 very misplaced. In fact, that piece could easily get trapped!   15...Rb8  could have prevented the move Nb6 being a fork, but unfortunately, it doesn't seem to achieve much anyway. For instance, after  16.Nb6  Be8  ,  Black does keep the bishop alive but at a cost of making all the pieces passive. }
16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Nxd7 Qxd7
{ Now, it's no longer as easy to attack. Remember, the light-squared bishop was a very important piece! However, Black is by no means uncomfortable! The bishop on h6 is stuck, and White has not really developed any play of his own on the queenside!  Perhaps the main thing Black should be afraid of in the long run is the idea of Nb1-d2-c4, bringing the knight to a brilliant square. Then White could follow up with b2-b4, eventually opening up the queenside and creating counterplay there. But, fortunately, this isn't happening for quite a while! }
18. Bxg7 Rxg7 19. Rfb1 h5
{ The kingside play is still rather dangerous! Next, Black wants to go ...g5-g4, and then not ...g4-g3, which allows White to close the flank with h2-h3, but rather ...h4-h3, breaking up the kingside structure! }
20. Ra3 g5 21. Na4 Bd8
{ This is a very cool move. Why worry about the counterplay on the queenside, if it can be easily stopped? The pawn is under fire, and of course, if the knight comes to b6, Black will just eliminate it, solving all the queenside problems for the rest of the game! }
22. Kh1 g4
{ The kingside play is smooth as butter.   22...Bxa5?  Of course, Black doesn't want to take immediately, as after  23.Nxc5  dxc5  24.Rxa5  ,  the structure gets damaged, and White gets a protected passed pawn on d5. }
23. Rf1 Bc7
{ This move might seem mysterious at first, but Black is simply making sure the b8-rook can get in the game! Next, he can play ...Kh7 and ...Rbg8, getting the last soldier in the fight! }
24. c3 Kh8 25. b4
{ Finally, White gets something going on the queenside, but of course, it doesn't matter since we are much faster on our flank. }
25... cxb4 26. cxb4 Rbg8
{ 26...Rc8!?  looks pretty interesting too, actually. Because of the misplaced knight on a4, White cannot easily fight for the c-file with his rooks, so Black might by accident take over the c-file and win on the other flank! }
27. Rc1 Bd8 28. Nb6 Bxb6 29. axb6
{ White finally gets some hope of invading with Rc7, but that can be easily stopped as well. }
29... Qd8 { The pawn on b6 is a liability too. } 30. fxg4 hxg4 31. g3 Qxb6
{ Finally, everything is collapsing. Black is completely winning! } 32. gxf4
exf4 33. e5
{ White is desperately trying to open up the center and maybe give some perpetual check or something. }
33... Qxb4 34. Rac3 Qd4 35. exd6 Qxd5+ 36. Kg1 Qxd6
{ And all the pawns got lost. The game went on for a few more dozen moves, but eventually Black converted his advantage. He was always winning, it just took a while.  As we can see, this is another great example of a game where Black knew the entire time what he was doing, while White was just shuffling his pieces around. Without a plan, he got outplayed in no time! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Slow Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Phuong Hanh Luong − Abhijit Kunte, Bangkok 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ This time, Black starts with the traditional move order. In this move order, typically used to play the Modern Benoni, Black is waiting for the move c2-c4, to avoid the setups with Nc3 and the pawn on c2. Of course, one of the downsides is that Black is no longer able to go ...Be7-g5. }
2. Nf3
{ White chooses the more conservative move order. By delaying c2-c4, he is avoiding sharp lines like the Benko Gambit, while also foregoing setups with f2-f3 or f2-f4. }
2... c5 3. d5 d6 4. Nc3 e5 5. e4 Be7
{ And we are again back to our traditional setups. } 6. Bb5+
{ As always, the check is aimed at provoking the awkward move ...Bd7 or ...Nbd7. Typically, Black wants the bishop to go to g4, and the knight to go to d7 only after that. Or sometimes Black uses the route a6-c7 for the knight. }
6... Nbd7
{ As always, Black now has a positional threat of ...a7-a6, winning a tempo and then quickly playing ...b7-b5. }
7. a4
{ White needs to make sure to play this prophylactic move to prevent ...b7-b5 in advance. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ As always, the goal is to prepare ...f7-f5. First Black can go ...g7-g6, making sure ...f7-f5 exf5 can be followed up with ...gxf5. }
9. Bd3
{ The bishop no longer does anything useful on b5, so it retreats to overprotect the e4-pawn. }
9... a6 10. Nd2
{ The knight is coming over to the wonderful square on c4, where it can put pressure on the d6-pawn, and potentially jump to the b6-square. }
10... b6
{ This is a rather unusual and interesting plan. By making this move, Black discourages a4-a5. Typically the move a4-a5 has the potential to squeeze the queenside and create an outpost on b6 for the knight. That's why preventing it could be valuable. Also, potentially, Black can slowly prepare ...b6-b5 by going ...Nc7, ...Bd7, ...Rb8, and ...b6-b5.   The only danger @@StartBracket@@be VERY careful to not run into this@@EndBracket@@ is that playing ...b6-b5 with the knight on c4 is often a bad idea because the white knight can jump from c4 to a5 and c6. But, if there is no knight on c4, then typically ...b6-b5 is a very good pawn advance for Black to accomplish. }
11. Nc4 Bg5 { Time to trade the bad bishop! } 12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. Qe2 Rb8
{ I am not sure about this move. Naturally, Black wants to go ...b6-b5, but it's not easy for several reasons. One is the aforementioned idea of Na5-c6, and the other will be seen in the game in a moment. }
14. Ne3 { The pawn is hanging! Black is sort of forced to go back! } 14... Ra8
15. Kh1 Ndf6
{ I find this move a bit unexpected. Black unblocks the bishop and is potentially looking to go ...Ng4, trading off a pair of knights. But I don't like the idea of cutting the queen off from being able to come back to the queenside to protect the d6-pawn and support the ...b6-b5 break. }
16. Nc4 Rb8 17. Ne3 Ra8 { More repetition! Will we just have a draw? } 18. Nc4
Rb8 19. Nd2
{ White decides to play on! Admittedly, Black wasn't forced to repeat either. }
19... Nc7 20. b3
{ This move seems rather slow. Black is preparing ...b6-b5, and what is the opponent doing? }
20... Nh5
{ Another very well-timed idea! The knight is coming over to c4 to put pressure on the kingside and potentially trade off the bishop on d3 to decrease the number of pieces. But can't White just stop the knight with g2-g3? }
21. Nc4
{ 21.g3  doesn't cause a collapse of any sort, but after  21...Bh3  22.Rg1  b5  ,  Black gets a lot of play on the queenside, and White has to be a bit careful about the kingside. For example, if the rook leaves the g1-square, some ...Nf4 ideas could be very unpleasant. }
21... Nf4 22. Qf3 Ne8
{ Black is no longer playing on the queenside, so it makes the most sense to use the knight for protecting the pawn. The queen, on the other hand, remains in an active position. }
23. g3 Nxd3
{ It's a bit unfortunate to trade off the bad bishop, but in exchange, Black decreases his space-related problems while also getting a lot of play within a few moves. }
24. Qxd3 Bh3 25. Rg1 Qh5
{ 25...f5!  I would have been very tempted to play this move immediately. The threat of ...f5-f4, squeezing White's kingside, and looking to follow up with ...Rf6-h6 and ...Qh5, aiming to checkmate White on h2, seems very unpleasant!  26.f3  f4  27.g4  h5!  looks like a great way for Black to make progress! }
26. f3 f5 { Finally! } 27. Nd2 Nf6 { More pieces are coming into the attack! }
28. Rae1 fxe4
{ This move might seem a bit unexpected, as it gives White an opportunity to recapture with the knight. }
29. Ncxe4 Nxe4
{ White either has to take with the pawn, giving up the outpost and allowing the black rook to invade to a terrific square on f2, or end up in a position where the f3-pawn is extremely weak! }
30. Qxe4 Bf5
{ The c2-pawn is also a problem. White needs to play very passively! } 31. Qc4
b5 { More tempi and initiative-gaining moves! } 32. axb5 axb5 33. Qc3 Qf7
{ Black achieves decisive progress in a somewhat unexpected way: the d5-pawn is falling! }
34. Rd1 Qxd5 35. Ne4 Bxe4 { The queen isn't hanging! } 36. Rxd5 Rxf3
{ Black is threatening too many things: the queen, a discovery like ...Rf2+, and the rook. The end! }
37. Rxe5 dxe5
{ White resigned. As you can see, White again lost without a fight! He had not created any counterplay whatsoever, and slowly got outplayed on the kingside. Different moves, same scenario! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Slow Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Nils Linde Olsen − Thorbjorn Bromann, Denmark 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. d5 e5 3. e4 d6 4. Bb5+ Nd7 5. a4
{ This is an important move for White to remember to make. If he doesn't, Black wins a tempo with ...a7-a6, forcing White to take on d7. That's because retreating is even worse as it allows Black to expand with ...b7-b5.   After  5.Nf3?  a6!  6.Bd3  b5  ,  Black is obviously doing great, as his queenside play is developing without any hurdles. }
5... Be7 6. Nf3 Nf6
{ This time, Black chooses a completely different plan, which will be the focus of this chapter's discussions. He is giving up the hope of trading the bishops with ...Be7-g5 since now the knight is preventing that idea from happening.   So why would Black do that and what's his plan? He wants to castle, then slowly develop, and prepare ...f7-f5 by means of ... g7-g6, ...Ne8-g7, and so on. Then, hopefully, he will be able to slowly build up the kingside attack. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O Ne8
{ With this move, Black is starting to prepare his kingside play. He could play ...f7-f5 right away, but typically that won't be very positionally desirable, as after exf5 and ...Rxf5, the white pieces get an outpost on e4. For that reason, it is better to be patient, wait and prepare ...f7-f5 under good circumstances, making sure you can take with the g-pawn, increasing your control over the center. So, Black wants to go ... g7-g6 first, and only then ...f7-f5. }
9. Bd3
{ Since the bishop is no longer doing anything useful on b5, White brings it back. Naturally, he wants to keep it on d3 because from here, it helps protect the e4-pawn and discourage the ...f7-f5 break. Conversely, if it went to e2, it would be useless there. }
9... g6 10. Bh6
{ This move looks tempting, but it doesn't really accomplish anything. } 10...
Ng7 11. Qd2 Nf6
{ This is another really useful part of our 'slow' plan. Black wants to kick out the bishop by playing ...Kh8 and ...Ng8, and then push ...f7-f5 under the best circumstances possible! That plan, for historic reference, was extensively popularized by Kasparov in the 80s, who used it in the King's Indian. }
12. h3
{ This move seems rather logical since White is preventing ...Ng4 as well as ...Bg4, but I think it has some subtle downsides as well. Specifically, if Black does manage to expand on the kingside with ...f7-f5-f4, ...g6-g5-g4, and so on, then the move h2-h3 will be nothing but an extra hook for Black's attack. }
12... Kh8 13. Nh2
{ It's not obvious what White's plan should be. As we can see, he is maneuvering rather aimlessly, allowing Black to smoothly execute his plan. }
13... Ng8 14. Be3 f5 { Everything is going just perfectly! } 15. f4
{ 15.f3  would have allowed developing the powerful standard attack with  15...Nh5  ,  then ... f5-f4, ...Bh4 to trade White's good bishop, ...g6-g5, ...Ng3, ...h7-h5, ...g5-g4, and so on. Please note White has not made any progress whatsoever on his flank! }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4
{ Now, I want you to pause and find a powerful positional idea for Black. }
16... g5 17. Be3 f4
{ That square on e5 is meant to be a gorgeous outpost! With these two last pawn moves, Black shuts down both bishops and secures the outpost on e5! Next, he'll bring the knight there with ...Nh6-f7-e5! }
18. Bf2 Bf6
{ I like this move less since it allows White to get quite a lot of counterplay.   18...Nh6!  was seen in one of the previous games of this chapter, which, amazingly, also got to this position on move 18. }
19. Qe2
{ White had a chance to get activity, but this indecisive pointless move gives up the chances again.   19.Nf3!  White needs to make the e4-e5 break work:  19...Nh6  20.e5!  dxe5  21.Bxc5↑  . }
19... Ne7 20. Ng4 Ng6
{ 20...Bxg4!  21.Qxg4  Ng6∓  also looks great. Sure enough, Black's light-squared bishop is a great piece, but by eliminating the knight, he could eliminate the last hopes for counterplay. Next, we'd want to go ...Ne5 and ...f4-f3!, tearing apart the opponent's king shelter. }
21. Nh6
{ What is the knight doing there, exactly? As we can see, White is playing without any plan whatsoever... }
21... f3 { It's over. The king's shelter is collapsing. } 22. gxf3 Bxh3 23.
Rfd1 Bxc3
{ Black frees up the f6-square and gets a decisive attack by bringing the queen in. The bishop looked good, but getting rid of it with a tempo is even better! }
24. bxc3 Ne5 25. Kh1 Qf6 26. Nf5
{ 26.Ng4  Bxg4  27.fxg4  Qxf2  wins a piece and the game, of course. } 26...
Nxf5 27. exf5 Qh6
{ Just watch the remaining moves. No need to comment, just enjoy the slaughter! }
28. Kg1 g4 29. Be3
{ 29.fxg4  Bxg4-+  not only wins an exchange but also allows the black knight to jump right in the heart of the position.  30.Qe3  Nf3+  31.Kf1  Qh3+  with checkmate. }
29... Qh5 30. Bf4 Nxf3+ 31. Kf2 Rae8 32. Be4 Rxf5 33. Bxd6 Nd4+
{ And White finally admitted his defeat.  This game was extremely similar to the second one. If you want to be extremely meticulous, you could argue White had one opportunity for counterplay with Nf3 and e4-e5, but overall, it's another example of how easy it is to win such positions if White plays without a plan, which is certainly the case in all of these games!  As you can see, even 2200-2400 rated players are often absolutely unfamiliar with what White should be doing in these positions! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Slow Plan − Model Games"]
[Black "Joel Lautier − Liviu Dieter Nisipeanu, Noyon 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
{ This is the most unusual game of all five of this chapter. First of all, it's a very high-level encounter! Secondly, White has played c2-c4 as opposed to keeping the pawn on c2. }
2... c5 3. d5 e5 { Again, we are looking at the slow setup. } 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4
Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. h3
{ This move, you would think, is aimed at preventing ...Bg4, trading off the light-squared bishop. However, as the game shows, White had a very different and much more aggressive idea in mind! }
7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 a6
{ Black isn't ready to push ...b7-b5, but he could always consider sacrificing a pawn in the Benko Gambit style! }
9. a4 { Of course, it makes no sense for White to allow that. } 9... Nh5
{ Typically, you see this knight go to e8, but this time Black starts preparing ...f7-f5 this way. What are the pros and cons of having a knight on h5? That would be really useful for you to know. At a first glance, it looks like it's bad to have it there for several reasons:  It's loose. Often White has tactics related to doing something with the f3-knight and then winning the one on h5.  It can be kicked out with g2-g4. However, this is exactly Black's idea! The knight isn't hanging at the moment, and Black is trying to provoke g2-g4 to jump into the heart of White's position: the f4-square. }
10. Ne2
{ White makes this move to take the f4-square under more control and create a positional threat of g2-g4, kicking out the annoying h5-knight.   10.g4?  Nf4!  is exactly what Black is dreaming about.   10.Nxe5??  Of course, the knight on h5 isn't hanging, as after  10...Nxe5  11.Qxh5  Nxd3+  ,  Black just wins a piece. }
10... g6
{ Black makes room for the knight. If chased away, it can retreat to g7 and help prepare ...f7-f5. }
11. g4 Ng7 12. Ng3 { Now White controls the f5-square really well! } 12... Kh8
{ Typically, playing ...f7-f5 would be the most logical and common idea. However, here this plan could easily backfire since White has not castled kingside. If the g-file opens up at a bad time, White could easily set up an attack with Rg1, Qg4, etc. Therefore, Black retreats away from the g-file. }
13. Be3 Nf6
{ Black wasn't ready to play ...f7-f5 just yet, so he moves the knight to g8 to protect the f5-square better. }
14. Qc2 Ng8 15. Ke2
{ White has a bit of a problem with the king. If he wants to attack on the kingside, castling there is clearly not an option. And actually, it's not an option no matter what since if White castles kingside, that side of the board will open up in no time, leaving the white king helpless.  Castling queenside is too dangerous as well since ...b7-b5 would instantly prove the king weak. So, if White wants to connect the rooks, there is no choice but to keep it in the center.   15.O-O-O  would be too scary, as after  15...Bd7  ,  Black will immediately prepare ...b7-b5 and tear apart the opponent's king. }
15... Bd7 16. b4
{ This comes across as a very unexpected decision! Does it look like all White has been doing on the kingside has been nothing but prophylaxis? }
16... cxb4
{ Black is about to play ...a6-a5 and keep an extra protected passed pawn. }
17. a5 { White needs to prevent that. } 17... f5
{ But now Black is ready to strike back on the f-file, at last! } 18. gxf5 gxf5
19. exf5 Bh4
{ The goal of this move is to, of course, eliminate the defender of the f5-pawn and take it back. }
20. Ne4
{ 20.Nxh4  Qxh4  doesn't help either. After ...Ne7, the f5-pawn will fall no matter what. }
20... Nxf5
{ Black is clearly much better, as the white king on e2 is now a huge liability. }
21. Rag1 Nf6 22. Bb6 Qe8
{ This sacrifice appears to be certainly both unexpected and unnecessary.   22...Qe7  23.Nxh4  Nxh4  24.Nxf6  Qxf6-+  leads to a winning position without sacrifices. }
23. Nxh4 Nxh4 24. Nxd6 Qh5+ 25. Kf1 Rg8
{ The threat is to trade the rooks, and either distract the white rook to win the h3-pawn, or to drag the king on g1 and checkmate it with ...Qg5+. }
26. Be2 Rxg1+ 27. Rxg1 Bxh3+ 28. Ke1
{ However, for now, White is clearly surviving. That's why I am still confused about why Black sacrificed a pawn on d6! }
28... Bg4 29. Rxg4
{ 29.Bxg4  Nxg4  30.Qe4!  would have not only helped White defend but also given him a better position! For instance, after  30...Rg8  31.Bd8!!  ,  with threats like Bxh4 followed by Nf7+, or Nf5, as well as Rxg4 followed by an annoying check to f6, Black is very uncomfortable! }
29... Nxg4 30. Qe4 Rg8
{ Black is pinned, and White has plenty of counterplay. For example, if I were him, I would immediately think of just running the c-pawn up the board! }
31. Bc7
{ At the end of this tragic game, White makes a suspicious move that allows the opponent to rapidly unpin everything.   31.c5  looks like a much more natural move. After some fun analysis, I have found the following logical way to end the game:  31...b3  ,  Black tries to distract the opponent with his passed pawn.  32.Kd2  Ng2!  The knight wants to jump to f4 and harass the annoying bishop.  33.Qxg2  Qh6+!  34.Kc3  Qc1+  35.Kxb3  Qb1+  36.Kc3  Qc1+  with a perpetual check. }
31... Rg7 32. Bd8 b3
{ Now, White is no longer able to stop the pawn with the king, since 33.Kd2?? blunders a piece to 33... Qh6+. }
33. Kd2 Qh6+ 34. Kc3 Qxd6 { The bishop on d8 is also hanging! } 35. Bxh4 Qa3
{ The pawn is unstoppable. } 36. Bd3 b2+ 37. Kd2 Qxa5+ 38. Ke2 Qb6 39. Qf5 Qg6
{ The queen returned home. Black is material up, the white king is weak, ...e5-e4 is knocking at the door... the game is ending! }
40. Qf8+ Rg8 41. Qb4 Qh5 42. Bg3 Nxf2+ 43. Kxf2 Qg5
{ And White resigned since he is getting checkmated. This was certainly a very messy game!  What can we learn from it, besides just enjoying a complicated battle between two chess giants? My primary takeaway would be that playing h2-h3 and g2-g4 is mostly a plan White should use to restrict the ...f7-f5 break, not attack the opponent.  However, as you could see, playing this way resulted in tons of uncertainty with the future of the white king! It was not safe to castle either kingside or queenside, and having the king in the center turned out a burden too. }
