[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sidelines − Model Games"]
[Black "Peter Bombek − Mario Kriz, Trenčín 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5 2. dxc5
{ As we have discussed in the theoretical chapter, this move is by no means dangerous. However, it leads to positions that remind of the Sicilian, or some other 1.e4 situations much more than of the Benoni, so it's important that we analyze them. }
2... e6 3. Nc3 Bxc5 4. Ne4
{ White is immediately going after the bishop pair. It looks weird and unnatural to move the knight several times this early in the opening, but the hole on d6 justifies doing that. }
4... Nf6 { Black is happy to give up the bishop pair for quick development. }
5. Nxc5 Qa5+ { Of course, we didn't just blunder a piece! } 6. c3 Qxc5 7. Nf3
d5
{ Now, White has the bishop pair. But it's not easy for him to comfortably finish development! Playing e2-e3 locks in the dark-squared bishop and doesn't look particularly attractive, while developing the bishop takes more time, and exposes it to ideas like ...f7-f6 and ...e6-e5. }
8. Qb3 O-O 9. Be3
{ White decides to get the bishop out. But where is it going? It looks really clumsy... }
9... Qd6 10. g3 Ng4 { Of course, the bishop immediately gets harassed. } 11.
Bd2 { 11.Bd4  e5!  is even clumsier. } 11... Qc5
{ Now White has to weaken his position @@StartBracket@@the light squares, in particular!@@EndBracket@@ even more! }
12. e3 Nc6 13. Be2 e5 { Of course, Black is glad to occupy the entire center! }
14. O-O e4
{ Why gift White an outpost on d4? Because we will gain one on e5, alongside additional space! }
15. Nd4 Nge5
{ Now, White's kingside is very loose. Next, we can try to go ...Bh3, ...Qd6-h6, and set up a decisive kingside attack if possible. }
16. Rac1 Nc4
{ In my opinion, this move is wrong. It doesn't cause Black any problems, but he had all the reasons to attack on the kingside, so why drive the pieces away from that part of the board?   16...Bh3!  17.Rfd1  Qd6!  looks even better. The light squares are so weak! }
17. Qc2 N6e5 18. b3 Nd6 19. c4
{ White creates a weak pawn, but at least, Black will be busy winning the pawn rather than checkmating White! }
19... dxc4 20. bxc4 Bg4
{ This, at last, is a great decision. The light squares around the king are very weak, and White has the bishop pair! Thus, trading off the light-squared bishops makes perfect sense. }
21. Nb3 Qc8
{ If White isn't careful, the kingside situation might become extremely dangerous in no time. With ...Bf3 and ...Qh3 coming, White is clearly in a very tricky situation! }
22. Bc3 Bf3 { Checkmate in two moves is knocking at the door! } 23. Rfd1
{ White can stop the mate but not material losses. } 23... Qh3 24. Bf1 Bxd1
{ Black wins an exchange, and with it, the game. } 25. Bxe5 Bxc2
{ Now all the pieces are coming off the board by force, which is, of course, great for Black, who is material up. }
26. Bxh3 Nxc4 27. Bd4 Bxb3 28. axb3 Nd2
{ The pawn is under attack, and the fork on f3 would be rather unpleasant too! }
29. Bc5 Nxb3
{ White finally resigned since he is an exchange down, and the queenside pawns will easily queen.  As you can see, the main takeaway from this game is that White went for an extremely clumsy setup and didn't have much of a chance later either.  Black should have been more aggressive on the kingside right away, but even without attacking there rapidly, he still did great. }
