[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sidelines − Model Games"]
[Black "Lucio Rosario Ragonese − Stefan Djuric, Letojanni 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3
{ This time, White chooses one of the most solid setups possible. He might be potentially interested in capturing the pawn on c5 and trying to hold on to it! }
3... Qc7
{ As you know from the theoretical chapter, I like this move a lot. Black keeps the tension, protecting the pawn and keeping a flexible position. Next, depending on what White does, he could choose to go ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, making the kingside extra safe, or ...e7-e6 and ...d7-d5. And, of course, the beauty of this move order is that it prevents any London-related setups!   3...cxd4  4.cxd4  d5  transposes into the Exchange Slav and it would be the most solid way to play. However, of course, doing so is neither exciting nor natural for a Benoni player. }
4. Bg5 Ne4
{ Unfortunately for White, it is not very easy to find a great position for the bishop! }
5. Bh4 cxd4 6. Qxd4
{ This odd-looking move is the most popular one. White is immediately disturbing the knight!   6.cxd4  is possible too, but it doesn't cause Black any problems. For example, after  6...Qa5+  7.Nbd2  Nc6  ,  the white bishop on h4 is clearly misplaced, and White is already running into some threats! }
6... f5
{ Black could also retreat, but it is very ambitious and justified to just keep the knight in the center. Next, Black is hoping to occupy the entire center with ...Nc6, ...d7-d5, and ...e7-e5! }
7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. Qa4
{ 8.Qd3  would be the better way to go. From here, White's queen would be able to prevent ...d7-d5!  8...Nxd2  and next, Black will finish development with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. The position is absolutely reasonable, of course, but White can try to push e2-e4 and at least be somewhat aggressive! ½-½ Bulic-Podobnik, Croatia 2015. }
8... d5 { Of course, the wonderful e4-knight is not going anywhere! } 9. e3 Nc5
{ Black could have also just kept taking more space  9...e5  . My understanding is that he didn't feel like doing so due to the potential changes in the pawn structure after  10.Nxe4  ,  however, after  10...fxe4  11.Nd2  Be7  ,  I really like Black's chances!  The doubled pawns are by no means weak. They greatly restrict White's pieces, and on top of that, Black enjoys the semi-open f-file! The f2-pawn can easily become a target. I certainly would not want to be White here! }
10. Qc2 e5
{ Black is clearly already taking over − look at that gorgeous center! } 11.
Bb5 a6
{ Black immediately tries to get the bishop pair too. Of course, it's not a bad decision, but I think he could have gotten even more out of the position by simply continuing to develop the pieces.   11...Bd6  ,  I see no need to harass the white bishop. Why did it go to b5, after all? Did it go there to trade off the knight? Let him do it then! }
12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. O-O Bd6
{ Look at this center! What did White achieve out of the opening, exactly? And on top of that, look at that bishop on h4, it is so misplaced! Black can even try to trap it with ...h7-h6 and ...g7-g5 at some point! }
14. Bg3 O-O 15. c4 { White is trying to get at least some counterplay. } 15...
f4 { Time to start creating threats. } 16. exf4 Bf5
{ Before capturing the pawn, Black develops another piece and gains another tempo! }
17. Qc3 d4
{ Black would still be better after this move, but it's not exactly obvious why he chose to not win the bishop!   17...exf4!  would have been much cleaner. After the forced  18.Bh4  h6  ,  there is no way for White to avoid losing the piece on the next turn to ...g7-g5! }
18. Nxd4
{ White immediately makes a panic-based decision and collapses.   18.Qa3!!  was the amazing opportunity to nearly save the game!  The point is that the knight on c5 is loose, which allows White to magically bail himself out after  18...exf4  19.Bxf4!  Bxf4  20.Qxc5  .  Black is still better thanks to the bishop pair and the powerful passed pawn on the d-file, but he is definitely no longer winning! }
18... exd4 19. Qxd4 Ne6
{ The f4-pawn is falling, and White's position is collapsing in no time. It's not just about the extra piece, but also about the tremendous difference in piece activity! }
20. Qc3 Nxf4
{ Black is threatening a massive fork on e2, so it makes sense for White to trade that knight off. }
21. Bxf4 Bxf4 22. Nf3 Be4
{ The knight is under pressure. Black is threatening to not only eliminate the knight and then win the h2-pawn, but also to ruin White's king shelter. The thing is that after ...Bxf3, taking with the queen would lose it to ...Bxh2! That's why White would have to take with the pawn, which will, of course, leave his king hopelessly weak. }
23. g3 Rf6 { A cute decision. Of course, the bishop isn't really hanging! } 24.
Rae1 { 24.gxf4?  Rg6+  25.Kh1  Qxf4  gets White mated on the next turn. } 24...
Bxf3
{ White resigned. Had White continued, he would have also lost an exchange after  25.Qxf3  Bd2  . As you can see, the game went really wrong for White from the very beginning: he found himself in a passive position without center and space, and things only got worse from there! }
