[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sidelines − Model Games"]
[Black "Eric Lutz − Christophe Sochacki, Belfort 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ This game saw a slightly unusual for us move order in the opening, but soon transposed to our theoretical lines. }
2. c3 c5 3. dxc5 { White takes the pawn and... } 3... e6 4. b4
{ White ambitiously tries to hold on to it! It's really valuable for us to look at this game because although you cannot really hold on to the pawn, it's worth knowing why exactly. If you play carelessly as Black, you can find yourself in a lost position where you are simply a pawn down for no reason! }
4... a5
{ It is very important to immediately start breaking up the pawn chain! } 5.
Qa4
{ White takes a bit of a desperate step − he tries to block the move ...axb4, even at a cost of placing his queen in such an ugly spot.   But what if White protects the pawns with  5.a3?  Make sure to learn the following idea:  5...axb4  ,  of course, White has to take with the c-pawn in order to not hang his rook.  6.cxb4  b6!  The goal is, obviously, to win back the c5-pawn.  7.cxb6  ,  but wait, can't White just capture on b6 and stay a pawn up?  7...Bxb4+!  Nope! The a-pawn is pinned, that's how Black gets the material back! After  8.Bd2  Bxd2+  9.Nxd2  Qxb6  ,  Black got the pawn back and is much better. Why is that the case? Because he has an extra pawn in the center, but the white a-pawn is weak! }
5... Na6
{ The pawns are a bit stuck. White's queen on a4 can't ever move away − remember that! }
6. Bb2 b6 7. Nd2
{ 7.cxb6  axb4  forces White's structure to collapse, of course. } 7... Bb7
{ Now, the a8-rook is finally protected, which means Black is ready to expose the loose a4-queen by ...axb4, ...Nxc5, etc!   7...bxc5?  would not be a good move, actually! That's because it allows White to build quite a lovely structure by playing  8.b5!  Nb8  9.c4!  and Black is quite passive and restricted! }
8. Qb5 axb4 9. cxb4 Bc6 { The poor queen is moving so often! } 10. Qc4 bxc5 11.
bxc5 { 11.b5?  d5  12.Qb3  c4!  and White loses the b-pawn for nothing. } 11...
Nxc5
{ Now, Black has an extra pawn in the center, while the opponent's a-pawn is a clear weakness. And, even more importantly, all of Black's pieces are so much more active! Why did White waste three moves shuffling his queen around, for example?! }
12. e3 Rb8
{ A pretty logical and creative move − Black is immediately trying to harass the opponent!   12...Na4  looks like a very tempting move to me. The point is that the bishop needs to go either back to c1, which of course looks silly, or to d4, where it seems rather vulnerable.  13.Bd4  Qa5!?  With ...Ne4 coming next, as well as ...e6-e5 and ...d7-d5, and the f1-bishop stuck due to the g2-pawn being under pressure, White is clearly in a lot of trouble! Let's see how he could easily get destroyed in no time.  14.Ngf3  Bxf3!  15.gxf3  e5  and all of a sudden, the bishop gets trapped! }
13. Be5 Rb4 { A cute move! Of course, the rook is not hanging. } 14. Qc1
{ Find a way for Black to win!  14.Qxb4??  Nd3+  wins us the queen. } 14...
Bxg2
{ The bishop is untouchable due to the massive fork on d3, so White loses the rook and the game. }
15. Bd4 Bxh1 16. Bxc5 Bxc5 17. Qxc5 Rg4
{ Black went to win very easily. As you can see, trying to hold on to the pawn can be a very tempting strategy, understandably so. However, it's the wrong one!  If White is desperately clinging on to that c5-pawn, typically, his queenside just falls apart, which is exactly what we saw happen in this lovely miniature. Make sure to know how to punish this type of play! }
