[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sidelines − Model Games"]
[Black "Ernesto Inarkiev − Daniil Dubov, Satka 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ This game saw a more traditional Modern Benoni move order, but we typically get here a bit differently.   1...c5  2.e3  Nf6  3.Nf3  g6  4.d5  is how we could expect to land here. As a result of White at first, playing timidly and then changing his mind, we are getting a typical Benoni position where using our standard ...Be7-g5 plan is no longer possible. However, White is a tempo down compared to the regular Benoni! }
2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 c5 6. d5
{ In the game, White got to this positional in a more regular way. It seems a bit weird to play e2-e3 and then e3-e4 a move later, but this move order does have some merits. More specifically, White usually plays this way to avoid playing Nc3, which allows him to play an interesting sideline against the Grünfeld.  Since the Grünfeld is a very popular weapon at the top level, many White players started using this move order, and the Swedish GM Axel Smith even wrote a book with a chapter The Poor Man's Benoni. Sure enough, White is not in trouble by any means, but I do not think we need to be too concerned when our opponent is a tempo down this early! }
6... e6 7. Nc3 exd5 8. cxd5 d6 9. O-O
{ We are in a regular Benoni position! You might end up in similar ones every now and then, so it would be beneficial to learn about some of the plans and ideas.  We got a rather imbalanced pawn structure. Ideas:  White has an extra pawn in the center, therefore a typical plan could be related to advancing the e-pawn. That could be done by: e4-e5, creating a passed pawn on the d-file; e3-e4, f2-f4, and then e4-e5, hoping to take with the f-pawn and get a powerful central pair. White can put pressure on the d6-pawn with e3-e4, Bf4, and Nd2-c4.  
Black, on the other hand, should:  Try to push ...b7-b5 to grab space on the queenside, where he has an extra pawn. Trade pieces by going ...Bg4 followed by ...Bxf3. Sometimes go ...c5-c4 and ...Nc5 if possible. It's very important for Black to not thoughtlessly play ...a7-a6 because after White responds with a2-a4, Black will no longer have an option of going ...Na6-c7.  
We talked about the importance of this idea in the chapter on typical plans and structures. To my mind, the ideal setup for Black in this position involves going ...Na6-c7, then ...Bg4, exchanging on f3, and ...Nf6-d7. This way Black can prepare ...b7-b5, open up the g7-bishop, and if needed, jump to e5 with the knight. That would help shield the d6-pawn from Bf4 ideas, for instance. }
9... Bg4 { Black follows the aforementioned plan. } 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3
{ Here, two setups look very attractive to me. } 11... Nbd7
{ This is certainly a logical move. However, my first preference is a slightly different way of playing.  11...Na6  is the move I like best. Why would the knight go here? A few reasons: it can come to c7 to support the ...b7-b5 break, the other knight can go to d7, and then maybe jump to e5, and once the other knight goes to d7, the g7-bishop is ready to shine! }
12. Qc2 a6
{ Black is trying to push ...b7-b5, which is something the opponent cannot allow, of course. }
13. a4 c4
{ With ...Rc8 and ...Nc5 coming next, Black seems very comfortable. He will try to jump into d3 or b3 with his knight, and then go ...Nf6-d7-c5/e5, activating the other knight as well as the bishop on g7. White, on the other hand, doesn't seem to have that much play available! }
14. Be2 Rc8
{ Black just protects the pawn. If White doesn't play e3-e4, the plan could be to go ...Rc5 and attack the d5-pawn! But if White does, it would be very tempting to go ...Nc5, ...Nfd7-e5, and jump with the knight to d3! }
15. a5
{ White makes this move to prevent Black from using the b6-square and to cancel the ...b7-b5 idea forever, but now the a5-pawn becomes a bit vulnerable. }
15... Rc5 16. Qa4 Re8
{ With this move, Black prevents e3-e4. The c4-pawn is not really under attack. }
17. Rd1
{ 17.Bxc4?  b5!  18.axb6  Nxb6  wins the c4-bishop. Quite a cute tactical idea, isn't it? }
17... Ne4
{ 17...Re5!  This somewhat unexpected move looks very strong to me since there is no clear and easy way to protect  the d5-pawn! The only move seems to be  18.Bf3  but now, Black has another promising idea.  18...Rf5!  What is the idea? Of course to sacrifice an exchange!  19.Bd2?  Rxf3!  20.gxf3  Ne5!  21.f4  Nd3  .  The knight on d3 is a monster and the white king is really weak! With ideas like ...Qc8 followed by ...Qxh3 knocking at the door and the d5-pawn likely falling on the next move, Black is clearly much better. }
18. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ Black opened up the g7-bishop, and he must have been thinking it would be impossible for White to develop his queenside. Unfortunately, that doesn't turn out to be correct. }
19. Bd2 f5
{ 19...Bxb2?  20.Rab1  and the problem is that Black cannot play ...c4-c3, which under other circumstances would have been a terrific move, as that would hang the rook on e4! }
20. Qa3
{ White wants to play Bb4 and win the d6-pawn! Now, the position is somewhat awkward! }
20... Rb5 21. Rab1
{ 21.Bb4  Nc5!  would keep the pawn safe and threaten ideas  like ...Rxb4 followed up with ...c4-c3.  22.Bf1  − if White made some random move, Black would have several cool ideas, including  22...Rxb4!?  23.Qxb4  c3  ,  the queen is hanging, so Black gets enough time to win the b-pawn.  24.Qa3?   24.Rd4  ,  White must give up an exchange to avoid a fantastic queen-trapping scenario.  24...cxb2  25.Rb1  Bxd4  26.exd4  ,  the knight cannot retreat since doing so would drop the d6 and b7-pawns. Perhaps, objectively, the position remains balanced.  24...cxb2  25.Rab1  Ra4!  would even accidentally trap the queen! }
21... Rb3
{ Black drops the d6-pawn and deserves to be in a lot of trouble, but fortunately for him, White doesn't dare to take it. }
22. Qa2
{ And just like that − one passive move and Black is taking over!   22.Qxd6!  would have created too many problems. For instance, after  22...Be5  23.Qe6+!  Kf8  ,  the white queen is nearly trapped, so it's understandable that White would feel scared to play this way. However, he has an amazing follow-up.  24.Bxc4!!  Rxc4  25.d6  and Black's rooks are all of a sudden very vulnerable! He would need to give up an exchange.  25...Rbb4  26.Bxb4!  Rxb4  27.Rbc1!  With the rook invading  on c7 and the black pieces this uncoordinated, the position is clearly almost lost! }
22... Nc5 { The knight is looking to jump to d3 very shortly! } 23. f3 c3
{ Look at that! Black is threatening to trap the queen with ...Ra4. } 24. fxe4
{ 24.bxc3!  was the only way to go.  24...Ra4?   24...Rxb1!  25.Qxb1  Re8  and it seems Black is better since all the white pawns are so weak! There are threats like ...Qxa5, ...Bh6, attacking the e3-pawn, and so on. The knight on c5 is gorgeous, while the white bishops are very passive. But, of course, this is not the end of the world.  25.Qxa4  Nxa4  26.Rxb3  gives White a decent position with two rooks for a queen. }
24... cxd2
{ Now White's position is falling apart! Black is about to go ...Qg5, ...Be5, ...Qg3, and just checkmate the opponent! The dark squares are super weak and White's pieces, especially the queen, are so far away and helpless. }
25. Bc4 Qg5 { Black can even ignore the rook! } 26. Bxb3 Qxe3+ 27. Kh1 Nxe4 28.
Rf1 Be5
{ With ...Ng3+ and a forced checkmate being inevitable, a 2700-level GM admitted his defeat in this lovely near-miniature. As you can see, these Benoni positions could get very complicated, and often collapse in no time! Make sure to remember the idea ...c5-c4! followed by ...Nc5-d3/b3! }
