[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sidelines − Model Games"]
[Black "Jouko Kyrola − Aleksei Holmsten, Jyväskylä 2000"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 { 1.d4  c5  2.e4  is how we would typically get to this position. } 1...
c5
{ This game started as a Sicilian, but soon transposed to our @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  c5  2.e4  chapter. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3
{ White plays the Alapin a move later than usual, which, of course, is the same thing in this move order. }
3... e5 4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 exd4 { And we finally transpose into our course. }
6. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Black has an isolated pawn, which might make it seem as though we are worse. However, we have a lot of pressure on the center and want to play ...d7-d5 very shortly, liquidating the center. }
7. Nxc6
{ 7.Nc3  ,  typically, White would protect the e4-pawn, keeping the tension. However, after  7...Bb4  ,  there is a lot of pressure on the e4-pawn, so White is more or less forced to take on c6 anyway. }
7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The e4-pawn is hanging, and we had not yet committed to playing ...Bb4. Since the g1-a7 diagonal is open and useful, we could potentially do even better!  It seems very logical and safe to hide the black king on e7 after developing the bishop to c5 first. Then, we will proceed with such simple and logical moves as ...Be6, ...Rhd8, and so on. Black has an extra pawn on the queenside, so trading pieces would be beneficial since the extra queenside pawn tends to be more valuable in the endgame. }
9. Bg5 h6
{ Now, White will need to either hang a pawn or give up the bishop pair! } 10.
Bxf6+ gxf6
{ Black has a wonderful pair of bishops. The dark-squared bishop is unopposed and will be very powerful on c5, for example. The goal is to play ...Bc5, ...Ke7, ...Be6, dominate the d-file, and eventually start advancing the queenside pawns. And, of course, Black can always undouble the pawns with ...f6-f5! }
11. Nc3 Kc7
{ The king is perfectly safe and comfortable here. And, of course, it will greatly help Black when it comes to advancing the queenside pawns! For example, now Black might consider going ...b7-b5 to restrict the white bishop from coming to c4, and potentially expand further with ...a7-a5, ...a5-a4, etc. }
12. O-O-O Bc5
{ Black is also winning time while developing his pieces to the most natural squares! }
13. Rd2 Be6 14. Bd3 a5
{ 14...b5  seems like the most natural move to me. Black takes the c4 and a4-squares under control, preventing ideas like Na4. Next, he can play ...a7-a5-a4 and ...b5-b4, looking to win the a2-pawn after kicking the knight out! }
15. a4
{ It is understandable that White wants to prevent the opponent from grabbing more space on the queenside, but now the a4-pawn and the b4-square become new weaknesses! }
15... Rad8 16. Kc2 Rd4
{ Black entirely dominates the dark squares. The knight cannot move away, as the a4-pawn would be lost. }
17. b3 Rhd8
{ Black is threatening to win a pawn by capturing ...Bxb3+, distracting White from the d3-bishop! }
18. Rhd1 Kb6 19. Ne2 Rb4 { The b3-pawn is also a target! } 20. Nc1 Kc7
{ Black is in no hurry whatsoever. Next, he can always consider pushing ...b7-b5, starting to make progress on the queenside. }
21. Re1 Rb6
{ A very creative idea. The goal is to open up the a3-f8 diagonal and make possible the move ...Ba3, which would threaten to eliminate the knight and attack the b3-pawn. }
22. Rf1 Ba3 { The b3-pawn is in trouble! } 23. Bc4
{ Now I want you to find how Black wins by force. } 23... Bxc4 24. bxc4
{ 24.Rxd8  Bxf1  also wins Black a piece. } 24... Rb2+
{ White resigned, as he loses a rook. As you can see, the position after he gave up the bishop pair on f6 became extremely difficult immediately! }
